@endnode

@node unic "[unic]    What is Unicode?"
@{b}What is Unicode?@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
The "Unicode" standard is a method of encoding the characters used in all
the world's written languages, as well as punctuation and other letter-like
characters.

Unicode is the product of the Unicode Consortium, a body entrusted with
the production of the Unicode standard, under the W3 (world wide web)
consortium.

My implementation is (so far) a partial implementation of Version 3.0 of
the Unicode standard. The Unicode standard has been adopted by the ISO
(International Standards Organisation) as ISO 10646.

Details of the standard are to be found in the book, "The Unicode Standard
Version 3.0", by the Unicode Consortium, ISBN 0201616335. You can buy it
online from www.unicode.com


@{b}Unicode Online@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
For official information on Unicode, see  www.unicode.com, the official
website of the Unicode Consortium. The site is well worth a visit or three.


@{b}The Scope of Unicode@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
As of Version 3.0, Unicode consists of 65536 16-bit values from 0000 to
FFFF (in hex). Not all values in this range are defined, but those that
are defined each correspond to a character, e.g.:

     0041  is    LATIN CAPITAL LETTER A
     0394  is    GREEK CAPITAL LETTER DELTA
     201C  is    LEFT DOUBLE QUOTATION MARK

Unicode also has rules for adding diacritical marks (like acute, grave &c)
to letters, and rules for direction (e.g. English is written left to right,
but Hebrew is written right to left).

Unicode defines the letters, but not particular glyphs. Thus, for example,
0041 is defined as "LATIN CAPITAL LETTER A", but that letter may be in many
different shapes and sizes. The Unicode Book gives a typical glyph to
represent each character. A particular glyph may occur more than once, but
Unicodes are defined by their semantics (meaning), so for example the Greek
letter phi may appear in several Unicodes, as just a letter, or as a
mathematical symbol, etc.


@{b}Relationship with ASCII@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
The first 128 Unicode characters correspond with ASCII values $00 to $7F.
The next 128 correspond with the @{i}de facto@{ui} default character set
for the internet, i.e. ISO 8859 Set 1 (Latin-1), which is the same as the
characters $80 to $FF in normal Amiga fonts, such as Times.font, &c.
Amiga got it right!


@{b}The Use of Unicode@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Unicode is the required character set for The Internet HTML standard Version
4, and for cascading style sheets CSS2. Also, Unicode is the character
set for JAVA. Increasingly, computer word processors are adopting it, e.g.
WORD for windows on the PC recognises Unicode (sort of).

This implementation for the Amiga is a step towards making JAVA, CSS2 and a
full HTML4 available on the Amiga.


@{b}Requirements to Implement Unicode@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
A thorough Unicode implementation has the following characteristics:

1. It will allow representation of Unicode characters in different sizes, in
   accordance with CSS2.

2. It will allow incorporation of fonts for particular scripts into it, so
   Unicode glyphs will be represented in the same style as other glyphs with
   common glyph elements and a semantic relationship.

Ideally, Unicode would be extremely flexible for high quality printing to
the screen, or to paper, in any style at all, with characters in any shape
or size, stretched intelligently any which way, with all possible degrees
of boldness, italics, &c as per the CSS2 standard. My implementation is less
than this utopian standard of perfection, but at least approaches it in some
respects.
@endnode

@node inst "[inst]   Installing Ucode"
@{b}Installing Ucode@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Ucode comes with an install script, in the usual way.

For the cogniscenti, here is what the install script does:

   1. Copies the Ucode drawer and its contents to the chosen destination
   2. Adds an assign of UCODE: to the Ucode drawer in S:User-startup

@endnode

@node plan "[plan]    Plans for the Future"
@{b}Plans for the Future@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Here are the things to be done in the near (or far) future, in order of
priority:

1. Make a text editor for UTF-8 / UTF-16 text

   I have this well under way. I will use ad-hoc keyboard layouts, and the
   ability to add/edit/load/save new keyboard layouts. Can anyone point me
   to web sites giving traditional keymaps for various languages?

2. Make my Unicode implementation able to work with "surrogate" characters,
   and higher bitplanes.

   This is nearly complete. Nearly all ucode.library routines are
   already surrogate- and higher bitplane- capable.

3. Make a "AmigaGuide" viewer that can read UTF-8 and UTF-16

   This is not started, but should be relatively simple.

4. Make C language stubs &c for ucode.library

   I'm not sure I can do this. It wouldn't be too hard for someone who knew
   what they are doing. Can anyone do this for me?

5. Make a unicode-aware text-only HTML viewer for the Amiga.

   i.e. a HTML text-only viewer that understands all heritage character
   encodings such as Shift-JIS, Latin-2, &c, as well as UTF-8 and UTF-16.
   This is not started, but will be quite simple, as the basic capabilites
   needed for this are already implemented in ucode.library

6. Make more glyphs.

   I have many glyphs already done in many sizes &c for various ranges of
   unicodes. I will release these progressively.

7. Extend the capabilites of UcodeSlave.

8. Do a CSS2 implementation.

   I would love to get stuck into this. But only after the above things are
   already done. CSS2 is very hard to program, and needs to be written
   along with a complete HTML4 viewer, as CSS2 can't just be "plugged in"
   to a HTML4 viewer, but must be completely integrated with it.
@endnode

@node myun "[myun]    My Unicode Implementation"
@{b}My Unicode Implementation@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

@{b}The Author....@{ub}

My name is Ken Shillito. I live in Corio, Victoria, Australia. I am a priest
of the Anglican Church of Australia, and my hobby is (obviously) Amiga
programming. I will support the Amiga (and the Anglican Church for that
matter) as long as I breathe. There won't be "denominations" in heaven -
will there be Amigas?

My primary computer skills are in 68K assembly language and mathematics. I
can read ancient Hebrew and Greek, and can understand and read French but
not write or speak it well. I have smatterings of German, Italian, Greek,
Spanish, Arabic and Latin. I have also read extensively in linguistics.

However, to be frank, I have found my lack of knowledge of particular
languages to be something of a handicap in this project. So, for example,
while I am very proud of the complete and comprehensive implementation of
Arabic and Hebrew in this implementation, the implemenation of Devanagari,
while usable, is rather crude. I will be doing research to progressively
improve my knowledge of various writing systems.


@{b}Open Source...@{ub}

If you want a copy of the source code (in 68K assembler) for ucode.library
and/or UcodeSlave, let me know by email and I will send it to you.


@{b}The Implementation...@{ub}

My Unicode implementation consists of a library:

  @{b}ucode.library@{ub}

and an expandable set of data files in a directory:

  @{b}UCODE:U0000@{ub}.

And these programs:

  @{"UcodeFix" link ufix}

       (analogous to Amiga's FixFonts) which you must run if you
       add or subtract files from UCODE:U0000.

  @{"UcodeSlave" link slav}

       to which you can send ARexx commands, to implement all the
       features of ucode.library in your ARexx scripts.

  @{"GlyphViewer" link ucod}

       for viewing Ucode's glyph files.

  @{"SampleStrings" link samp}

       for demonstrating some of ucode.library's capabilities

  @{"Font Maker" link how1}

       for making any arbitrary selection of Ucode glyphs into an Amiga
       bitmapped font.


@{b}Note:@{ub} As well as UCODE:U0000, there will potentially be other subdirectories
of Ucode, i.e. UCODE:U0001 to UCODE:UFFFF for extensions to Unicode.
@endnode

@node ufix "[ufix]   The UcodeFix Program"
@{b}The UcodeFix Program@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
If you delete any files from the UCODE:U0000 directory, or add any new files
to it, you must at some time run the UcodeFix program. You will see its
icon in the main Ucode drawer.

UcodeFix makes &/or updates a file "UCODE:U0000/List", which contains the
details of all files in UCODE:U0000, sorted in the way that ucode.library
likes them.

If UCODE:U0000/List has out-of-date contents, not all routines in
ucode.library will work properly.

UcodeFix is analogous to Amiga's "FixFonts" program. As FixFonts is to the
FONTS: directory, so is UcodeFix to the UCODE: directory.
@endnode

@node ucod "[ucod]    The GlyphViewer Program"
@{b}The GlyphViewer Program@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
If you click Ucode's @{b}GlyphViewer@{ub} icon, you will run Ucode's Glyph
Viewer program.

The program begins by loading into memory a file of 1024 glyphs. You can
view these by working the window's scroller. If you leave the mouse pointer
on a glyph for a while, its unicode value will pop up nearby.

You can view other files of 1024 glyphs by clicking either of the buttons:

 "Goto"   } For loading other sets
 "Load"   } of 1024 glyphs.

Big areas of some glyph files may be blank, as not all potential unicode
values are allocated, and some (e.g. 0000 - 0020) do not have glyphs.


@{b}Glyph Attributes@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
The glyphs you view have a set of 4 qualities called "attributes", as
follows:


@{b}Nominal Size@{ub}

Glyphs can have nominal sizes from 5 to 31.

A nominal size consists of an "ascender", i.e. the part above the baseline,
and a "descender", i.e. the part below the baseline. e.g. for nominal size
11 the ascender is 8, and the descender is 3. The glyph may also have a few
extra lines above the nominal height for "diacritical marks" such as acute
or grave. e.g. for nominal size 11 there can be up to 3 such extra lines,
making a total "actual height" of 14.


@{b}Width Descriptor@{ub}

Glyphs come in 9 different widths, represented by numbers 0 to 8, or
2-letter descriptors as follows:

    0 UC ultra-condensed                    5 SE semi-expanded
    1 EC extra-condensed     4 NM normal    6 EX expanded
    2 CD condensed                          7 EE extra-expanded
    3 SC semi-condensed                     8 UE ultra-expanded


@{b}Weight Descriptor@{ub}

Glyphs come in 9 different weights, represented by numbers 1 to 9. 1 is
lightest, 9 is heaviest. 4 is "normal", 7 is "bold".


@{b}Style Descriptor@{ub}

Glyphs come in 5 styles, represented by 2-letter descriptors as follows:

    SS sans serif
    WS with serif
    SC script ("italic")
    FA fantasy
    TT fixed width ("teletype")

                                _oOo_

When Glyph Viewer starts up, it shows glyphs with attributes:

    nominal height     11
    width descriptor    4 = NM normal
    weight descriptor   1 = lightest
    style descriptor   SS = sans serif


@{b}The 'Goto' Button@{ub}

If you click GlyphViewer's "Goto" button, you will see a set of 1 or more
unicode values, being a list of all files with the same attributes as the
file currently loaded. Each file has 1024 bytes. There can be up to 64 files
in the list, as follows:


  0000 0400 0800 0C00 1000   .......   EC00 F000 F400 F800 FC00


Actually, D800 and DC00 are illegal values, though you may see a file
labelled DC00, whose glyphs are not unicodes, but dummy glyphs used for
ucode.library's internal purposes. There is never a file labelled D800.
There will also never be files for E000, E400, E800, EC00, F000 or F400,
as E000 - F8FF are reseved for private use.


@{b}The 'Load' Button@{ub}

If you click Glyph Viewer's "Load" button, you can choose from all the
glyph files.

The "Page" button currently does nothing, but will when implememented
allow you to choose unicodes outside the range 0000 - FFFF.

The "Size" button allows you to choose files with nominal size from 5 to 31.

When you see the file you want, click it, and Ucode will load and display
that file.

@endnode

@node samp   "[samp]   The SampleStrings Program"
@{b}The SampleStrings Program@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
If you click the @{b}SampleStrings@{ub} icon in the Ucode drawer, you will run the
"SampleStrings" program.

A window will come up showing a range of possible choices, to put
ucode.library through its paces.

The Unicode standard is not just a set of characters, but also a set of
rules for sorting & printing strings of Unicodes. ucode.library can accept
string inputs in the form of "ASCII" in many heritage encodings, such as
Shift-JIS, Latin-2, etc., along with HTML4-style &...; things, embedded
Esc sequences, etc. It can also accept input in UTF8 or UTF16 encodings.

The various samples are demonstrations of the following capabilites of
ucode.library:

  - composing characters with *many* different ways for diacritical marks
    to join onto their supporing character, and possibly more than one
    diacritical mark piling onto the same character.

  - many different forms of punctuation and spacing.

  - the very complex & confusing "unicode-bidi" rule for bi-directionality
    (e.g. Hebrew, Arabic are right to left, while Latin is left to right)
    with embedded strings running the other way, mirrored punctuation marks,
    etc.

  - the special requirements of scripts. e.g. Arabic has terminal & medial
    forms, Indic scripts join each other.

  - some features to enhance quality, such as left/right/full justify,
    centering, small caps, automatic kerning, &c.

The sample strings are just a beginning of the complexity and sophistication
of ucode.library's abilities.

@endnode

@node how1 "[how1]    The FontMaker Program"
@{b}The FontMaker Program@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
If you click the @{b}FontMaker@{ub} icon in the Ucode drawer, you will
load the "FontMaker" program.

FontMaker allows you to make any arbitrary set of unicode glyphs into an
Amiga font.

I should now explain that normally, Amiga fonts contain 189 glyphs, i.e.

  ASCII   values  $21 to $7E     } Together, these make up the internet
  Extra   values  $A1 to $FF     } @{i}de facto@{ui} default character set, Latin-1

When Font Maker starts, the window will contain a set of 256 buttons, each
standing for one of the font characters from $00 to $FF. You can change any
of these to hold any Unicode value from 0000 to FFFF. If the Unicode of
that value has a glyph, then it will be "mapped" into the font. Initially,
the boxes will contain the default Latin-1 values.

There are also buttons at the top as follows:

Help    - click for assistance

Default - click to change all buttons back to Latin-1

Range   - click to set a range of buttons to consecutive unicode values.
          (all buttons in the range must be visible on the window)

          Here is what you do:

          1. Edit the first button in the range to hold the first unicode
             value

          2. Click range

          3. Click the first button in the range. All buttons before it will
             disappear.

          4. Click the last button in the range.

          All buttons will then re-appear, and the range will be filled with
          consecutive unicodes.

Presets - click this, and a list of presets will appear. All except the last
          affect only ASCII values A1 - FF. The last line pokes values into
          01-1F and 80-9F as per some windows fonts.

Preview - to see what the present values in the buttons would look like if
          made into a font

Attributes - if you click this, FontMaker takes you through a 4-step
          process to set glyph attributes to new values. If UCODE: does
          not have glyphs with the attributes you set, it will try to resize
          glyphs to meet your requirements. This does not always give
          very pleasing results.

About -   gives details of the version and author of the FontMaker program.

Font -    makes the font. First, FontMaker asks for the name of the font.
          Then, it tells you what the font files created will be (the actual
          height is more than the nominal height. Latin-1 upper case letters
          will equal the nominal height, and only characters with diacritical
          marks, or outsize glyphs, will exceed the nominal height). There
          will then be a pause as FontMaker makes the font. Finally,
          FontMaker uses graphics.library's Text routine to show the text.
          If they fit, all "ASCII" values from 21 to FF are displayed.

@endnode

@node edit "[edit]   The GlyphEditor Program"
@{b}The GlyphEditor Program@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
If you click the @{b}GlyphEditor@{ub} icon, you will see the GlyphEditor
program.

You should consider glyph editing to be advanced usage - you should do a
backup of all the glyph files before you tinker with them.

The interface with GlyphEditor is especially designed to make glyph editing
quick and easy for practiced users. But its user interface is not especially
pleasing for beginners, since it is advanced usage.

GlyphEditor has its own Help built in, so refer there for particulars.

@endnode

@node sett "[sett]   Incorporating Ucode in your Applications"
@{b}Incorporating Ucode in your Applications@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
It is not necessary to include all the files in my Ucode distribution in
the distribution of your application. You may if you wish include only
those files your application wants to use. But, in all cases, you must
include ucode.library.

1. Your distribution must have a directory called UCODE

2. Your program should check to see if UCODE: exists, and if it does, use
   the version of Ucode already installed by the user.

3. If UCODE: does not already exist, then your program should assign
   UCODE: to the Ucode directory in your application. If it does so, then
   when your program exits, it should remove the assign of UCODE:

4. The Ucode directory must have as a minimum the file

       ucode.library

   and the sub-directory

       U0000

   with the file

       U0000/List

   and the directory

       Licenses

   with all its contents.

5. If your program wants to use ARexx scripts, it should include the
   UcodeSlave program in your distribution's Ucode directory.

6. If your program opens ucode.library, it should point A1 to the string:

       DC.B 'UCODE:ucode.library',0

5. If your program has files saved by TLUsavepreview, then there need not
   be any files in U0000 except List, since TLUloadpreview does not need
   any glyph files to load, format and print files saved by TLUsavepreview.

  (The ARexx calls for the above are respectively SPREVIEW, LPREVIEW,
   FORMAT and PRINT).

6. But if your program wants to call TLUpreview, or TLUgrabrport, or
   TLUstring, (PREVIEW, GRAB or STRING), then it must include whatever
   glyph files are needful in the Ucode/U0000 directory.

7. If your program calls TLUcharset (CHARSET), you must include from the
   Ucode/Maps directory whichever of its contents are needful.

If your distribution has glyph files in Ucode/U0000, then you must also
correct the "List" file in U0000, by doing this, before you distribute your
program:

   - temporarily assign UCODE: to your distribution's Ucode directory
   - run the UcodeFix program

UcodeFix will then update List in the Ucode/U0000 directory, to incorporate
all the files it finds in any of the subdirectories U05 to U31 it finds.
@endnode

@node slav "[slav]   The UcodeSlave Program"
@{b}The UcodeSlave Program@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
My Unicode implementation has a program in it called

   "UcodeSlave".

If you run UcodeSlave (e.g. by double-clicking its icon in the "Ucode"
drawer) it will appear to just sit in memory and do nothing. That is because
UcodeSlave does nothing but receive and execute ARexx commands.

So, to actually use UcodeSlave, you must issue commands to it via ARexx
scripts. These nodes have full details of all UcodeSlave's ARexx commands:

 @{"UcodeSlave's ARexx commands - introduction" link atut}
 @{"UcodeSlave's ARexx commands - reference   " link arec}
 @{"UcodeSlave's demonstration scripts        " link arex}

You will be able to do @{b}everything@{ub} that ucode.library can do by
means of sending ARexx commands to UcodeSlave. Programming in ARexx is
much simpler than in C or assembler, so this will make ucode.library more
accessible.

@endnode

@node atut "[atut]    Ucode Slave's ARexx commands - introduction"
@{b}Ucode Slave's ARexx commands - introduction@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
UcodeSlave is simply a program which receives ARexx commands. Its purpose is
to print Unicode to windows.


@{b}UcodeSlave's ARexx Port@{ub}

UcodeSlave uses the ARexx port @{b}UPort@{ub}


@{b}REGISTER and DEREGISTER@{ub}

There can be several scripts using UcodeSlave at the same time. If a script
wants to use UcodeSlave, the first thing it must do is to "register" with
UcodeSlave, by sending a @{"REGISTER" link regi} command. When it does, UcodeSlave sends
it a number, from 1 to 8, which I call in these docs the "uuser" number.
Nearly all UcodeSlave commands require a script to supply a uuser number as
a parameter.

When your script finishes using UcodeSlave, the last thing it does is to
relinquish its uuser number, with the @{"DEREGISTER" link dere} command. UcodeSlave may
then give its uuser number to another script that REGISTERs.

There are, however, two other important calls which a script can make to
UcodeSlave which do @{b}not@{ub} require the uuser number, i.e. QUIT and
UNQUIT.


@{b}QUIT and UNQUIT@{ub}

The @{"QUIT" link quit} command tells UcodeSlave to close down. It will not actually do
so, however, until such times as there are no registered uusers. So, if any
uuser has ever sent a QUIT command, then UcodeSlave will wait until the last
uuser calls @{"DEREGISTER" link dere}, and will then close itself down. If it happens that
there are no registered uusers at the time UcodeSlave receives a QUIT
command, it will close down immediately.

The @{"UNQUIT" link unqu} command has the effect of cancelling a previous @{"QUIT" link quit} command.
If UcodeSlave has received an UNQUIT, it will just sit in memory forever,
even if there are no uusers, until such times as it receives a @{"QUIT" link quit} command.
A QUIT cancels all previous UNQUITs if any; an UNQUIT cancels all previous
QUITs if any.


@{b}Starting up and Closing Down@{ub}

Bearing in mind the above, here is the basic structure of beginning and
ending the use of UcodeSlave:


    [load and] address UPort

         REGISTER

             Issue UcodeSlave commands as required, addressing UPort to
             do so, or other ports to do things with other ARexx ports.

         DEREGISTER

    QUIT


@{b}UcodeSlave's Commands@{ub}

UcodeSlave has many commands. The basic purpose of UcodeSlave is to let you
put unicode onto a window. Generally, applications running ARexx scripts
for UcodeSlave will already have windows open, on which they want to put
Unicode. You will see in the docs in the next node how to "lend" a window
to UcodeSlave so it can get Unicode put on it. I call such windows "borrowed"
or "unowned" windows in UcodeSlave's docs.

Alternately, you can get UcodeSlave to open its own windows, which I call
"owned" windows. Although all my demonstration scripts use owned windows,
this is only because they are @{i}demonstration@{ui} scripts. @{i}Real@{ui} scripts
for real applications would presumably nearly always lend their own windows
to UcodeSlave, rather than ask UcodeSlave to open windows.


@{b}Quo Vadis?@{ub}

The best approach now is to skim the UcodeSlave Reference Section which
follows this node. Then, run each demonstration script in the
UCODE:Arexx_Stuff drawer, and read notes about it in @{"Sample Scripts" link arex}.
@endnode

@node arec "[arec]    UcodeSlave and ARexx - UcodeSlave's ARexx Commands"
@{b}UcodeSlave's ARexx commands - Reference Section@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
UcodeSlave creates an ARexx port named

     UPort

UcodeSlave's commands may be divided into these categories:

     @{"How UcodeSlave works       " link howu}
     @{"Control commands           " link cont}
     @{"Lending a window/rastport  " link lend}
          @{"GUI commands    " link guic}    <----  optional
     @{"Simple Unicode commands    " link ucom}
     @{"Advanced usage of 'USET'   " link adus}
     @{"Advanced Unicode commands  " link adva}
     @{"Catalog management         " link cata}
     @{"Commands for editing glyphs" link ared}

All of UcodeSlave's commands are case-blind. And n.b. only the first 4
characters of them are looked at. So, for example, in the case of the
WINDOW command, the following will be accepted, as you would expect:

     WINDOW
     window
     Window

but also the following, since their first 4 characters are correct:

     windo
     windw
     wind
     windfred

Nevertheless, for readability of your script, I hope you will use only the
correct form of the command, i.e. in the case of WINDOW, either WINDOW,
window, or Window, according to taste, but not wind, windw, etc.

If words are required as parameters for commands (e.g. the word 'RASTPORT'
may appear as a parameter of the WINDOW command) then it too is case blind,
and it too has only the first 4 characters looked at.
@endnode

@node howu "[howu]    How UcodeSlave works"
@{b}How UcodeSlave works@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
UcodeSlave accepts commands through its ARexx port named "UPort".

Nearly all commands require the sender to supply a user number. The main
commands that do @{i}not@{ui} require a user number are:

 @{"QUIT" link quit}      causes UcodeSlave to close down, next time that no users are
           registered (immediately, if none are currently registered).

 @{"UNQUIT" link unqu}    which cancels a previous @{"QUIT" link quit}.

 @{"REGISTER" link regi}  a user sends this to acquire a user number, which must be
           appended to further commands, except for @{"QUIT" link quit}, @{"UNQUIT" link unqu} and a
           few others (i.e. @{"REALLYQUIT" link real}, @{"UTRACE" link utra}, @{"UNUTRACE" link unut}, @{"UERROR" link uerr}).

@{b}In these docs, the number that UcodeSlave supplies to a script that
@{"REGISTER" link regi}s is written "uuser".@{ub}

UcodeSlave maintains a set of resources for each registered user. When a
script @{"DEREGISTER" link dere}s, any of those resources which the uuser has not already
specifically freed are freed automatically.


...@{b}Create and/or ADDRESS UPort@{ub}....

Here is a suitable code fragment for a script to ADDRESS UcodeSlave the
first time:

    /* create and/or address UPort */
    if show('P','UPort') then
      do
        address 'UPort'
        'unquit'
      end
    else
      do
        address command 'run UCODE:UcodeSlave'
        address command 'WaitForPort UPort'
        address 'UPort'
        'unquit'
      end

On subsequent ADDRESSes to UPort you would merely put:

    address 'UPort'


...@{b}Registering and Unregistering@{ub}...

Here is a suitable code fragment to register as a uuser:

    /* register */
    'register'
    uuser = -rc
    if rc = 3 then say "can't register - too many users"
    if rc = 4 then say "can't register - out of memory"
    if rc < 0 then do


Then may follow all the commands the script wants UcodeSlave to do. Finally,
here is a suitable code fragment to deregister and quit:


    /* deregister */
        'deregister' uuser

    end

    /* quit */
    'quit'
@endnode

@node cont  "[cont]   UcodeSlave's Control Commands""
@{b}UcodeSlave's Control Commands@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
UcodeSlave has the following control commands:

@{"QUIT      " link quit}  Causes UcodeSlave to quit next time no users are registered
@{"UNQUIT    " link unqu}  Cancels the effect of QUIT
@{"REALLYQUIT" link real}  Forces all users to be deregistered, & UcodeSlave to quit
@{"UTRACE    " link utra}  Causes UcodeSlave to display a trace window
@{"UNUTRACE  " link unut}  Cancels the effect of UTRACE
@{"REGISTER  " link regi}  Allocates a uuser number
@{"DEREGISTER" link dere}  Frees a uuser number
@{"UERROR    " link erro}  Gets an error report

@endnode

@node quit  "[quit]    ARexx command QUIT"
@{b}QUIT@{ub}
~~~~
Format

     'QUIT'

Normally, UcodeSlave sits in memory forever. If no users are registered, it
uses very little memory.

If a script sends a QUIT command, then next time no users are registered,
which might be immediately, UcodeSlave will close itself down. Any script at
any time can send a QUIT command, and it is not necessary to be registered
to do so.

If UcodeSlave has any system resources still allocated when it closes down,
it will free them.

@endnode

@node unqu  "[unqu]    ARexx Command UNQUIT"
@{b}UNQUIT@{ub}
~~~~~~
Format

     'UNQUIT'

UNQUIT cancels the effect of a previously sent @{"QUIT" link quit} command. If no QUIT
command has been received, then UNQUIT is ignored.

Initially, UcodeSlave is in the UNQUIT state, and it will return to that
state if it happens to be in the QUIT state, whenever it receives an UNQUIT
command. Any script at any time can send an UNQUIT command, and it is not
necessary to be registered to do so.

QUIT and UNQUIT do not nest: any QUIT cancels all previous UNQUITs; any
UNQUIT cancels all previous QUITs.

When an unregistered user first issues the REXX 'ADDRESS UPort' command, it
should immediately issue an UNQUIT command to stop UcodeSlave from closing
down before it has a chance to register.

@endnode

@node real  "[real]    ARexx Command REALLYQUIT"
@{b}REALLYQUIT@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~
Format

     'REALLYQUIT'


REALLYQUIT forces UcodeSlave to immediately unregister all registered
users if any, and then to @{"QUIT" link quit}.

Any script can send a REALLYQUIT command at any time, and need not be
registered to do so.

If any other messages are waiting at UPort when the REALLYQUIT is received,
UcodeSlave will reply to them, setting rc to 15.

REALLYQUIT is only meant to be used in the development stages of a project.
If everything has got muddled up and bogged down, then you can RX a script
like this:


   /* clean up a mess when debugging */
   if show('P','UPort') then do
       ADRESS 'UPort'
       'REALLYQUIT'
   end


which removes everything and makes a clean slate ready for the next try.
but once your project is working ok, it should not use the REALLYQUIT
command. (You will find such a program at path UCODE:Arexx_Stuff/Kill.rexx).

@endnode

@node utra  "[utra]    ARexx Command UTRACE"
@{b}UTRACE@{ub}
~~~~~~
Format

     'UTRACE' [WINDOW / FILE]

UTRACE can optionally be followed by WINDOW or FILE, with WINDOW the
default.

UTRACE causes UcodeSlave to open a little window of its own, which reports
everything that UcodeSlave does. And, if you specify FILE, it will also
open a file T:Utrace to which it appends the same data as to the window.
This can be useful if the lines you want scroll off the window before you
can read them.

UTRACE reports the following:

   1.  All @{"IDCMP" link idcm} commands when they are received
   2.  All IDCMP messages received at any owned windows
   3.  All replies to IDCMP commands, and the value of -rc they returned
   4.  All other commands received, and the value of -rc they returned

Note that this tracing is internal to UcodeSlave - it can be used as a
complement to ARexx's own TRACE feature, which will tell you what a
particular script is doing.

Any script can issue a UTRACE command at any time, and it need not be
registered to do so. If UTRACE is already operative and a new UTRACE command
is received with a different WINDOW/FILE option, then UTRACE will switch to
the new option. Note that UTRACE always sends to the little window
UcodeSlave opens for the purpose, but depending on the FILE / WINDOW will
or will not also append to the T:Utrace file. UTRACE slows things down
slightly, especially if the FILE option is selected.

@endnode

@node unut  "[unut]    ARexx Command UNUTRACE"
@{b}UNUTRACE@{ub}
~~~~~~~~
Format

     'UNUTRACE'

UNUTRACE cancels the previous @{"UTRACE" link utra} command if there was one. UTRACE data
stop being sent to UcodeSlave's UTRACE window, but the window remains open
until such times as UcodeSlave closes down. Also, UTRACE data stop being
appended to the T:Utrace file, if that was happening.

Any script at any time can send an UNUTRACE command, and it need not be
registered to do so.

UTRACE and UNUTRACE do not nest, so any UNUTRACE received will cancel all
previous TRACE commands, and any UTRACE received will cancel all previous
UNUTRACE commands.

UTRACE and UNUTRACE are only meant to be used in the development stages of
a project - once your project is complete, any UTRACE and UNUTRACE commands
should be removed from your scripts.

@endnode

@node regi  "[regi]    ARexx Command REGISTER"
@{b}REGISTER@{ub}
~~~~~~~~
Format

    'REGISTER' [planes [width [height]]]

The [planes], [width] and [height] parameters are optional, and are normally
omitted. (See below)

REGISTER causes UcodeSlave to issue a uuser number to -rc, which will be
1 to 8. The following errors can occur:

    rc = 3 = can't REGISTER - too many users
    rc = 4 = can't REGISTER - out of memory
    rc = 5 = can't register - bad parameters (can't happen if no parameters)

Here is a suitable code fragment for REGISTERing:


   'register'
   if rc = 3 then say "Can't register - too many users"
   if rc = 4 then say "Can't register - out of memory"
   if rc < 0 then do

       uuser = -rc


       ..... issue UcodeSlave commands, using "uuser" as a user number ....


       'deregister' uuser

   end


Note that all UcodeSlave commands, except for @{"QUIT" link quit}, @{"UNQUIT" link unqu}, @{"UTRACE" link utra},
@{"UNUTRACE" link unut}, @{"REALLYQUIT" link real} and REGISTER require the script to append as the first command
parameter the uuser number returned by a REGISTER call.


...@{b}The uuser number@{ub}

Your script(s) should make no assumptions what uuser number they will be
given.

@{b}Where you see "uuser" in the docs, I mean the number that is returned to
a script in reply to the REGISTER command.@{ub}


...@{b}Can two (or more) scripts share a uuser number?@{ub}

Only one script can REGISTER a uuser number, and that number will never
be given to another REGISTERer unless the uuser relinquishes the number
by @{"DEREGISTER" link dere}ing. But, suppose a script tells that uuser number to another
script, can they both use it? Yes they can - UcodeSlave does not forbid
it. But be careful you don't get into a muddle.


...@{b}Can a script get more than one uuser number?@{ub}

If a script calls REGISTER more than once, it can have two (or more) uuser
numbers. UcodeSlave does not forbid this. But, since each REGISTER uses up
some memory, there does not seem to be any point in doing so.


...@{b}Advanced Usage@{ub}...

When a uuser registers, UcodeSlave creates a programming object for each
uuser called a "ucode_path". Within the ucode_path there are several
further embedded programming objects, one of which is a little rastport
called a "ucode_rport" which is used for getting glyphs into chip memory
before blitting them to windows.

This little rastport has chip memory of the same number of bitplanes as
the default public screen, the same width as the default public screen,
and default height of 70. Normally you need not know this object exists.
However there is a command @{"PRINT" link prin} (advanced usage) which prints
pre-formatted lines, and the size of these lines is limited to the size of
the ucode_rport's memory. You can therefore append planes, width and
height to the REGISTER command, subject to the following limits:

   planes = 2 to 8
   width  = 48 to 2048
   height = 36 to 128

@endnode

@node dere  "[dere]    ARexx Command DEREGISTER"
@{b}DEREGISTER@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~
Format

     'DEREGISTER' uuser

where uuser is a number that was given to the script by a @{"REGISTER" link regi} call.

After a user DEREGISTERs, the uuser number that was previously REGISTERed
becomes unregistered, and available to be given to any script that might
subsequently issue a REGISTER command.

If the script which registered as uuser has caused UcodeSlave to allocate
any resources (such as owned windows), and has not specifically de-allocated
them when it DEREGISTERs, then UcodeSlave automatically de-allocates those
resources. That is to say, that within its own context, UcodeSlave does
resource tracking.

(Note that if a script issues a @{"REALLYQUIT" link real} command, UcodeSlave automatically
DEREGISTERs any uusers that have not already DEREGISTERed).

@endnode

@node erro  "[erro]    ARexx Command UERROR"
@{b}UERROR@{ub}
~~~~~~
Format

     'UERROR' [uuser]

The UERROR command is advanced usage.

The error number returned by this is from ucode.library. If @{"REGISTER" link regi} failed,
and rc was 4, then what caused the problem was a ucode.library routine
called "TLUstart" which tries to make a programming object called a
"ucode_path". UERROR calls ucode.library to get an error report (if
possible) about what caused the error. If you have already registered
successfully, you must include uuser, and then you'll get an error
report from your most recent ucode.library call.

UERROR can return the following values in -rc. Most would be caused by
corruption in your hard disk system or shortage of memory.

 0 No error - or cause of error unknown
 1 TLUstart failed - Amiga library version s/be >= 37
 2                   can't open graphics.library
 3                   can't open intuition.library
 4                   out of memory
 5 out of memory
 6 UcodeFix failed - can't open UCODE:U0000/List for writing
 7                   can't write to UCODE:U0000/List
 8 TLUmakefont failed - bad filename
10                   can't open FONTS:name/size for writing
11                   can't write to FONTS:name/size
12                   can't create dir FONT:name
13                   can't open diskfont.library
14                   NewFontContents failed
15                   can't open FONTS:name.font for writing
16                   can't write FONTS:name.font
17                   can't lock FONTS:
18 can't open a glyph file for reading
19 can't read a glyph file / glyph file kaput
20 can't open UCODE:U0000/List for reading
21 can't read UCODE:U0000/List or UCODE:Uni/List kaput
22 TLUsaveprev failed - bad write
23 TLUloadprev failed - bad read
24 TLUloadprev failed - ucode_preview too small to hold file
25 TLUloadprev failed - bad file contents
@endnode

@node lend "[lend]   Lending a Window / Rastport to UcodeSlave"
@{b}Lending a Window / Rastport to UcodeSlave@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
The purpose of my Unicode distribution is of course to write Unicode to
windows. The most straight-forward way to do this is to provide a window
address to UcodeSlave, so that UcodeSlave can write to that window. You can
alternatively supply a rastport address for UcodeSlave to write to.

Ucode uses the following commands:

@{"WINDOW     " link wnd0}   Borrow a window / rastport
@{"SETWINDOW  " link stw0}   Attach a borrowed window / rastport to a script
@{"CLOSEWINDOW" link cls0}   Un-borrow a window /rastport
@{"SCREEN     " link scr0}   Specify a screen on which to seek windows
@{"About WBOX " link abou}   How to specify a print position
@{"WBOX       " link wbox}   Specify the area to draw on a window

In @{"UcodeSlave's GUI Commands" link guic} you will see extended versions of these
commands. But in this node I will just cover the basic commands as you
might need them for lending windows.

@endnode

@node wnd0  "[wnd0]    ARexx Command WINDOW"
@{b}WINDOW@{ub}     lend an already-open window / rastport
~~~~~~

@{i}This node tells you as much about the WINDOW command as you need to know
@{i}for borrowed windows. Click here for the full version of@{ui} @{"WINDOW" link wind}

Format

     WINDOW uuser $address [WINDOW / RASTPORT]

       or

     WINDOW uuser NAME name


  The WINDOW / RASTPORT parameter is optional, with default WINDOW. If your
  script specifies RASTPORT, then the $address will apply to an already-open
  rastport rather than an already-open window.

  If your script lends a RASTPORT, the rastport @{b}must@{ub} have a bitmap
  attached to it.

  The $address parameter means the script must supply the actual address of
  the window / rastport in hex notation. e.g. to lend a window at actual
  address "wind":

     'WINDOW' uuser D2X(wind,8)

  To lend a rastport at actual address "rast":

     'WINDOW' uuser D2X(rast,8) RASTPORT

  If you use the second format above, then UcodeSlave will look for the
  first non-blank character after NAME, and will take that to be the name
  of the window to be lent. The name is case significant, so if you specify
  the name 'fred', then a window named 'fred' will be found, but not a
  window named 'Fred'.

  e.g. suppose your script knows there is a window opened that has the
  name 'Cool window' in its title bar. You can lend it like this:

     'WINDOW' uuser 'NAME' 'Cool window'

  To find the named window, UcodeSlave looks through all windows on the
  default public screen.

  If your script has issued a @{"SCREEN" link scr0} command, then the currently operative
  SCREEN command will be the screen searched for a NAMEd window. If no
  SCREEN command has been successfully issued, UcodeSlave will seek the
  window on the default public screen, i.e. (usually) the workbench.

  You can't use NAME format to find a rastport, since rastports don't have
  names.

  If you omit the name after NAME, like this:

     'WINDOW' uuser 'NAME'

  then UcodeSlave will borrow the currently active window, if any.


Result      -rc =  9 to 16 if borrowed window
                  25 to 32 if borrowed rastport

            rc =   4  can't open - too many borrowed windows
                   6  can't open - too many borrowed rastports
                   8  bad command syntax
                   9  can't find NAMEd window


...@{b}The window / rastport becomes "attached"@{ub}...

If you call WINDOW successfully, the window / rastport becomes "attached"
to uuser. That means that if the script issues any commands which do
drawing, they will draw to the window / rastport which is currently
attached.


...@{b}The previously attached window (if any) will be detached@{ub}...

When WINDOW is called, if there was a window previously attached to uuser,
it will be detached and, until a uuser calls SETWINDOW for it, it will be
"free" and not attached to any uuser. @{b}This detachment happens even if
WINDOW fails.@{ub}


...@{b}Can the lender do things to a window while it is lent?@{ub}...

Yes, it can - UcodeSlave does not forbid this. The attached window is not
@{i}actually@{ui} attached at all. It just means that UcodeSlave can use the address
of the window or rastport to write to it. There are no problems about doing
this with a rastport. But with a window, the application which has lent the
window to UcodeSlave should have IDCMP verifies set when it sends drawing
commands to UcodeSlave, and not reply to any verify IDCMPs until UcodeSlave
replies to the drawimg commands.


...@{b}Can more than one uuser have the same window attached?@{ub}...

Yes, UcodeSlave does not forbid this.


...@{b}Can a uuser issue the @{"DEREGISTER" link dere} command while a window is attached?@{ub}...

Yes, UcodeSlave does not forbid this.

@endnode

@node stw0  "[stw0]    ARexx Command SETWINDOW"
@{b}SETWINDOW@{ub}       attach/detach a window/rastport to/from a uuser
~~~~~~~~~

@{i}This node tells you as much about the SETWINDOW command as you need to know
@{i}for borrowed windows. Click here for the full version of@{ui} @{"SETWINDOW" link setw}

Format

     SETWINDOW uuser [wnum]

Where uuser = the -rc returned by a @{"REGISTER" link regi} command
      wnum  = the -rc returned for that window/rastport by a @{"WINDOW" link wnd0} command

Result   rc = 0 = success
         rc = 2 = no such window / rastport
         rc = 3 = that window / rastport already attached to another window


...@{b}The attached window / rastport@{ub}...

When any uuser successfully calls @{"WINDOW" link wnd0}, the window/rastport which is
thereby successfully attached is given a number by UcodeSlave. That window
becomes attached to that uuser. If that uuser calls WINDOW again then the
new window will become attached to that uuser, and the old window will
become "free", unattached to any uuser. In such a state, UcodeSlave cannot
do anything to it, until it becomes once more attached to a uuser.

A window gets re-attached to a uuser by the SETWINDOW command. It need not
be attached to the same uuser as first attached it with a WINDOW command.
And, if a uuser already has a window attached when it calls SETWINDOW, then
the previously attached window will become "free", unattached ot any user.
@{b}The detachment happens even if the SETWINDOW command fails.@{ub}

It is legal to call SETWINDOW with the number of the window which is already
attached. In that case, nothing will happen.


...@{b}Omitting wnum@{ub}...

If wnum was 0 or omitted, the window (if any) currently attached to this
uuser will be released, and the uuser will not have any window attached to
it. The window will not be set to any uuser until this or another uuser
calls SETWINDOW with it.

@endnode

@node cls0  "[cls0]    ARexx Command CLOSEWINDOW"
@{b}CLOSEWINDOW@{ub}     unlend a window / rastport
~~~~~~~~~~~

@{i}This node tells you as much about the CLOSEWINDOW command as you need to know
@{i}for borrowed windows. Click here for the full version of@{ui} @{"CLOSEWINDOW" link clos}

Format

     CLOSEWINDOW uuser

Result  rc = 0 = ok
        rc = 2 = bad, this uuser did not have a window attached to it

If a borrowed window is attached to uuser, then a CLOSEWINDOW command
will cause UcodeSlave to "forget about" that borrowed window / rastport.
(It does NOT close it).

The number the window was given will then become free to be given to another
borrowed window / rastport when @{"WINDOW" link wnd0} is called.

If a uuser @{"DEREGISTER" link dere}s, then if there is a window / rastport still attached
to it at the time, it will be automatically CLOSEWINDOWed.

Once CLOSEWINDOW has operated successfully, no window / rastport will be
attached to the uuser that called CLOSEWINDOW, until it successfully calls
WINDOW or SETWINDOW.

@endnode

@node scr0  "[scr0]    ARexx Command SCREEN"
@{b}SCREEN@{ub}      specify a screen to use for seeking windows to be lent.
~~~~~~

@{i}This node tells you as much about the SCREEN command as you need to know
@{i}for borrowed windows. Click here for the full version of@{ui} @{"SCREEN" link scre}

Format

     SCREEN uuser NAME [name]       name is the name of a public screen
                                    if omitted -> the default public screen
                                    if WORKBENCH -> the workbench

Results

     -rc =  1 to 4   The screen was found
                     If -rc = 1, the default public screen was found

      rc =  2        too many screens
      rc =  3        out of memory
      rc =  4        can't attach screen - type unrecognised
      rc =  5        bad command syntax
      rc =  6        can't find screen with that name


The SCREEN command tells the @{"WINDOW" link wnd0} command where to look for windows. e.g.
suppose the script wants to lend a window named "Cool window" on a public
screen named "Cool screen", the commands are:

      'SCREEN' uuser 'NAME Cool screen'
      if rc < 0 then 'WINDOW' uuser 'NAME Cool window'

@endnode

@node abou  "[abou]    ARexx - about WBOX"
@{b}About WBOX@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~
The UcodeSlave @{"GRAB" link grab} and @{"PRINT" link prin} commands require the uuser to specify an
xpos, ypos to print at, and a @{"WBOX" link wbox}, being the sub-region of the window or
rastport on which printing takes place. So in the simplest case, we have
something like this:


     +----------------------+
     |                      | <---- window interior (WINT)
     |     +------------+   |
     |     |            | <-------- window box (WBOX)
     |     |  +------+  |   |
     |     |  |      |  |   |
     |     |  |      | <----------- text
     |     |  +------+  |   |
     |     +------------+   |
     |                      |
     +----------------------+

In the above digram, the WBOX fits in a sub-region of the window, and all
text fits within the WBOX. If it happens that text is too wide to fit in the
WBOX, and/or too high, and/or uuser specifies negative xpos and/or ypos for
WBOX, then text will be clipped. No text will ever appear outside the WBOX.

And if the uuser specifies a WBOX with negative xpos and/or ypos, or a width
and/or height that does not fit inside the WINT as it is sized at the
time of printing, then it will be clipped, resulting perhaps in further
clipping of the text as it is printed. It is even possible that text could
be entirely outside the WBOX, or the WBOX entirely outside the WINT. Note
that the WBOX position is taken relative to the WINT. If the uuser doesn't
specify a WBOX, then the WBOX will be the entire WINT

@{b}Now, here is a more complex example....@{ub}

Since windows may have scrollers, you can consider the window to show a
sub-section of a larger canvas. To be specific, it is the "interior" of the
window, the area inside the window borders, that scrolls around the canvas.

     +-------------------+
     |                   | <-- the imaginary canvas the window scrolls over
     |                   |
     |      +--------+   |
     |      |        | <-------the window interior (WINT)
     |      |        |   |
     |      |        |   |
     |      +--------+   |
     |                   |
     +-------------------+

If there is no such larger canvas (the window has no scrollers) then the
canvas simply coincides with the maximum interior dimensions of the window

In any case, UcodeSlave expects the uuser to specify a WBOX, being the
area to be printed to. You can consider this to be notionally an area of the
larger canvas.

so on the above, we might draw the WBOX like this:

                 +--------------------+
                 |   +------+         | <-- the imaginary canvas
                 |   |      |         |
     the    ------ > |   +--+-----+   |
     WBOX        |   |   |  |     | <-------the WINT
                 |   +---+--+     |   |
                 |       |        |   |
                 |       +--------+   |
                 |                    |
                 +--------------------+

In the above example, the WBOX would have -ve xpos and ypos relative to the
WINT.

But then the actual text to be printed will also scroll around relative to
the WBOX - the WBOX is like a window over the text, with some visible and
some not.

Drawing just the WBOX from the above, and imagining it to over part of the
text - the text being on its own imaginary canvas larger than the WBOX, we
might have:

                 +------------+
                 |            | <----  the text's imaginary canvas
                 |   +-----+  |
                 |   |     | <-------- the WBOX
                 |   |     |  |
                 |   |     |  |
                 |   +-----+  |
                 +------------+

Only the text lapping the WBOX (if any) is visible, and only the WBOX
lapping the WINT (as the user has currently sized it) is visible.

The WBOX is notionally drawn relative to the window's imaginary canvas, not
the window, and the text is drawn relative to the WBOX, also not the window.

So let us say the window is placed at posn (a,b) in the overall imaginary
canvas, and the WBOX is placed at posn (c,d) within the overall imaginary
canvas. The WBOX has width e and height f. The text is at position x,y
relative to the WBOX.

Then here are the data the uuser sets:

   1. WBOX is  c-a, d-b, e, f
   2. GRAB or PRINT coordinates would be  x, y

The text is always clipped to fit within the WBOX (and may be entirely
outside the WBOX, when nothing would be printed). In the above example,
x and y would both be negative. the WBOX position is relative to the
WINT, c-a, d-b in the above example, which would also both be negative.
When the window scrolls, the WBOX position scrolls the opposite way
relative to the window.

@endnode

@node wbox  "[wbox]    ARexx Command WBOX"
@{b}WBOX@{ub}            set up a print-to area on a window
~~~~
              See also @{"About WBOX" link abou}

Format

     WBOX uuser [xpos ypos width height]

Result   rc = 0 = success
         rc = 2 = bad, this uuser has no window / rastport set to it
         rc = 3 = bad, bad command parameters

xpos and ypos can be -32768 to 32767. They are relative to the top left
   of the rastport's bitmap, or the window's drawing area.
width and height can be 1 to 32767.
If xpos ypos width height are all omitted, WBOX will leave the window with
   no WBOX.
If WBOX fails with rc = 3, it will leave the window with no WBOX.
If WBOX is called when the window already had a WBOX, the old WBOX will be
   replaced by the new WBOX.

Every window or rastport can have a WBOX. A WBOX is a region relative to the
window interior where rendering will take place. When a window is first
opened it has no WBOX. In that case, the whole window is taken to be the
WBOX. But if a WBOX exists, then all rendering to the window (e.g. a GRAB
command) will be only within the edges of the WBOX, and not anywhere
outside the WBOX.

A WBOX need not be entirely within the interior of a window. For example,
it could overlap the lefthand side, or the bottom, or even all 4 sides. In
fact, the window's WBOX may even be entirely outside the window's borders.
Where the borders of a WBOX are partially or entirely outside the window's
borders, the rendering will be clipped as required. Where a command (such
as @{"GRAB" link grab}) renders to a window, the xpos and ypos of the command are relative
to the top left corner of the WBOX.

@endnode

@node guic "[guic]   UcodeSlave's GUI Commands"
@{b}UcodeSlaves's GUI Commands@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

@{i}This node is optional - if you do not wish for UcodeSlave to open its own
windows, then simply skip to the next node, i.e.@{ui}
     @{"UcodeSlave's Simple Unicode Commands" link ucom}.

These are the GUI-type commands for setting up windows, rastports, &c to
use as output:

@{"SCREEN      " link scre} Which screen to use        @{"WFRONT     " link wfro} Window to front
@{"WINDOW      " link wind} Open/borrow a window       @{"WBACK      " link wbac} Window to back
@{"WNAME       " link wnam} Set name of a window       @{"SFRONT     " link sfro} Screen to front
@{"SETWINDOW   " link setw} Attach/detach a window     @{"SBACK      " link sbac} Screen to back
@{"CLOSEWINDOW " link clos} Close/un-borrow a window   @{"SETIDCMP   " link seti} Set a window's IDCMP
@{"IDCMP       " link idcm} Get message from window    @{"SCROLLERS  " link scro} Set window's scrollers
@{"IDCMP supp  " link isup} Further IDCMP information  @{"BLIT       " link blit} Blit from rastport
@{"BEGINREFRESH" link begi} Start window refresh       @{"RECTANGLE  " link rect} draw a rectangle
@{"ENDREFRESH  " link begi} End window refresh         @{"AREA       " link area} Draw an area
@{"UNIDCMP     " link unid} Cancel an IDCMP command    @{"LOCK       " link lock} Lock window for drawing
@{"WMOVE       " link wmov} Move/size a window         @{"UNLOCK     " link unlo} Unlock window
@{"ICON        " link icon} Draw an "icon"

The purpose of my Unicode distribution is of course to write Unicode to
windows. The most straight-forward way to do this is to lend a window to
UcodeSlave, so that UcodeSlave can write to that window. You can
alternatively supply a rastport address for UcodeSlave to write to. The
previous node, @{"Lending a Window to UcodeSlave" link lend} showed how to do so.

UcodeSlave will also open a window or rastport for your script to write
unicode on if you wish. UcodeSlave will also collect messsages (such as
keyboard input or mouse clicks) from windows if you ask it to.

As well as displaying Unicode directly, UcodeSlave can also save any
arbitrarily-chosen set of Unicode glyphs your script might specify as an
Amiga font, which you can use in any program that allows you to specify
which font to use.

Once you have asked UcodeSlave to display Unicode on a window or rastport,
you can tell UcodeSlave to save the displayed image as IFF ILBM files,
either as a diskfile or on the clipboard. In that way, you can cut and paste
Unicode images to word processing programs that support the clipboard.

There is also a facility to save things which I call "Unicode preview
files" - these are a very powerful and flexible way of doing things, since
they are fully self-contained, and can re-format themselves to any layout
scheme.

All of the above mean that, in addition to UcodeSlave's actual Unicode-type
commands, you can also issue commands for a primitive GUI that UcodeSlave
sets up to use as an intermediary between processing Unicode into whatever
you want it to be.

@endnode

@node scre  "[scre]    ARexx Command SCREEN"
@{b}SCREEN@{ub}          specify which screen you want to open windows on
~~~~~~
Format

     SCREEN uuser ADDRESS [$address]   screen at $address
     SCREEN uuser NUMBER number        number from previous call
     SCREEN uuser IBASE number         number in IntuitionBase list
     SCREEN uuser NAME [name]          name of public screen

Result  -rc = 1 to 4 = success
              1      = the default public screen
              2 to 4 = other screens

         rc = 2 = too many screens
         rc = 3 = can't get screen drawing info (out of memory)
         rc = 4 = screen type unrecognised
         rc = 5 = bad command syntax
         rc = 6 = can't find the specified screen


The SCREEN command does not bring the specified screen to the front, or
attach it in any way. Its only use is in the WINDOW command. You can
specify up to 4 screens, which UcodeSlave gives numbers of 1 to 4, and
of which screen number 1 is always the default public screen.

When you issue a @{"WINDOW" link wind} command, if WINDOW opens a window it will be on
the currenly specified SCREEN. If WINDOW opens a rastport, it will have a
bitmap created for it, with similar size and bitplanes as the currently
specified SCREEN. If WINDOW lends a bitmap, the currently specified
screen is ignored. If WINDOW lends a window by using NAME name, a window
with that name will be sought on the currently specified SCREEN. If WINDOW
lends a window by using $address, then the window should either be on
the currently specified SCREEN, or be of similar drawing characteristics
(e.g. HIRES, &c) as the currently operative SCREEN.

I stress that the above is the @{b}only@{ub} use of a SCREEN command. A few commands
require UcodeSlave to look at the screen of the attached window, but when
that happens, UcodeSlave uses the window's pointer to its owning screen,
NOT the currently operative SCREEN. That is to say, the window attached to a
uuser need not be on the currently operative SCREEN.

When UcodeSlave first starts, UcodeSlave locks the default public screen
at the time it starts. That screen will be the initial screen given to
each uuser when it @{"REGISTER" link regi}s, even if the default public screen changes.
If there is no default public screen when UcodeSlave starts, it will refuse
to start.

UcodeSlave can "know about" up to 4 screens, numbered up to 4, of which
number 1 is always the default public screen when UcodeSlave opens. If you
issue a SCREEN command, UcodeSlave will find it, and return its number if it
already "knows about" that screen, or else add it to its list (which can be
up to 4 screens) and returns its number in the list.


The SCREEN command has 4 possible formats:


...@{b}SCREEN uuser ADDRESS [$address]@{ub}...

$address is the address of the screen's Intuition Screen structure.
If you omit $address, UcodeSlave will attach SCREEN 1, the default public
screen.

e.g. if a screen's address is at address "scr", you would send the
command:

     'screen' uuser D2X(scr,8)


...@{b}SCREEN uuser NUMBER number@{ub}...

Number can be 1, which is always default public screen when UcodeSlave
started up (i.e. usually the workbench).

If you specify 2 to 4, UcodeSlave must already have returned that number as
a reply to a SCREEN command, not necessarily to the same uuser. that way,
you can re-attach any screen UcodeSlave already knows about.


...@{b}SCREEN uuser IBASE number@{ub}...

@{b}It is very unlikely a script would ever want to use this format.@{ub} If you
specify 1, then the currently active screen in Intuition's list of screens
is returned. If you specify 2+, then UcodeSlave "walks through" the list of
screens, and returns that number in the sequence. If there is no such
screen, you'll get an error.


...@{b}SCREEN uuser NAME [name]@{ub}

If you specify name, then UcodeSlave will seek a public screen with that
name. If you omit name, then UcodeSlave will return the default public
screen.


...@{b}What if a SCREEN closes?@{ub}...

When UcodeSlave puts a public screen in its list, it "locks" it, so it
cannot close until UcodeSlave closes down.

If the currently operative screen is a private screen, and that screen
closes, and UcodeSlave tries to open a window on it, then UcodeSlave will
either refuse to open the window, or more likely crash. So if a script
supplies a private SCREEN, the script must know that the screen will not
close before the script is finished with it!

@endnode

@node wind  "[wind]    ARexx Command WINDOW"
@{b}WINDOW@{ub}          open a window, or "borrow" an already-open window
~~~~~~
Format

     WINDOW uuser

            {0 / $address}    Default 0, i.e. open an owned window/rastport.
            {NAME    name}    If $address supplied, or NAME format,
            {NAME        }    window / rastport will be borrowed.

  All further params are ignored if NAME format.

            [WINDOW / RASTPORT]         default WINDOW

  All further params are ignored if window borrowed.
  The next two params are ignored if RASTPORT specified.

            [BORDERS / NOBORDERS]       default BORDERS
            [SCROLLERS / NOSCROLLERS]   if BORDERS, default SCROLLERS
                                        if NOBORDERS, must be NOSCROLLERS
            [initwidth]                 if WINDOW default half screen width
                                        if RASTPORT default screen width
            [initheight]                if WINDOW default half screen height
                                        if RASTPORT default screen height

  All further parameters ignored if RASTPORT.

            [minwidth]                  default quarter screen width
            [minheight]                 default quarter screen height
            [maxwidth]                  default screen width
            [maxheight]                 default screen height
            [xpos]                      default middle of screen
            [ypos]                      default middle of screen

  Any of the parameters except the last two can be replaced by 0, when the
  default applies - but if xpos or ypos are 0 it will be taken be the actual
  value. If you give bad parameter values in the parameters from minwidth
  onward, UcodeSlave will attempt to correct them.

  If uuser supplies $address for a borrowed window, then it must supply
  the actual address of the window's Intuition Window structure in hex
  notation. e.g. if a script knws that a window is open at address wind:

     'WINDOW' uuser D2X(wind,8) 'WINDOW'

  To open an owned window with default parameters:

     'WINDOW' uuser


Result      -rc =  1 to 8  if owned window
                   9 to 16 if borrowed window
                  17 to 24 if owned rastport
                  25 to 32 if borrowed rastport

            rc =   3  can't open - too many owned windows
                   4  can't open - too many borrowed windows
                   5  can't open - too many owned rastports
                   6  can't open - too many borrowed rastports
                   7  can't open - out of memory
                   8  can't open - bad parameters
                   9  can't open - NAMEd window unfound

(See also @{"SCREEN" link scre}).


...@{b}The purpose of the WINDOW command@{ub}...

This command opens windows, which are called "owned" windows, or else
"borrows" windows, i.e. notes that windows belonging to the script or
another application exist. Alternately, it creates rastports, or "borrows"
rastports. If it borrows rastports, they MUST have BitMaps attached.

The simplest case is

     'WINDOW' uuser

which opens a window, which is therefore an "owned" window. If successful,
UcodeSlave returns -rc = 1 to 8, since owned window numbers are 1 to 8. The
window will have borders and scrollers by default, and be of dimensions as
per the above defaults.

If a NOBORDERS window is specified, a window will have no dragbar, size
gadget, close gadget, or zoom gadget, but if it is a BORDERS window it
will have all of these. If a window is NOBORDERS, it must also be
NOSCROLLERS.

If UcodeSlave is borrowing a window/rastport, only the uuser, $address/NAME
and WINDOW/RASTPORT parameters apply, so any further parameters will be
ignored.

If UcodeSlave is opening an owned rastport, then the uuser, 0 for address,
WINDOW/RASTPORT, initwidth & initheight parameters apply, and any further
parameters will be ignored. UcodeSlave will create and attach a BitMap
to the rastport, which will be the applicable maxwidth & maxheight in size,
and the same number of bitplanes as the screen. If the initwidth and/or
initheight are omitted or have value 0, the size of the screen will be used.


...@{b}The window becomes attached@{ub}...

The act of calling WINDOW will cause the window / rastport to be "attached"
to the uuser that sent the WINDOW command. From then on, until that window
becomes detached (by a subsequent WINDOW / @{"SETWINDOW" link setw} / @{"CLOSEWINDOW" link clos} command
from that uuser), all commands applying to windows by that user will
be done to that window / rastport.

If you ask UcodeSlave to do things to a borrowed window, the application
which actually owns the window might not appreciate it. in other words,
make sure you know what you are doing.


...@{b}the previously attached window (if any) will be detached@{ub}...

When WINDOW is called, if there was a window previously attached to uuser,
it will be detached and (until a uuser calls @{"SETWINDOW" link setw} for it) will not be
attached to any uuser. @{b}This happens even if WINDOW fails.@{ub}

@endnode

@node wnam  "[wnam]    ARexx Command WNAME"
@{b}WNAME@{ub}          give/change a name to an owned window
~~~~~
Format

     WNAME uuser wname

Where wname = a string, being the name to give the currently set window.
Maximum length 63 bytes.

Result   rc = 0 = success
         rc = 2 = bad, string length = 0, or has non-ASCII characters
         rc = 3 = bad, out of memory
         rc = 4 = bad, no owned window attached to uuser

There must be an owned window attached to uuser. When UcodeSlave first
opens an owned window (as a result of a @{"WINDOW" link wind} command), it has no title.
So to give it a title, call WNAME immediately after calling WINDOW. You can
change the name by sending another WNAME call. Note that each WNAME call
takes up 64 bytes of memory, which is not freed until such times as
uuser calls @{"DEREGISTER" link dere}.

@endnode

@node setw  "[setw]    ARexx Command SETWINDOW"
@{b}SETWINDOW@{ub}       attach/detach a window/rastport to a user
~~~~~~~~~
Format

     SETWINDOW uuser [wnum]

       or

     SETWINDOW uuser WAIT [wnum] [wnum] ....

Where uuser = the -rc returned by a @{"REGISTER" link regi} command
      wnum  = the -rc returned for that window/rastport by a @{"WINDOW" link wind} command

Result   rc = 0 = success
         rc = 2 = no such window / rastport
         rc = 3 = that window / rastport already attached to another window
         rc = 4 = WAIT format and no free owned windows
         rc = 5 = bad command format / parameters


...@{b}The attached window / rastport@{ub}...

When any uuser successfully calls @{"WINDOW" link wind}, the window/rastport which is
therefore created or borrowed is given a number by UcodeSlave. That window
becomes attached to that uuser. If that uuser calls WINDOW again then the
new window will become attached to that uuser, and the old window will
become "free", unattached to any uuser. In such a state, UcodeSlave cannot
do anything to it, until it becomes once more attached to a uuser.

A window gets re-attached to a uuser by the SETWINDOW command. It need not
be attached to the same uuser as first attached it with a WINDOW command.
And, if a uuser already has a window attached when it calls SETWINDOW, then
the attached window will become "free", unattached to any user.

It is legal to call SETWINDOW with the number of the window which is already
attached. In that case, nothing will happen.


...@{b}Omitting wnum@{ub}...

If wnum was 0 or omitted, the window (if any) currently attached to this
uuser will be released, and the uuser will not have any window attached to
it. The window will not be set to any uuser until this or another uuser
calls SETWINDOW with it.


...@{b}SETWINDOW with WAIT@{ub}...

If you call SETWINDOW with WAIT, then UcodeSlave will first detach the
currently attached window if any. Then, as far as uuser is concerned, it
will wait for any "free" window, i.e. any window not currently set to any
other uuser, to have an IDCMP. When a free window has an IDCMP, UcodeSlave
will attach that window to uuser, and return with results as per @{"IDCMP" link idcm}.

@{b}Note that UcodeSlave never looks for IDCMPs from borrowed windows, only
from owned windows.@{ub}

If while your script is sleeping other uusers attach or close all free owned
windows, then UcodeSlave will wake your script and return with rc = 4.
(Or else your script would hang up permanently).

The purpose of SETWINDOW with WAIT is to enable your script to manage a
suite of windows.

If free windows get the following types of IDCMPs while a uuser is sleeping,
UcodeSlave will NOT wake your uuser, but simply reply to the IDCMPs and
otherwise ignore them: ACTIVEWINDOW, INACTIVEWINDOW, MOUSEMOVE, DELTAMOUSE,
and VERIFYs. This is to stop things from getting into a loop.

Normally, SETWINDOW with WAIT will look at all free windows to seek an
IDCMP. But it may be that you want your script to only check particular
windows. Bear in mind that any other applications may be using UcodeSlave,
and may have its own windows free. Obviously, you would not want your
script to attach any of those windows.

So, I recommend that your script always attaches a list of 1 or more
window / rastport numbers (up to 8), which will be the only ones that
UcodeSlave looks at for IDCMPs.

e.g. if your script sends the command

    SETWINDOW uuser WAIT 1 3 4

then when SETWINDOW returns, it will be with window 1, 3 or 4 attached.
If your script does not append a list after SETWINDOW uuser WAIT, then it
will be as if it had issued:

    SETWINDOW uuser 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8

The numbers in the list must be from 1 to 8, a maximum of 8 in the list.
It doesn't matter if the windows with each number exist or not, or are
attached to another uuser or not. It doesn't matter if you duplicate items
in the list.

If the following things happen while SETWINDOW with WAIT is waiting:

 - a window in the list doesn't exist:  it will not be looked at (of course)
 - a window in the list gets closed:    it will stop being looked at
 - a window in the list gets opened:    it will start being looked at
 - a window in the list is attached
   to another uuser:                    it will not be looked at
 - a window in the list gets detached
   from another uuser:                  it will start being looked at
 - a window in the list gets attached
   to another uuser:                    it will stop being looked at
 - all windows in the list stop being
   looked at:                           SETWINDOW returns in error (rc=4)

UcodeSlave can be used simultaneously by many scripts. But unlike Amiga
"pure" programs, which can simultaneously be doing various things,
UcodeSlave completely finishes one command before it starts another
command. The only exceptions are IDCMP and SETWINDOW with WAIT, where
UcodeSlave can be doing other uusers' commands while waiting for an IDCMP
from one or more windows. Hence the information in the previous paragaph.


...@{b}Which window is attached?@{ub}...

After SETWINDOW uuser WAIT, you may want to know which window became
attached. In that case you can use the @{"QUERY" link quer} command like this:

   QUERY uuser 8

which returns the attached window / rastport number in -rc.


...@{b}Bypassing UcodeSlave@{ub}...

If a script wants to do things directly to an owned window, i.e. not by
using UcodeSlave commands, but by directly making Amiga library calls, then
it is a good idea to detach the window from any uuser while the things are
done.

@endnode

@node clos  "[clos]    ARexx Command CLOSEWINDOW"
@{b}CLOSEWINDOW@{ub}     close or unborrow a window / rastport
~~~~~~~~~~~
Format

     CLOSEWINDOW uuser

Result  rc = 0 = ok
        rc = 2 = bad, this uuser does not have a window set to it



If a borrowed window is attached to uuser, then a CLOSEWINDOW command
will cause UcodeSlave to "forget about" that borrowed window / rastport.
The number it was given will then become free to be given to another
borrowed window / rastport when @{"WINDOW" link wind} is called.

An owned window or rastport is actually closed if the uuser to which it
is attached calls CLOSEWINDOW.

If an owned window or rastport becomes detached from any uuser, and is never
again attached to a uuser by a @{"SETWINDOW" link setw} command, then that window or
rastport does not get closed until such times as UcodeSlave closes down.

If a uuser @{"DEREGISTER" link dere}s, then if there is a window / rastport still attached
to it at the time, it will be automatically CLOSEWINDOWed.

Once CLOSEWINDOW has operated successfully, no window / rastport will be
attached to the uuser that called CLOSEWINDOW, until it successfully calls
@{"WINDOW" link wind} or @{"SETWINDOW" link setw}.

@endnode

@node idcm  "[idcm]    ARexx Command IDCMP
@{b}IDCMP@{ub}           await/get a message from an owned window
~~~~~
Format

     IDCMP uuser


IDCMP sends the following +ve result to rc if it fails:

      rc = 3 = bad, this uuser does not have an owned window attached
                    to it.

but if if succeeds, it sends a -ve or zero result to rc.

A script can only successfully call IDCMP if it has an owned window
attached to it. A rastport or a borrowed window will not do.

IDCMP messages are Amiga's way of telling the user that messages are
received. so, if a window is active, and the user presses a key on the
keyboard, or clicks a mousebutton, amiga's window system (called
"intuition") sends a message to the window.

It is your script's responsibility to send IDCMP commands regularly to
UcodeSlave if it has any owned window attached to it, or @{"SETWINDOW" link setw} WAIT if
the script is managing several windows. Otherwise the user might be e.g.
typing characters, and wondering why the window doesn't do anything.

When Ucodeslave opens an owned window, it sets a number of IDCMP "flags",
which tells intuition to send IDCMP messages when certain types of IDCMP
events occur, but not others. These are the IDCMP flags which UcodeSlave
sets when it opens a window:

     NEWSIZE         GADGETDOWN     CLOSEWINDOW    DISKINSERTED
     REFRESHWINDOW   GADGETUP       RAWKEY         DISKREMOVED
     MOUSEBUTTONS    REQSET         REQCLEAR       WBENCHMESSAGE
     MENUHELP        MENUPICK       NEWPREFS       DISKINSERTED
     DISKREMOVED     WBENCHMESSAGE  ACTIVEWINDOW   INACTIVEWINDOW
     VANILLAKEY      IDCMPUPDATE

These will be explained (up to a point) below, but if you want a fuller
explanation, you should consult the official Amiga ROM Kernal manuals. If
you want to change the IDCMP flags that are set, see the @{"SETIDCMP" link seti} command.

UcodeSlave pre-processes the IDCMP messages into the following information:

  1. a code
  2. a qualifier
  3. a mouse position
  4. an IAddress
  5. timer information

When you get a reply to your IDCMP command, you only get the code. But you
can get all of the other data with the MOUSE, QUALIFIER, IADDRESS, SECONDS,
and MICROS commands. (see @{"Idcmp supp" link isup}).

Here are the various types of IDCMP results that UcodeSlave returns in
-rc:

  0. A null event.

     IDCMP can return in certain rare circumstances with not an error, but
     with rc = 0, i.e. a null event. In such a case, do not call
     MOUSE, QUALIFIER etc. as they will not have valid contents. In
     general, if IDCMP returns with 0, you would immediately call IDCMP
     again.


  1. A vanilla key event.

     These will return these codes in -rc:

        Backspace          $08
        Tab                $09
        CR / Enter         $0D
        Esc                $1B
        Space              $20
        Del                $7F

        printable ASCII    $21-$7E, $A1-$FF

     (The exact results depend on Amiga keyboard map preferences settings)

     These represent the ASCII of keys pressed on your keyboard. e.g. if
     the user presses the 'A' key while the owned window attached to your
     script's uuser is active, then the -rc returned to your IDCMP will
     be $61, which is the ASCII for 'a'. If you pressed SHIFT with A, then
     the code would be $41, the ASCII of 'A'.


    2. a raw key event.

     UcodeSlave sends the following values in -rc for
     "rawkey" key up events:

           $81-$8A     function keys F1 to F10
           $8B         help
           $8C         left arrow
           $8D         right arrow
           $8E         up arrow
           $8F         down arrow

     (some of the above might be diverted to commodity "hotkeys" that
      the user might have attached to the keyboard)

     UcodeSlave does not send you rawkey key down events.


    3. a closewindow event

       -rc = $93 = user has clicked the "closewindow" gadget

       (your script should then presumably send a @{"CLOSEWINDOW" link clos} command)


    4. a gadgetup event

       -rc = $95 = user has released the mousebutton over a
                            gadget

       This would only happen if you have attached gadgets to the window.
       If you get such a message, you would presumably next issue an
       @{"IADDRESS" link isup} command to get the address of the gadget that was upped.


    5. a menupick event

       -rc = $9C = user has picked a menu item.

       This would only happen if you attach a menu to the window.

       If -rc bits 0-7 = $9C, then the following data are placed in bits
       0 to 23 of -rc if you issue the @{"QUALIFIER" link isup} command:

           bits 0-7    the menu number      } Each of these is 1+
           bits 8-15   the item number      } if meaningful
           bits 16-23  the sub-item number  }

       Presumably your script would then do what the user has requested.


    6. a sizewindow event

       -rc = $96 = user has resized the window.


    7. an inactivewindow event

       -rc = $97 = window has become inactive

       while a window is inactive, hardly any IDCMPs can get through. The
       next message you would normally receive would be an activewindow
       event.


    8. the scrollers have moved

       -rc bits 0-7 = $98 = the user has moved one of the scrollers

       If your script gets this message, it should send a @{"QUERY" link quer} command
       to find the position of the scrollers. It would then presumably
       scroll the window contents as required.

       If a script sends a @{"SCROLLERS" link scro} command, it may get an IDCMP scroller
       event as a consequence of UcodeSlave moving the scrollers.


     9. an IDCMPUPDATE message has arrived

       -rc bits 0-7 = $99 = an IDCMPUPDATE message has arrived

       This could only happen if you have attached a BOOPSI object to
       your window. Actually, the scrollers that UcodeSlave puts in owned
       windows that specified SCROLLERS are in fact BOOPSI objects, but
       UcodeSlave intercepts these, and sends messages from them as
       code = $98 (see item 8. "the scrollers have moved" above).


    10. left mouse button down    -rc bits 0-8 = $80
        left mousebutton up       -rc bits 0-8 = $9A
        right mousebutton down    -rc bits 0-8 = $13
        right mousebutton up      -rc bits 0-8 = $14

        Right mouse button events do not arrive, unless your script has
        somehow switched on your window's rmb trap.

        If an lmb event arrived, your script would presumably immediately
        issue the @{"MOUSE" link isup} command to find where the pointer was at the
        time, and then act accordingly.

        With keyboard events, UcodeSlave only sends IDCMP for key up events,
        (or repetitively if a key is held down), since users expect
        something to happen only when a key is released. But with mouse
        events, they expect something to happen when the mouse button is
        downed, not perhaps if it is upped, so that's when your script
        should act.


    11. refresh - window has been resized, so its imagery needs refreshing

        -rc = $9F = refresh

        If your script gets a refresh event, it must @{b}as urgently as
        possible@{ub} issue a @{"BEGINREFRESH" link begi} command, followed re-drawing the
        window, and then an @{"ENDREFRESH" link begi} command.

        All other commands except BEGINREFRESH are disabled after IDCMP
        returns -rc = $9F, and most commands (except drawing commands) are
        disabled after BEGINREFRESH is received, and before ENDREFRESH is
        received.


    12. mousemove

        -rc = $9E = mousemove

        If your script gets a mousemove event, it would presumably send
        a MOUSE command to see where the mouse is. mousemove can cause
        a lot of messages.

        By default, UcodeSlave does not ask intuition for these, so you
        would have to issue a @{"SETIDCMP" link seti} command to request them.

    13. gadget down

        -rc = $94 = gadget down

        This is the counterpart to a gadget up event - see "4. gadget up"
        above.


    14. deltamouse

        -rc = $01 = deltamouse

        This operates like "12. mousemove" above, which see. By default,
        UcodeSlave does not ask intuition for these, so you would have to
        issue a @{"SETIDCMP" link seti} command to request them.


    15. menuhelp

        -rc = $9D = menuhelp

        See the Amiga ROM Kernal manuals for details of this. If you receive
        a menuhelp event, @{"QUALIFIER" link isup} returns the same format as a menupick
        event (see @{"menupick" link "idcm"125}).


    16. an intuiticks event

       -rc = $03 = an intuitick has happened

       Theoretically intuition puts, in every window that wants it, a
       a message every 50th of a second. Unfortunately intuiticks don't
       arrive reliably, so this as a method of synchronising things doesn't
       work.

       By default, UcodeSlave does not ask intuition for these, so you
       would have to issue a @{"SETIDCMP" link seti} command to request them.


     17. workbench message

       -rc = $04 = a workbench message has arrived.

       See the Amiga ROM Kernal manuals for details of this.


     18. disk inserted /removed

       -rc = $91 = disk inserted
       -rc = $92 = disk removed

       These IDCMPs are broadcast to windows whenever a floppy is inserted
       or removed, even if the windows are inactive, provided of course the
       relevant IDCMP flag is set.


     19. new prefs

       -rc = $9B = newprefs

       This IDCMP is sent to all windows with the relevant flag set if
       the user changes the workbench prefs (i.e. all the things in the
       workbench preferences drawer). The really conscientious programmer
       might check if the user has reset preferences that affect his/her
       script, and act accordingly.


     20. active window

       -rc = $90 = active window

       This IDCMP is received whenever a window is activated, e.g by
       the user clicking it.


     21. requester set

       -rc = $11 = requester set

       This IDCMP is sent to a window if a requester is set.


     22. change window

       -rc = $02 = change window

       This IDCMP is sent when a window not only changes size (as in
       @{"sizewindow" link "idcm"141}) but also if the user moves the window.

       By default, UcodeSlave does not ask intuition for these, so you
       would have to issue a @{"SETIDCMP" link seti} command to request them.


     23. requester clear

       -rc = $12 = requester clear

       This IDCMP is sent to a window if a requester is cleared.


     24. -rc = $16 = size verify
         -rc = $15 = menu verify
         -rc = $17 = requester verify

       If UcodeSlave receives any of these, it does not reply to it, and
       the Amiga system will time them out.

       UcodeSlave always adds these three to the IDCMP flags when you issue
       a @{"LOCK" link lock} command, and removes them when you issue
       an @{"UNLOCK" link unlo} command.

       The effect of these IDCMP flags is to "lock" a window (since
       the window resize gadget doesn't work, requesters can't go up, and
       menus can't drop down, while these flags are set) until UcodeSlave
       replies to intuition after receiving the message.

       If a script wants to render to an owned window, here is what should
       happen:

         1. issue a LOCK command.

            While LOCK is in force, the window cannot be resized.

         2. Do the rendering.

         3. issue an UNLOCK command.


       Your script should not attach or detach verify IDCMP flags using
       @{"SETIDCMP" link seti}, but rather by using @{"LOCK" link lock} and @{"UNLOCK" link unlo}.



@{b}Window Refreshing@{ub}

If your script gets $9F (refresh) to an IDCMP I recommend that you merely
issue the commands:

       @{"BEGINREFRESH" link begi} uuser
       @{"ENDREFRESH  " link begi} uuser

and other wise ignore them. This is because UcodeSlave windows are smart
refresh windows, and so they will also get $96 (size window) whenever a
window needs refreshing. You can then issue 'LOCK' uuser, re-draw the
window, and then issue 'UNLOCK' uuser. This is better because Amiga's
refreshing system doesn't work reliably, and also because if a user tries to
use the size gadget while a window is refreshing, there is a slight chance
the Amiga will hang up.

See also under @{"MOVE" link move} (advanced usage).

@endnode

@node isup "[isup]   ARexx Commands MOUSE QUALIFIER IADDRESS ISECONDS IMICROS"
@{b}MOUSE  QUALIFIER  IADDRESS  ISECONDS  IMICROS@{ub}
~~~~~  ~~~~~~~~~  ~~~~~~~~  ~~~~~~~~  ~~~~~~~
When your script gets back the result of an @{"IDCMP" link idcm} command, it can issue the
following commands to get more information:

   MOUSE uuser        returns the MouseX and MouseY in bits 0-15 and 16-30
                      respectively in -rc. The mouse position is at the
                      time the IDCMP took place, relative to the top left
                      of the window.

   QUALIFIER uuser    returns the state of the keyboard "dead" keys in
                      -rc, as follows:

                        bit  0  1 if left shift key held down
                             1  1 if right shift key held down
                             2  1 if caps lock is on
                             3  1 if Ctrl key held down
                             4  1 if left Alt key held down
                             5  1 if right Alt key held down
                             6  1 if left Amiga key held down
                             7  1 if right Amiga key held down
                             8  1 if the numeric pad was used
                             9  1 if keyboard repeat was operative
                            10  (unused)
                            11  (broadcast to all windows)
                            12  1 if left mouse button held down
                            13  1 if right mouse button held down
                            14  1 if middle mousebutton held down

   IADDRESS uuser     returns half the address of a gadget in -rc, if a
                      gadget returned the IDCMP. Else 0. (Returns half the
                      address so rc can be always +ve; double the return
                      value to get the actual address.

   ISECONDS uuser     returns the timer seconds value in -rc
   IMICROS uuser      returns the timer microseconds value in -rc
                      ISECONDS and IMICROS are not much use, since ARexx is
                      too slow for time sensitive things.

@endnode

@node begi  "[begi]    ARexx Commands BEGINREFRESH ENDREFRESH"
@{b}BEGINREFRESH  ENDREFRESH@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~  ~~~~~~~~~~
Format

     BEGINREFRESH uuser
     ENDREFRESH uuser

Results

    rc = 0 = success
    rc = 1 = bad, no owned window attached to uuser
    rc = 2 = bad, window not in refresh state
    rc = 3 = bad, BEGINREFRESH already received


@{b}To make your scripts work reliably, you need to take careful note of
this information about the BEGINREFRESH and ENDREFRESH commands.@{ub}

All UcodeSlave's owned windows are "Smart Refresh" windows. Those that are
resizeable will send "refresh window" IDCMP events whenever they are
resized. in general, the resizing of a window will mean that your script
will usually want to redraw its contents.

Here is what should happen:

   (a) UcodeSlave replies to your IDCMP command with a $9F in -rc
       (i.e. a "refresh window" event).

   (b) Your script sends a STARTREFRESH command.

   (c) Your script then sends 0 or commands for re-drawing the window.
       Intuition will cleverly act so as to only re-draw those drawing
       commands which are actually on the part of your window that became
       exposed by being enlarged. This means that the whole thing is much
       quicker than re-drawing the whole window. So though your script
       may think it is re-drawing the whole window, intuition only re-draws
       what is necessary.

   (d) Finally your script sends an ENDREFRESH command

While your window is in a STARTREFRESH state, Intuition "locks" it, which
means the user cannot resize it until your script sends an ENDREFRESH.

@{b}The refreshing process must happen as quickly as it possibly can.@{ub}

Example: suppose a subroutine (function) labelled "Draw" has all the
commands necessary for re-drawing the window. Here is how to handle refresh
commands:

       'idcmp' uuser
       char = -rc
       if char = 159 then do            /* 159 = $9F = refresh */
           'beginrefresh' uuser
           call Draw
           'endrefresh' uuser
       end

If your refreshing takes more than a reasonable time, there is a chance
UcodeSlave will hang up. So, if in doubt, do this:

       'idcmp' uuser
       char = -rc
       if char = 159 then do            /* 159 = $9F = refresh */
           'beginrefresh' uuser
           'endrefresh' uuser
           call Draw
       end

i.e. call "Draw", but in this case not between 'beginrefresh' and
'endrefresh'. This is slower, and may look a bit uglier on the window as it
happens, but is safer. If the user tries to move or resize the window while
it is refreshing (which is hardly possible if it takes less than a quarter
of a second), UcodeSlave might possibly hang up. I can't find why this
happens - it shouldn't. So, to be safe, if refreshing takes a while, do the
refreshing @{b}after@{ub} calling beginrefresh and endrefresh.

If your script neglects to send a STARTREFRESH command, UcodeSlave will not
accept any further @{"IDCMP" link idcm} commands from you, or let you do anything to the
window at all, until you send a STARTREFRESH. And, if your script has sent
a STARTREFRESH, UcodeSlave will not let you send IDCMP commands, or do
anything at all to the window - other than draw to it of course - until you
send an ENDREFRESH.

If there is simply no need to redraw the window contents when your script
gets a $9F, then it can simply issue the commands:

      'startrefresh' uuser
      'endrefresh' uuser

with nothing between them.

@endnode

@node unid  "[unid]    ARexx Command UNIDCMP"
@{b}UNIDCMP@{ub}        stop waiting for a reply to an IDCMP
~~~~~~~
Format

    UNIDCMP uuser

Result

    UNIDCMP always returns rc = 0


If a script has sent an @{"IDCMP" link idcm} command, the script will "go to sleep" until
it receives a reply. The UNIDCMP is a rather complex way to "time out" an
IDCMP command. But note: the script that sent the IDCMP cannot send an
UNIDCMP command while it is waiting. Rather, another script must send the
UNIDCMP command, using the uuser number of the first script.

UcodeSlave will reply to the first script's IDCMP command with rc = 0,
and to the second script's UNIDCMP command with rc = 0.

Here is the sequence of events to set it up:

  1. Script 1 tells script 2 its uuser number, and that it is sending
     an IDCMP command.
  2. Script 1 sends an IDCMP to UcodeSlave.
  3. If Script 1 gets a reply, it tells script 2.
  4. If Script 2 has not been told there is a reply after a specified delay,
     it sends an UNIDCMP command.
  5. Script 1 will then get a reply to its IDCMP command, with rc = 0.

Obviously, this is a sophisticated scenario, for advanced usage. Also, timer
sensitive things don't work that well with ARexx, as it is rather slow.

Note: the @{"SETWINDOW" link setw} uuser WAIT command ends with the uuser waiting for an
IDCMP, so it too can be aborted with an UNIDCMP command, when it returns
with rc = 0, and no window attached to uuser.

@endnode

@node wmov  "[wmov]    ARexx Command WMOVE
@{b}WMOVE@{ub}            move/size an owned window
~~~~~
Format

     WMOVE uuser xpos ypos width height

Result   rc = 0 = success
         rc = 2 = bad, this uuser has no owned window attached to it

xpos, ypos, width, height = the desired window position & size.


If the parameters that your script supplies are incompatible with the
dimensions of the attached window supplied, or the screen it appears on,
UcodeSlave will correct the parameters as far as required.

If your script specifies -1 for a dimension, it will be left at its old
value.

@endnode

@node wbac  "[wbac]    ARexx Command WBACK"
@{b}WBACK@{ub}      owned window to back
~~~~~
Format

     WBACK uuser

Result   rc = 0 = success
         rc = 2 = bad, no owned window attached to uuser

Moves an owned window behind all other windows on its screen. If it was
activated, it stays activated.

@endnode

@node wfro  "[wfro]    ARexx Command WFRONT
@{b}WFRONT@{ub}     owned window to front, and activate it
~~~~~~
Format

     WFRONT uuser

Result   rc = 0 = success
         rc = 2 = bad, no owned window attached to uuser


Moves an owned window in front of all other windows on its screen, and
(if it is inactive), activates it. This might cause an active window event
to be sent to the IDCMP.

@endnode

@node sfro  "[sfro]    ARexx Command SFRONT"
@{b}SFRONT@{ub}       bring a screen which has an owned window to front
~~~~~~
Format

     SFRONT uuser

Result  rc = 0 = success
        rc = 2 = bad, no owned window attached to uuser

Moves the screen on which an owned window appears to the front of all other
screens. The window is neither activated or brought to the front - use the
@{"WFRONT" link wfro} command for that. If there is only one screen, or the
screen with the attached window on it is already in front, nothing happens.

n.b. This command does @{b}not@{ub} use the screen (if any) currently set
with a @{"SCREEN" link scre} command - the screen to be brought to the front is found from
the owned window's internal pointer.

@endnode

@node sbac  "[sbac]    ARexx Command SBACK"
@{b}SBACK@{ub}       put a screen which has an owned window to back
~~~~~
Format

     SBACK uuser

Result  rc = 0 = success
        rc = 2 = bad, no owned window attached to uuser

Moves the screen on which an owned window appears to the back of all other
screens. The window is not moved to the back of its screen - use the @"WBACK" link wbac}
command for that. If there is only one screen, or the screen with
the attached window on it is already the hindmost, nothing happens.

n.b. This command does @{b}not@{ub} use the screen (if any) currently set
with a @{"SCREEN" link scre} command - the screen to be moved to the back is found from
the owned window's internal pointer.

@endnode

@node seti  "[seti]    ARexx Command SETIDCMP"
@{b}SETIDCMP@{ub}        set an owned window's IDCMP
~~~~~~~~
Format

     SETIDCMP uuser SET/ADD/SUB $idcmp

Result   rc = 0 = success
         rc = 2 = bad, this uuser has no owned window attached
         rc = 3 = bad, bad parameters

$value is a mask (in hex notation) of IDCMPs as per the table below.

If SET, $value will be the new IDCMP value
If ADD, $value will be added into the existing IDCMP value
If SUB, $value will be subtracted out of the existing IDCMP value

The available values are:

        SIZEVERIFY      $00000001
        NEWSIZE         $00000002
        REFRESHWINDOW   $00000004
        MOUSEBUTTONS    $00000008
        MOUSEMOVE       $00000010
        GADGETDOWN      $00000020
        GADGETUP        $00000040
        REQSET          $00000080
        MENUPICK        $00000100
        CLOSEWINDOW     $00000200    (preferably, use LOCK and UNLOCK
        RAWKEY          $00000400     if you wish to alter the VERIFY
        REQVERIFY       $00000800     flags).
        REQCLEAR        $00001000
        MENUVERIFY      $00002000
        NEWPREFS        $00004000
        DISKINSERTED    $00008000
        DISKREMOVED     $00010000
        WBENCHMESSAGE   $00020000
        ACTIVEWINDOW    $00040000
        INACTIVEWINDOW  $00080000
        DELTAMOVE       $00100000
        VANILLAKEY      $00200000
        INTUITICKS      $00400000
        IDCMPUPDATE     $00800000
        MENUHELP        $01000000
        CHANGEWINDOW    $02000000

There is more about these under the @{"IDCMP" link idcm} command.

@endnode

@node scro  "[scro]    ARexx Command SCROLLERS"
@{b}SCROLLERS@{ub}            re-position the window's scrollers
~~~~~~~~~
Format

     SCROLLERS uuser xtotal xvisible xtop xstep ytotal yvisible ytop ystep

Result   rc = 0 = success
         rc = 2 = bad, window has no owned window attached
         rc = 3 = bad, attached window has no scrollers
         rc = 4 = bad, bad parameter values

You can only send a SCROLLERS command to a window if it is an owned window.

Windows with scrollers have arbitrary initial scroller parameters of

         256 256 0 1 256 256 0 1

The following rules apply for parameters:

         xtotal >= xtop + xvisible
         xstep <= xvisible
         ytotal >= ytop + yvisible
         ystep <= yvisible

xtotal is the notional maximum width of the window display, if it all fitted
on the window at once, while xvisible is the width which will fit. xtop
is the left-most visible point. xstep is the amount that xtop will change
if one clicks the scroller's left or right arrow. If one clicks the scroller
to the left or right of its drag button, xtop will change by
xvisible - xstep. The corresponding rules apply for vertical dimensions.

The parameters are commonly, but not necessarily, measured in pixels. In
fact they have no absolute size, but are simply proportional to each other.

If SCROLLERS merely change xstep &/or ystep, nothing will happen until
the next time one clicks the scrollers' little arrow buttons.

@endnode

@node blit  "[blit]    ARexx Command BLIT"
@{b}BLIT@{ub}          blit from a rastport to a window
~~~~
Format

    BLIT uuser rastport xfrom yfrom width height xto yto

Result

    rc = 0 success
    rc = 2 no window / rastport attached
    rc = 3 bad parameters
    rc = 4 no such sender / sender must be rastport


The BLIT command blits an area from a rastport to a window. So, either an
owned or borrowed window / rastport must be attached to uuser when BLIT
is called.

The parameter "rastport" (in format above) must be the number of a rastport
(not a window) from 17 to 32. Presumably, uuser will have previously had
the rastport attached, and drawn to it, and then detached the rastport and
attached the window to be blitted to.

The area in the rastport (xfrom, yform, width, height) is relative to the
top left of the whole rastport - NOT the rastport's WBOX if it has one.
xfrom and yfrom must be >=0, and width and height must be >0.

The receiving position (xto, yto) will be relative to the receiving window's
WBOX, or if it doesn't have a @{"WBOX" link wbox}, to the window interior's top left.
xto and yto can be -ve.

UcodeSlave will clip what is blitted if it is too big to fit in the
receiving window's WBOX (or interior if it doesn't have a WBOX).

@endnode

@node rect  "[rect]    ARexx Command RECTANGLE"
@{b}RECTANGLE@{ub}      Draws a rectangle
~~~~~~~~~
Format

    RECTANGLE uuser xpos ypos width height [pena] [penb]

Result

    rc = 2 = no window / rastport attached
    rc = 3 = bad parameters

xpos and ypos can be -ve. width and height must be positive non-zero. [pena]
and [penb] if specified are 0 to 255, and can be the same as each other.

The rectangle drawn has sides 2 pixels wide, and top & bottom 1 pixel high.
If you specify different values for the 2 pens, you get an Amiga-style
bevelled box; whereas if you specify the same colour for the pens you get
a plain box. The default pens are 1 2.

The specified rectangular area is relative to the current WBOX for the
attached window / rastport; no rendering takes place outside of the WBOX.
If a window / rastport currently has no @{"WBOX" link wbox}, the entire window interior /
rastport is taken as the WBOX.

@endnode

@node area  "[area]    ARexx Command AREA"
@{b}AREA@{ub}            Fills a rectangular area with a colour
~~~~
Format

    AREA      uuser xpos ypos width height [pen]

Result

    rc = 0 = success
    rc = 2 = bad, no window / rastport attached
    rc = 3 = bad, bad parameters

xpos and ypos can be -ve. width and height must be positive non-zero. [pen]
if specified is 0 to 255.

Fills the specified rectangular with a colour. If [pen] is omitted, the
PENS background pen (default 0) is used. (See @{"PENS" link pens}).

The specified rectangular area is relative to the current WBOX for the
attached window / rastport; no rendering takes place outside of the WBOX.
If a window / rastport currently has no @{"WBOX" link wbox}, the entire window interior /
rastport is taken as the WBOX.

@endnode

@node lock  "[lock]    ARexx Command LOCK"
@{b}LOCK@{ub}            Lock a window for drawing
~~~~
Format

    LOCK     uuser

Result

    none

If uuser has an owned window attached, LOCK attaches VERIFYs to the window,
which means it cannot be resized. Your scripts should only LOCK a window
for the minimum possible time while drawing commands (@{"GRAB" link grab}, @{"PRINT" link prin}, @{"AREA" link area},
@{"RECTANGLE" link rect}) are taking place. Then, it should call UNLOCK. Your scripts must
not leave windows in a LOCKed state, but must call @{"UNLOCK" link unlo} just as soon as
all drawing commands are complete. If a lot happens between one drawing
command and another, it is best to UNLOCK after the first and LOCK before
the second.

If there is no owned window attached to uuser, LOCK has no effect.

@endnode

@node unlo  "[unlo]    ARexx Command UNLOCK"
@{b}UNLOCK@{ub}          Unlock a window
~~~~~~
Format

    UNLOCK   uuser

Result

    none

Cancels the effect of @{"LOCK" link lock}. UNLOCK must be called just as soon after LOCK
as possible, i.e. immediately all drawing commands are finished. If there
is not an owned window attached to uuser, or if there is but it is already
UNLOCKed, then UNLOCK has no effect.

@endnode

@node icon  "[icon]    ARexx Command ICON"
@{b}ICON@{ub}         Draw an "icon"
~~~~
Format

    ICON  uuser number pena penb xpos ypos

Result

    rc = 0 = ok
    rc = 2 = bad, no window / rastport attached
    rc = 3 = bad, bad parameters

Draws a little icon, from the following list:

    number 0 right arrow } like in scrollers
           1 left arrow  }
           2 up arrow    }
           3 down arrow  }
           4 tick
           5 cross

(The above list will be added to in future releases)

Each icon is width 8 pixels, height 5 pixels. The foreground and background
pens are pena and penb, each 0 to 255. xpos and ypos are the corrdinates of
the top left of the icon, within the current @{"WBOX" link wbox}. If the icon does not fit
in the WBOX it will be trimmed. xpos and ypos can be negative.

@endnode

@node ucom "[ucom]   UcodeSlaves's Simple Unicode Commands"
@{b}UcodeSlave's Simple Unicode Commands@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
These commands create an environment for grabbing glyphs from Ucode's
data files onto a window.

   @{"USET" link uset}   Set ucode_path attributes
   @{"PENS" link pens}   Set pens for GRAB commands
   @{"GRAB" link grab}   Grab a Unicode string to a window

@endnode

@node uset  "[uset]    ARexx Command USET"
@{b}USET@{ub}            set ucode_path attributes
~~~~
Format

    USET uuser height width style weight

Results

    rc = 0 = success
    rc = 2 = bad, invalid / missing nominal height
    rc = 3 = bad, invalid / missing width descriptor
    rc = 4 = bad, invalid / missing style descriptor
    rc = 5 = bad, invalid / missing weight descriptor


When scripts issue @{"REGISTER" link regi} commands, UcodeSlave creates for each uuser
a programming object called a "ucode_path". The ucode_path is quite a
complex and intricate thing, but what is important for now is that it
has 4 "attributes", attributes which you can set with the USET command.

Once you have the attributes you want, you can then issue @{"GRAB" link grab} commands to
put unicode glyphs whose characteristics match those attributes into your
script's windows / rastports.

Here is the meaning of each attribute:

    height      A number from 5 to 31, which is the nominal height of the
                glyph. The actual height can go a little higher, since some
                glyphs (e.g. A circumflex Ĺ) have "diacritical marks" (in
                the case of Ĺ the circumflex is the diacritical mark) above
                them. So, for example, a glyph with nominal height 11
                can have an actual height up to 14.

                Nominal size 11 currently has far more glyphs available than
                other sizes. I suggest you focus on the following sizes:

                 8  (small)
                11  (normal)
                14  }
                17  }
                20  } various levels of headings.
                23  }
                26  }

                But sizes 5-31 are all legal, and hopefully will eventually
                be available. Sizes smaller than 8 are rather unreadable.

    width       A pair of upper case letters (lower case NOT allowed),
                as follows

                   UC ultra-condensed     SE semi-expanded
                   EC extra-condensed     EX expanded
                   CD condensed           EE extra-expanded
                   SC semi-condensed      UE ultra-expanded

    style       A pair of uppercase letters (lower case NOT allowed).
                They can be anything, but these are the "generic" styles:

                   SS sans-serif
                   WS with serif
                   SC script ("italic")
                   TT teletype (fixed width)
                   FA fantasy

                The actual choice is limited, to say the least. So in
                practice, you have SS, and to a very limited extent WS.

                Note the following:

                   - ucode.library can make any glyphs fixed width if
                     required, making TT style somewhat redundant.
                   - ucode.library can "tilt" glyphs, which can be used
                     as a crude subsitute for SC, just like Amiga's
                     graphics.library does.
                   - ucode.library can capture glyphs "on the fly" from any
                     Amiga bitmapped font, so if fonts are available for
                     the language(s) you are working with, you may not
                     need a big range of glyph styles.
                   - styles tend to only have meaning in the glyphs of a
                     particular range of languages that use them rather than
                     "across the board". So grabbing fonts for particular
                     scripts rather than across the board makes more sense.
                   - size 11 is a little too small for CJK glyphs (i.e.
                     Korean / Chinese / Japanese). They have too much
                     detail for size 11, and would be hard to read. So for
                     that reason, I make the so-called size 11 CJK glyphs
                     actually size 14, as if they had diacritical marks. I
                     also do this with various other glyphs (such as
                     dingbats) that are a bit too complex for size 11.


    weight      A number from 1 (lightest) to 9 (blackest). 4 is normal,
                and 7 is "bold".

When ucode.library tries to grab glyphs, if it can't find a file with the
required characteristics in the UCODE: directory, it will search for the
best fit it can find.

When a ucode_path is first formed, it has the following default attributes:

    nominal height     11   (the height for normal printing)
    width descriptor   NM   (normal)
    style descriptor   SS   (sans serif)
    weight descriptor   1   (lightest)

When I make glyph files for a range of unicode values, I always make glyphs
with the above attributes before I make any others.

In more advanced UcodeSlave usage, you will see that ucode.library can
vary the weight, height and width (but not style) of a glyph automatically
(or "algorithmically", to use the correct jargon). But of course doing
so takes time, and the results are never as good as a glyph designed to be
the required size.

Glyphs have "ascenders", i.e. the part above the line, and "descenders", i.e.
the part below the line. In Latin script, the following: g j p q y and maybe
Q normally have descenders. Others may in some styles, e.g. some forms of
f have descenders. Each nominal size has a certain number of pixels allotted
to the descender. e.g. size 11 has 8 for the ascender, and 3 for the
descender.

@endnode

@node pens  "[pens]    ARexx Command PENS"
@{b}PENS@{ub}            set pens
~~~~
Format

     PENS uuser pena penb

Result

     rc = 0 = success
     rc = 2 = bad parameters

pena and penb are the foreground and background pens for uuser's @{"GRAB" link grab}
commands. Their values are 0 to 255, default 1,0.

@endnode

@node grab  "[grab]    ARexx Command GRAB"
@{b}GRAB@{ub}            grab 1 or more Unicode glyphs to a window

Format

    GRAB uuser xpos ypos $1st [cspace [$2nd [$3rd .....

Result

    -rc = total width in pixels



     rc = 2 = no window / rastport attached


xpos and ypos can be -ve. xpos is the leftmost pixel of the 1st glyph.
ypos is the y position of the baseline, @{i}not@{ui} the top of the glyph.

cspace = the number of pixels spacing between glyphs. This is not needed
if only the 1 glyph is to be grabbed.

$1st, and $2nd etc if present, must be in hex notation. A-F in the value
can be a-f. Unicode values almost always have 4 hex digits, though the
the Unicode standard will provides for 8 digit characters (not implemented
in this release).

The glyphs grabbed will have the attributes of the ucode_path which belongs
to the uuser. See USET above for details.

xpos and ypos are relative to the WBOX of the attached window. No rendering
takes place outside the WBOX. If a window / rastport does not have a WBOX,
the entire rastport / window interior is assumed to be the WBOX. See @{"WBOX" link wbox}.

The pens used for rendering are as per the most recent PENS command. The
default pens are 1 0.

If one of the unicode values you specify has no unicode value assigned to
it, or is an unprintable unicode, or I have not yet made a glyph for it,
or the file system is corrupt, then GRAB will show dummy glyphs, analogous
to the way Amiga's graphics.library shows boxes for unprintable ASCIIs.

Strictly speaking, the GRAB command does @{i}not@{ui} print unicode. All it does,
is to print glyphs, each of which has a Unicode associated with it. The
Unicode standard is a lot more than a mere set of glyphs. Nevertheless,
@{b}many users will need no more than the @{"USET" link uset} and GRAB commands to do all
that they might want to do.@{ub}

The elementary usage of the USET command which I have covered so far will
work, but is very slow. So, for best results, see the next node on
"Advanced usage of UcodeSlave's USET command.
@endnode

@node adus "[adus]   Advanced usage of UcodeSlave's uset command"
@{b}Advanced usage of UcodeSlave's @{"USET" link uset} command@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

@{b}XUSET@{ub}       pre-load glyphs into memory; grab from Amiga fonts
@{b}OFONT@{ub}       open an Amiga font
@{b}CFONT@{ub}       close an Amiga font

Format

    XUSET uuser ADD first last
    XUSET uuser SUB first last
    XUSET uuser STYLE width style weight first last
    XUSET uuser FONT first_ascii last_ascii first
    XUSET uuser WARP height width weight
    XUSET uuser WARP CUSTOM height width horz_embold vert_embold
    XUSET uuser DIMS list
    OFONT uuser NAME name.font/size
    OFONT uuser CHOOSE hail
    CFONT uuser


Results

    XUSET         rc = 0  success
                  rc = 2  out of memory
                  rc = 3  XUSET buffer full
                  rc = 4  bad parameters
                  rc = 5  XUSET..FONT, but no font attached

    OFONT         rc = 0  success
                  rc = 2  this uuser already has a font attached
                  rc = 3  can't open diskfont.library
                  rc = 4  can't opened named / chosen font
                  rc = 5  can't open asl.library
                  rc = 6  can't put up requester (out of memory)
                  rc = 7  user cancelled requester
                  rc = 8  bad parameters

    CFONT         rc = 0  success

(If an XUSET executes successfully, that does not mean that the every detail
 of it worked. It may be that some things that were supposed to be loaded
 into memory do not get loaded, for some reason. In that case, everything
 will still work ok, but will be a little slower).

I discussed UcodeSlave's USET command in the @{"Simple Unicode commands" link ucom} node.
Here are some more advanced features of the USET command.

These are important particularly for making UcodeSlave faster.

The key to these is the XUSET command. When a script issues an XUSET
command, it will do nothing right away. Rather, UcodeSlave will store up
the effect of all XUSET commands a uuser might issue. Then, if the uuser
issues a USET command, the USET will execute in such a way as to implement
all the XUSET data which have been stored up. After the USET command, all
that uuser's XUSET commands will then be "discharged" (i.e. forgotten). If
the uuser issues a @{"DEREGISTER" link dere} command while XUSETs are stored up, they will
of course be forgotten, without ever having been used by a USET command.

In order to use XUSET commands wisely, the programmer needs to balance 2
things:

  - memory usage, and
  - speed

Basically, the more glyphs you put in memory, the faster that ucode.library
will operate. But, of course, the more memory that will be taken up.

The glyphs to be added must be of the attributes which the eventual
@{"USET" link uset} sets. If glyphs of those @{i}exact@{ui} attributes cannot be found
on file, then they will be ignored. If your script has added glyphs to
memory with XUSET commands, then they will stay in memory, even if you
use USET to set another set of attributes. They are only "accessible" for
GRAB (or other) commands while the ucode_path has attributes exactly
matching the attributes of the stored glyphs.

Note that the storing in memory is by each uuser for its own use. Glyphs
which one uuser loads will not be available to another uuser. A script could
however send its uuser number to another script to give it access to the
glyphs stored in its ucode_path.


...@{b}Adding glyphs to memory@{ub}...

  XUSET uuser add first last

Adds glyphs first to last to memory. e.g.:

  XUSET uuser ADD 0021 007F
  XUSET uuser ADD 00A1 00FF

These put the Latin-1 glyphs into memory.

n.b. XUSET..ADD  will add glyphs of the attributes being set by the ultimate
USET command, not the ones already set when the XUSET command is received.
If any or all of these glyphs are in memory already, they will not be
loaded again.


...@{b}Remove glyphs from memory@{ub}...

  XUSET uuser SUB first last

Removes glyphs (if any) from first to last from memory. e.g.:

  XUSET uuser SUB 00A1 00FF

will remove glyphs from memory which have the unicodes 00A1 to 00FF.

n.b. XUSET..SUB  will sub glyphs of the attributes being set by the ultimate
USET command, not the ones already set when the XUSET command is received.

It is ok for XUSET..SUB to specify glyphs that are not in memory. But of
course in that case, nothing happens.

Any glyphs still in memory, which have never had XUSET..SUB called for
them, will be removed automatically when your script issues the
DEREGISTER command.


...@{b}Grabbing from alternate files@{ub}...

Your ultimate USET command will specify the characteristics of glyphs which
UcodeSlave must use when it wants to load glyphs. e.g. if your USET issues
the command:

    USET uuser 11 NM SS 1

then UcodeSlave when it looks for glyphs will look in files with the
specified attributes. Now if your script happens to know that for a given
range of unicodes a file exists with some other attributes than these,
it can issue a XUSET command which will load the specified glyphs from
that file, and use them, even though their attributes do not match the
attributes that the USET command sets. The command is:

    XUSET uuser STYLE width style weight first last

The width, style and weight parameters are the same as in the USET command.
The 'first' and 'last' parameters will be the range of Unicodes affected.

Here is an example:

    XUSET uuser STYLE NM SS 4 0530 058F
    USET uuser 11 NM SS 1

0530 - 058F covers the Armenian script. In the above example all other
scripts will be grabbed with weight 1, but Armenian script will be grabbed
with weight 4. Thus for particular ranges any of the width, style or
weight attributes (but not the height attribute) can be varied for
particular ranges of unicode values. Of course, for this to work, files of
glyphs of the required attributes must exist.


...@{b}Grabbing from Amiga fonts@{ub}...

Rather than specifying a "style" attribute, it is better to collect fonts
with styles as required for each script. There are lots available for
the Latin-1 script, but are far less common for other scripts. It is also
worth bearing in mind that ucode.library can "compose" composite glyphs from
the primary glyph + a diacritic mark. For example, from the glyph 0041 (A)
and 0301 (acute), ucode.library can compose 00C1 (A acute).


....@{b}Opening a pre-determined font@{ub}...

First, a font must be opened like this:

    OFONT uuser NAME fontname.font/height

e.g. to open a font named "Topaz/8" (i.e. size 8 in the Topaz font family),
you would issue the command:

    OFONT uuser NAME Topaz.font/8

for which UcodeSlave returns the result  rc = 0  if successful.


....@{b}Opening a font chosen by the user@{ub}...

To do this, issue the command

    OFONT uuser CHOOSE reqhail

for which UcodeSlave returns the result. 'reqhail' is the window name of
the asl font requester.


...@{b}Grabbing from the font@{ub}...

To prepare to grab from the font, issue the command

    XUSET uuser FONT first_ascii last_ascii first

e.g. to grab a Latin-1 font to the corresponding Unicode glyphs

    XUSET uuser FONT 21 7F 0021

Any ASCII value can be grabbed to any Unicode; your script must know how
the font maps its glyphs if it is a non-Latin font, and specify how they
are to be mapped to Unicode glyphs. This may take several XUSETs for each
group of consecutive ASCIIs that map to consecutive Unicodes. The glyphs
from the Amiga font do not get actually grabbed until the eventual USET
is issued. So, if you want to grab from 2 (or more) different fonts, you
would have to OFONT the first, issue XUSET(s) for it, then a USET, then
CFONT for it, and then repeat the process for the 2nd font, &c.

Loading a font glyph into an undefined unicode slot is pointless, since
ucode.library will not print it. The same applies to loading a font glyph
into a unprintable unicode slot.

When grabbed font glyphs are finished with, they may be disposed of by
XUSET..SUB. That is to say, XUSET..ADD glyphs and XUSET..FONT glyphs can
be disposed of in the same way, by using XUSET..SUB before subsequent calls
to USET.



...@{b}Setting Custom Drawing Values@{ub}...

The primary attributes of the ucode_path are its nominal size, width
descriptor, style descriptor, and weight descriptor. However it also
has 11 minor attributes, which are set automatically to default values
each time that USET is called. These 11 minor attributes are:


  xxp_inht  the height in pixels above the baseline of the top of joining
            lines between Indic characters

  xxp_arht  the height in pixels above the baseline of the top of joining
            lines between Arabic characters

  xxp_ijht  the height of Indic joining lines in pixels

  xxp_arht  the height of Arabic joining lines in pixels

  xxp_drwv  the height in pixels of vertical miscellaneous drawing lines
           (e.g. the drawing of enclosing diacritics)

  xxp_drwh  the width in pixels of horizontal miscellaneous drawing lines
           (e.g. the drawing of enclosing diacritics)

  xxp_bohw  the width in pixels of the smear line in algorithmic emboldening

  xxp_bohw  the height in pixels of the smear line in algorithmic emboldening

  xxp_itdx  the dx for algorithmic tilting } tilting angle is ATAN(dx/dy)
                                           } dx can be -32 to +32, but not -1
  xxp_itdy  the dy for algorithmic tilting } dy can be 0 to 64
                                             (if dx or dy = 0, no tilt)

  xxp_iker  the kern in pixels of all diacritical marks that kern with
            their principal characters.


The default values never need changing if no XUSET...FONTs are inserted,
and no warping takes place. If fonts of Arabic or Indic characters are
inserted, you will most likely need to have XUSET...DIMS to specify the
height above the baseline and thickness of joining lines between them.

XUSET...DIMS is followed by a list of up to 11 values, being the above
values in order. Any list items with a value of -1 will be ignored, i.e.
the default value will be unchanged. Only itdx can have a negative value,
and in that case it must not be -1.

Format:

   XUSET uuser DIMS val1 [val2 [val3 ...   <-- up to 11 values

e.g.   XUSET uuser -1 3     sets xxp_arht to 3, leaves others unchanged.



...@{b}What if XUSET..ADD and XUSET..FONT glyphs overlap?@{ub}

If there are already glyphs in memory, neither XUSET..ADD or XUSET..FONT
glyphs will be loaded over the top of them.

If there are XUSET..ADD(s) / XUSET..FONT(s) / XUSET..STYLE(s) for the same
Unicode slots, only the first for each slot will be loaded into memory.

So for example if you want to load XUSET..FONT glyphs over glyphs already
in memory, you must include XUSET..SUB for the glyphs, to remove the old
versions, or else the new versions will not be loaded.


...@{b}What if XUSET..ADD &/or XUSET..FONT conflict with XUSET..SUB?@{ub}

All the XUSET..SUBs are done before the USET is executed, then all the
XUSET..ADDs & XUSET..FONTs are done.


...@{b}Disposing of the font@{ub}...

To dispose of a font, (@{i}after@{ui} USET has been called for its XUSETs!),
issue the command

   CFONT uuser

A uuser must call CFONT before it can call OFONT again. If a uuser never
calls CFONT, calling DEREGISTER automatically calls CFONT if required.

It is not forbidden to call CFONT if no font is currently open. In such a
case, nothing will happen.


...@{b}What if the font has glyphs too big or too small?@{ub}...

If a font's glyphs are too big or too small, USET will still grab them, and
use them as best it can. The result may not be pleasing.

So, in other words, it is your script's responsibility to see that the
font dimensions are reasonably compatible with the height (and perhaps
width and weight) of the attributes being set.


...@{b}Resizing / Emboldening Glyphs@{ub}...

Since glyphs come in potentially 27 different nominal heights, 9 differnt
widths, and 9 different weights, with potentially 65536 glyphs in each,
not to mention extension beyond 0000FFFF, it would be clearly impractical
to have glyphs of all sizes, like bitmapped fonts.

At first the solution seems to be to use outline fonts, but these are not
practical since they are too slow to use "on the fly". But though
algorithmic rescaling of fonts by Amiga's graphics.library is fast, the
results are very poor and it only operates vertically, not horizontally.

For these reasons, ucode.library uses its own algorithmic method, which
operates about 100 times faster than resizing Amiga's outline fonts. It
gives better results than outline fonts for rescaling small glyphs, but not
for big glyphs. It gives its best results over small ranges of resizing. Its
results are faster, and much better than graphics.library's algorithm.
So it seems to me to give the best compromise between speed and beauty.

At the current stage of development ucode.library's method gives really
good results for horizontal scaling and emboldening, but still needs some
improvement for vertical scaling and emboldening. In the next release these
will be improved, without compromising speed. I will also have a system for
stretching just the descenders of characters, and chaning the size ratio
between upper and lower case.

To use resizing, which I call "WARP"ing, use the XUSET...WARP format.

XUSET...WARP operates on glyphs you load with XUSET...ADD commands, which
are resized as they are loaded. It also causes glyphs subsequently grabbed
from files to be resized on the fly. It does @{i}not@{ui} operate on XUSET...STYLE
or XUSET...FONT glyphs.

Here is the usual command format:

   XUSET uuser WARP height width weight

These cause ucode.library to get glyphs with the height, width and weight
specified in the USET command, but to resize & embolden them, so they will
as closely as possible resemble glyphs loaded from a file with height,
width and weight as per the XWARP command.

in XUSET...WARP format:

 height      can be any valid height value, i.e. 5 to 31
 width       can be any any of    UC EC SC NM SE EX EE UE
 weight      can be from 1 to 9

but note that currently, ucode.library can increase or reduce height or
width, but can only increase weight. Thus, if the specified height, width,
weight combination in UCODE...WARP requires lighter actual weight than that
of the USET combination, the weight you get will not be as light as you want.
I propose to fix this in later versions of ucode.library


...@{b}Custom Warping@{ub}...

There is an alternate format for the XUSET...WARP, i.e.:

   XUSET uuser WARP CUSTOM height width horz_embold vert_embold

This allows you to specify a custom set of warping parameters.

height     allows you to specify the number of steps to increase or reduce
           the glyph's actual height. The actual height cannot be reduced
           to less than 5.

width      this is a percentage from 20 to 325 to decrease/increase the
           width of a glyph. Note that a glyph cannot be reduced to a width
           less than 3, or increased to a width more than 48.

horz_weight  this is the number of steps to increase the glyph's horizontal
           weight.

vert_weight  this is the number of steps to increase the glyph's vertical
           weight.

A glyph cannot have a width greater than 48, cannot have an ascender greater
than 54, and cannot have a total height (ascender + descender) greater
than 60. If you input invalid parameters to XWARP...CUSTOM, UcodeSlave will
correct them. If warper parameters are set such that a particular glyph
would become wider than 48 pixels, it will be widened to a width of just 48.


...@{b}What if there are multiple XWARPs?@{ub}...

Your script should send at most 1 XWARP before a USET. If you send more,
then the first one sent will prevail, UcodeSlave will ignore the others.


...@{b}Can a script do other things between sending XUSET / XWARP,and
                sending USET?@{ub}

Yes. The XUSETs / XWARP will have no effect, but just sit in a buffer, until
such times as the uuser sends a USET command (or a DEREGISTER command).


...@{b}IMPORTANT:  The effect of XUSET...WARP on glyph availability@{ub}...

When your script puts glyphs into memory with XUSET...ADD, XUSET...STYLE, or
XUSET...FONT, they stay there, until such times as your script XUSET...SUBs
them, or your script @{"DEREGISTER" link dere}s.

When the glyphs are loaded into the memory buffers, ucode.library stores
them in such a way as to know the following:

  - the attributes that were being USET when the glyph was loaded
    (i.e. the height, width, style and weight)

  - the warper values if any that were being @{"USET" link uset}.

The glyphs will then be available until your script again calls USET. Can
your glyphs be used thereafter? Yes they can - but ONLY if a call is made
to USET which @{i}exactly @{ui} matches the attributes and warper values
that were set when the glyphs were first loaded.


...@{b}Memory Utilisation@{ub}...

When USET implemenets an XUSET...SUB, it clears the memory buffer(s) holding
the SUBbed glyphs. They then become available for other glyphs. As USET adds
glyphs with XUSET...ADD, XUSET...STYLE or XUSET...FONT, it uses up any empty
memory buffers the ucode_path has, and makes new memory buffers as required.
What it does @{i}not@{ui} do, is free memory. So, if USET processes a XUSET...SUB, it
frees up memory buffers for other uses, but does not actually release the
memory.

Thus, if your script temporarily takes up a lot of memory with XUSET...ADD,
etc., is there a way to return that memory back to other scripts / programs,
without issuing a DEREGISTER command?

Yes, there is. The way, is to make a clone of a ucode_path for temporary
use. I will later show you how to do this under @{"CLONE" link clon}. The CLONE
command also has other uses. Each uuser has a ucode_path which it uses, and
which cannot be released until its script issues a DEREGISTER. But as you
will later see, clones can be made and released dynamically.


...@{b}How does it all work?@{ub}...

The ucode_path programming object that UcodeSlave created for each uuser
contains along with its own attributes &c the following embedded programming
objects:

   - a ucode_glyph       a workspace for grabbing glyphs
   - a ucode_rport       a little rastport for getting glyphs into chip
                                                   memory ready for blitting
   - a ucode_list        a list of data files
   - a ucode_blok        a @{i}complex@{ui} memory area for storing glyphs
   - a ucode_group       a file image, used only if editing glyphs
   - a ucode_warper      used for resizing / emboldening glyphs

You don't need to know about these - UcodeSlave is written in such a way
that you don't need to know about ucode.library's internal workings.

@endnode

@node adva "[adva]   Advanced Unicode Commands"
@{b}UcodeSlave's advanced unicode commands@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{"PREMAKE " link prem} Make a ucode_preview
@{"PREVIEW " link prev} Put/append characters to ucode_preview
@{"FORMAT  " link form} Format ucode_preview into lines
@{"PRINT   " link prin} Print next line in ucode_preview
@{"TAGS    " link tags} Set options for PREVIEW/FORMAT/PRINT
@{"CHARSET " link char} Specify the charset for PREVIEW ASCII input
@{"QUERY   " link quer} Get information
@{"PLINE   " link plin} Specify next line to be PRINTed
@{"MOVE    " link move} Re-draw text when a window is resized/scrolled
@{"HILIGHT " link hili} Highlight a range of text
@{"BSCROLL " link bscr} Draw/Monitor ad hoc scrollers on owned windows
@{"SELECT  " link sele} Select a range of PRINTed boxes
@{"COPY    " link copy} Copy SELECTed text to the clipboard
@{"SPREVIEW" link spre} Save the ucode_preview contents
@{"LPREVIEW" link lpre} Load the ucode_preview contents
@{"CLONE   " link clon} Clone the ucode_path


The @{"GRAB" link grab} command simply pokes glyphs onto a window. That is not actually
implementing Unicode, and really that is all that most so-called Unicode
implementations do. But a @{i}true@{ui} Unicode implementation does much
more than that: it must deal properly with the following:

      diacritic marks  (like acute, grave &c)
      under/overlining, strike thrus, &c
      complex rules for bidirectionality
      character forming - e.g. Arabic characters that change shape
      character joining - e.g. Indic language joining characters

along with various other features needed for CSS2 implementation.

For true Unicode implementation, with CSS2 support, the above commands are
used as follows:

1. UcodeSlave requires you to create a programming object called a
   ucode_preview. To do so, you issue the @{"PREMAKE" link prem} command. Once a script
   owns a ucode_preview, it can issue the other commands.

The script will typically want to make a block of text to be displayed.
This is a 3 stage process:

   - preview     when the text is gathered into the ucode_preview
   - format      when the text is formatted into lines
   - print       when the text is printed to a window / rastport

2. @{"PREVIEW" link prev}  adds text to the ucode_preview.

3. @{"FORMAT " link form}  formats the ucode_preview into lines.

4. @{"PRINT  " link prin}  prints the next line of text.

The PREVIEW, FORMAT and PRINT commands can be inter-mingled with each other,
and also with

   @{"TAGS" link tags} commands, to set options for the PREVIEW, FORMAT and PRINT commands.
   @{"USET" link uset} commands, to vary the text attributes in the ucode_preview (i.e. you
        can have various sizes & styles of text in the same ucode_preview)
   @{"WBOX" link wbox} commands, to print text to successive areas in the window.

A ucode_preview is fully self-contained. Once the characters are in it,
ucode.library does not need to look at the glyph files when UcodeSlave
executes FORMAT and PRINT commands on your ucode_preview. Note that PREVIEW
is by far the slowest command to execute - once your ucode_preview has been
made, FORMAT takes negligible time, and PRINT fairly quickly sends each line
to the Amiga's blitter.

In a later node, you will see that a ucode_preview can be saved to disk,
to be re-loaded, FORMATted and PRINTed at a future occasion. This allows
your applications to include reFORMATable unicode "objects" along with
ucode.library, without any need for the distribution to include glyph files.

In a later node, you will see that a script can have clones of its
ucode_path, each with different attributes if desired. This allows calls to
PREVIEW with different clones of ucode_path, thus saving your script from
calling USET all the time. Each clone uses very little extra memory.

@endnode

@node prem  "[prem]    ARexx Command PREMAKE"
@{b}PREMAKE@{ub}        Create a ucode_preview for use by PREVIEW/FORMAT/PRINT
~~~~~~~
Format

     PREMAKE uuser [bytes]

Results:

    rc = 0 = success
    rc = 2 = bad, uuser has already successfully called PREMAKE
    rc = 3 = bad, out of memory
    rc = 4 = bad, bad bytes value (if present, must be >= 10000, <= 1000000)

A ucode_preview uses a lot of memory - it is not designed to hold many pages
of text. The default size is 50000, which would hold maybe a printed page
of text. The minimum allowed size is 10000, and the maximum allowed is
1000000.

@endnode

@node prev  "[prev]    ARexx Command PREVIEW"
@{b}PREVIEW@{ub}                        send input text to the ucode_preview
~~~~~~~
Format

     PREVIEW uuser NEW/ADD AT    $address
     PREVIEW uuser NEW/ADD STR   string
     PREVIEW uuser NEW/ADD FILE  path
     PREVIEW uuser NEW/ADD PASTE path

Results

     rc = 0 = success
          2 = bad, no ucode_preview exists for this uuser
          3 = bad, xxp_spcx/xxp_spcy kaput. This would be caused by your
              disk drive being kaput, or (more likely) by your sending bad
              attributes to  @{"USET" link uset} command.
          4 = bad, out of memory
          5 = bad, bad parameters (bad command format)
          6 = bad, can't open FILE/PASTE path
          7 = bad, PASTE file is garbled, or not IFF


Your script must call @{"PREMAKE" link prem} successfully before it can call PREVIEW.
If you are calling PREVIEW for the first time since you called PREMAKE,
NEW or ADD will be treated the same.

The first parameter can be NEW, which removes the previous contents of
the ucode_preview, and then inserts the text you supply. Or, the first
parameter can be ADD, in which case the text you supply will be appended to
the text already in the ucode_preview.

After NEW/ADD, the third parameter can be AT, in which case an address must
follow in hex. UcodeSlave will then expect to find text at that address.

Or, the third parameter can be STR, in which case the text (if any) after
STR will be inserted into the ucode_preview.

Or, the third parameter can be FILE, in which case the path (file name) of
the file must follow. UcodeSlave will read bytes from the file into the
ucode_preview. The file would simply be a file full of strings in the format
set by the TAGS command.

Or, the third parameter can be PASTE, in which case the path (file name) of
the file must follow. UcodeSlave will read bytes from the file into the
ucode_preview. The file must be in IFF format. UcodeSlave will seek any
UT16 chunks in the file, and read them into the ucode_preview. The COPY
command creates files with UT16 chunks.

The filepaths supplied with PREVIEW...FILE/PASTE can be absolute, or
relative to UcodeSlave's CD, which presumably would be the directory where
the script is run from.

It is much quicker, and more memory efficient, to send all text with one
PREVIEW call, rather than in many PREVIEW calls.


...@{b}What format should the supplied text be?@{ub}...

By default, the supplied text is in "ASCII" format. That means, that it is
in normal ISO-8859-1 Latin-1 text. See under @{"TAGS" link tags} for other formats.


...@{b}See under @{"TAGS" link tags}!!@{ub}...

There is *much* more about the capabilities of the PREVIEW command under
the TAGS command. To get the most from the PREVIEW command, you must study
all the TAGS command options carefully.


...@{b}TAGS and PREVIEW...PASTE@{ub}

Not all TAGS apply in the case of PREVIEW...PASTE. This is because UT16
chunks are always in Latin-1, always UTF16, always forced ltr direction,
and never have embedded Escs or HTML things.

@endnode

@node form  "[form]    ARexx Command FORMAT"
@{b}FORMAT@{ub}                 format a ucode_preview into lines
~~~~~~
Format

     FORMAT uuser line_width [1st_line]

Results

     rc = -n = success, -n is the minimum line spacing required for even
               spacing of all lines so that there is at least 1 clear pixel
               between all lines
           2 = uuser has not successfully called @{"PREMAKE" link prem}
           3 = uuser has not successfully called @{"PREVIEW" link prev}
           4 = can't have 1st_line unless FORMAT already successfully
               called since last PREVIEW
           5 = bad parameters (bad command syntax)
           6 = out of memory

line_width   the width in pixels which lines are divided into. Must not
             be zero. If a character box is more than the line width, it
             will be placed alone on a line. FORMAT does not split words
             apart when it sorts the character boxes into lines, unless
             the words are too long to fit. FORMAT may split lines at
             soft hyphen characters, unless you tell it (in TAGS) not to.

1st_line     This is only relevent if you are re-calling FORMAT. If you
             are calling FORMAT for the first time since you last called
             PREVIEW, then you must either omit 1st_line or make
             1st_line = 0. When you specify first_line, FORMAT leaves all
             lines before 1st_line alone, and starts re-formatting from
             1st_line. In this way, you can have lines of different lengths,
             e.g. for @{"PRINT" link prin}ing in different @{"WBOX" link wbox}s. You can also specify
             different @{"TAGS" link tags} values between calls to FORMAT.

@endnode

@node prin  "[prin]    ARexx Command PRINT"
@{b}PRINT@{ub}          Print next line of FORMATted ucode_preview contents
~~~~~
Format

     PRINT uuser xpos ypos [line_number]

Results

    -rc = n = success, n = the height of the line printed + 1. If the last
              line had already been printed, rc = 0
     rc = 2 = bad, uuser has not successfully called @{"PREMAKE" link prem}
     rc = 2 = bad, uuser has not successfully called @{"FORMAT" link form}

Before a uuser can call PRINT, it must call @{"FORMAT" link form}. If a uuser calls @{"PREVIEW" link prev}
one or more times after calling FORMAT, it must again call FORMAT before it
can call PRINT.

PRINT prints the next line of text, or the requested line_number if supplied.
Just like the @{"GRAB" link grab} command, PRINT prints relative to the operative WBOX
(see @{"WBOX" link wbox}). The ypos is the position of the top of the line's
line box, not its baseline. ypos is relative to the top of the @{"WBOX" link wbox}. xpos is
relative to the left of the WBOX. xpos and/or ypos can be negative.

If your script wants to have evenly spaced lines, it should remember the
return code from FORMAT, and bump ypos by minus that amount every time. If
it wants to squeeze the lines closer together, it can add minus the PRINT
return code to ypos each time. When PRINT returns 0, it means that all lines
were already printed. If it returns 1, then the line was completely blank.

After you call FORMAT, the next time you call PRINT you'll get 0. Then the
next call to PRINT you'll get line 1, etc. You can however PRINT (say)
line 6 by supplying line_number = 6, (then if you again called PRINT you'd
get line 7, etc.). If you supply an non-existent line_number, PRINT will
place the ucode_preview at the end of the last line, not print anything,
and return with rc = 0.

Note that the @{"QUERY" link quer} command allows you to find out information about the
lines in uuser's ucode_preview.

@endnode

@node tags  "[tags]    ARexx Command TAGS"
@{b}TAGS@{ub}              Set options for PREVIEW/FORMAT/PRINT commands
~~~~

Format

     TAGS uuser tag params [tag params] .....

Results

     rc = 0 = success
     rc = 2 = bad, unrecognised tag name
     rc = 3 = bad, bad tag parameter value
     rc = 4 = bad, uuser has never successfully called @{"PREMAKE" link prem}


The list of TAGS below may seem bewildering at first, but you should make
yourself familiar with all the TAGS to get the most out of @{"PREVIEW" link prev}/@{"FORMAT" link form}/
@{"PRINT" link prin} calls.


After ..TAGS uuser.. come 1 or more tag + parameter(s) pairs, as per (a) to
(I) below. @{"(a) to (z)" link "tags"38} refer to PREVIEW; @{"(A) to (C)" link "tags"261} to PRINT; and @{"(D) to (F)" link "tags"274}
to PREVIEW/FORMAT/PRINT collectively.



(a) DFLT    (no parameter)    restore all defaults
    All TAGS are set back to their default values

If 'DFLT' occurs as a tag name (without parameters), it sets all tags to
their default values. But if DFLT occurs as a parameter value, it sets only
the tag it follows to its default value.

The next few options cause @{"PREVIEW" link prev} to stop processing an input string if
various things happen. If all are NO (the default), PREVIEW continues until
it finds a null delimiter in the input string. You can set any combination
of them to YES.

__@{b} Tags which apply to PREVIEW @{ub}__

(b) WSPQ  YES / NO / DFLT     Stop if white space other than 0020 found in
    input string.  Default NO

(c) SPCQ  YES / NO / DFLT     Stop if 0020 found in input string. Default NO

(d) SHYQ  YES / NO / DFLT     Stop if 00AD (soft hyphen) found in input
    string.  Default NO

(e) ALLQ  YES / NO / DFLT     Stop if anything other than a spacing
    character or diacritical mark found in input string.  Default NO

(f) ADRQ  $address / NONE / DFLT    If the parameter is an address (in hex),
    stop if that address reached in input string. If NONE, do not stop
    at any address.  Default NONE

(g) EOLQ  YES / NO / DFLT     Stop if 000A or 000D or 2028 found in input
    string.  Default NO

(h) EOPQ  YES / NO / DFLT     Stop if 000C or 000F or 2029 found in input
    string.  Default NO

(i) BOXQ  NONE / number / DFLT     Causes PREVIEW to stop once a number of
    boxes have been made. If NONE, there is no limit.  Default NONE.

(j) TABQ  YES / NO / DFLT     Stop if 0009 (tab) found in input string.
    Default NO.


(k) BIDI  LTR / RTL / AUTO / DFLT    If LTR, forces PREVIEW to make all text
    left to right, whereas RTL forces right to left. But if AUTO, the
    Unicode bidirectionality algorithm will apply. And boy, was the Unicode
    bidi algorithm hard to program.  Default AUTO

(l) FIXW  NONE / #1 - #48 / $unicode / DFLT   If NONE, PREVIEW makes char-
    acter boxes of variable width, e.g. M is wider than I. If the parameter
    is #1 to #48, then the width is that many pixels. If the parameter is a
    Unicode (in hex), then the width of that Unicode character will be the
    fixed width. If FIXW applies, character boxes will still have the
    operative CSPC after them. Joined characters like Arabic and Devanagari
    will still have their joins.  Default NONE

(m) SMLC  YES / NO / DFLT    If you specify NO, then letters a to z will
    appear normally. But if you specify YES, they will shaped as A to Z, but
    the height of lower case letters. This is called "small caps" style.
    I have included this option to assist in implementing CSS2. Default NO

(n) OLDN  YES / NO / DFLT    If you specify NO, then number 0 to 9 will
    appear normally, i.e. sitting on the baseline. But if you specify YES,
    they will be shaped differently, for better appearance when they
    appear in text. For lists and tables, specify NO; for numbers in
    running text, specify YES.  Default NO

(o) DCOM  YES / NO / DFLT    If you specify NO, then Unicodes which have
    built-in diacritic marks such as Ĺ (A circumflex, Unicode 00C2) will
    be printed as per their glyphs. But if you specify YES, the character
    will be printed in 2 (or more) steps, the character first, and then its
    diacritic mark(s) added. This gives better-looking and much more
    readable results, especially for small characters.  Default YES

(p) FMAT  ASCII / UTF8 / UTF16 / DFLT
    By default, PREVIEW expects you to input characters in ASCII format.
    That is, all characters are in the range 00 to FF. But you can also
    input in UTF-8 format, or UTF-16 format.

    Default ASCII.

    See also the @{"FORMAT" link form} command (for transformation of "ASCII" into
    heritage encoding schemes like Latin-2, Shift-JIS, and many others).

(q) BIBF 0 - 15 / DFLT     The initial (brought forward) value for N1 in
    the Unicode bidi calculation.  Default 0

(r) WHIT $unicode / DFLT   If EMBD has NOWHITE set, all sequences of white
    space in the input string are replaced by a single character. WHIT's
    parameter may be the Unicode (in hex) of the replacement character.
    Default 0020

(s) MIRR YES / NO / DFLT   If Yes, Preview replaces quote character
    201C by 201D, and 201D by 201F, if they parse as bidi RTL. The Unicode
    standard is unclear about whether this should happen. Note that if an
    LTR embeds quote characters around an RTL quote, @{i}the quote  characters
    parse as LTR.@{ui} And vice versa.  Default YES.

(t) EMBD  {ESCS TAGS AMPS NOWHITE} /DFLT    The parameter(s) can be either
    DFLT (when none of the options apply), or any combination of ESCS, TAGS,
    AMPS, and NOWHITE. If any of these apply, they affect PREVIEW's
    processing of the input string as follows:

    (i) ESCS    The Unicode standard says that an implementation can process
        Esc sequences however it wishes. Here is what ucode.library does:

        - if an Esc (001B) character occurs, it will assume an embedded
          Amiga escape sequence is occuring (see devices/printer.i in the
          Amiga includes). In all cases, it will skip the escape sequence.
          If there is not a valid Amiga Esc sequence after the Esc,
          TLUpreview will skip 1 character after the Esc.

        - if EMBD...ESCS is currently set, TLUpreview will process the
          following escape sequences:

          aSGR3  (i.e. Esc[3m)   begin italicising
          aSGR23 (i.e. Esc[23m)  stop italicising
          aSGR1  (i.e. Esc[1m)   begin emboldening
          aSGR22 (i.e. Esc[22m)  end emboldening
          EscD                   send a line feed

          EscD will send a linefeed even if NOWHITE is operative, so it
          operates like a <BR> tag.

          The effect of "italicising" will depend on the @{"ITCL" link "tags"239} tag, which
          see below. The effect may also depend on the @{"XUSET...DIMS" link adus}
          command, if applicable.

          The effect of "emboldening" will depend on the @{"BOCL" link "tags"245} tag, which
          see below. The effect may also depend on the @{"XUSET...DIMS" link adus}
          command, if applicable.

          @{b}Special (private) Esc sequences@{ub}
          If EMBD...ESCS is operative, ucode.library allows you to put the
          following non-standard Esc sequences into the text:

          EscE     begin italicising - same effect as aSGR3
          EscF     end italicising   - same effect as aSGR23
          Esc4     begin emboldening - same effect as aSGR1
          Esc5     end italicising   - same effect as aSGR22

          EscU2,n  force n to be the foreground pen
          EscU1    cancel the effect of EscU2
          EscU4,n  force n to be the background pen
          EscU3    cancel the effect of EscU4
          EscU6    force this & subsequent lines to be full justified
          EscU7    same as EscU6, except lines followed by blank lines
          EscU8    force this & subsequent lines to be right justified
          EscU9    force this & subsequent lines to be centred
          EscU10   force this & subsequent lines to be left justified
          EscU5    cancel the effect of EscU6 - EscU10
          EscU11,n force use of language table n (see @{"CHARSET" link char})
          EscU20   cancel the effect of Esc11
          EscU13   force text direction LTR
          EscU14   force text direction RTL
          EscU12   cancel the effect of EscU13 - EscU14
          EscU16   force small capitals off
          EscU17   force small capitals on
          EscU15   cancel the effect of EscU16 - EscU17
          EscU19,n force fixed width printing on/off
                   n = 1 - 31 = fixed width 1 to 31; n = 0 = not fixed width
          EscU18   cancel the effect of EscU19

          The special (private) Esc sequences should not (of course) be used
          in data exchanged with applications which do not use ucode.library

          As you can see, the CtrlU's  temporarily override the effect of
          various tags.


       (ii) if EMBD...AMPS is currently set, PREVIEW will not take literally
          any ampersand it finds, but instead it will treat it as if it
          were an ampersand in an HTML4.0 page. So, for example:

             &alpha;    produces a lower case alpha (03B1)
             &#65;      produces A  (0041)
             &#x41;     produces A  (0041)
             &#X41;     produces A  (0041)

          also, if AMPS if operative, PREVIEW will always stop processing an
          input string if it finds a '<'  (less than). To input & or <
          the input can have &amp; or &lt; as you would expect. If you use
          &#0; to input a null, it will not cause PREVIEW to stop processing
          the input; the null will simply be skipped. But any other null
          in the input string will make PREVIEW stop processing it at that
          point.

       (iii) if EMBD...TAGS is currently set, PREVIEW will process the
          folowing tags, provided they do @{i}not@{ui} have attributes:

             <B> or <EM>     start emboldening    }
             <I>             start italicising    } These are case blind,
             </B> or </EM>   stop emboldening     } so you can have <i>,
             </I>            stop italicising     } <br>, etc.
             <BR>            send a linefeed      }

           But any other tags, or even the above if they have attributes,
           will cause PREVIEW to stop processing the input string at the '<'.
           For the effect of <B> or <I>, see under ESCS above.

       (iv) if EMBD...NOWHITE is currently operative, then all sequences of
           one or more whitespace characters will be replaced by a single
           space character, normally 0020 (see WHIT above).

           Whitespace is defined in the Unicode book. It includes all space
           characters and line feeds, but not 00A0 (non-breaking space). It
           also includes 0009 (tab). (Do NOT use &nbsp; for line formatting).

(u) ITAL  YES / NO / DFLT    If YES, forces all characters to be Italic.
    Default NO.

(v) BOLD  YES / NO /DFLT     If yes, forces all characters to be bold.
    Default NO.

(w) ITCL 0 to 63 / DFLT     Specifies a "clone" to be used for italicising.
    If you have a specially prepared italic font, you can use XUSET to set
    it in a clone, and specify the clone number with ITCL. See the @{"CLONE" link clon}
    command for details. If you specify DFLT, ITCL is inoperative, and
    PREVIEW uses algorithmic italicising (i.e. tilting).  Default -1 = none.

(x) BOCL 0 to 63 / DFLT     Operates for emboldening just like ITCL
    operates for italicising.  Default -1 = none, i.e. algorithmic.

(y) CLON 0 to 63 / DFLT     Specifies which "clone" to be used for getting
    non-bold, non-italic glyphs. Default -1 = use current @{"CLONE" link clon}.

(z) BOIT 0 to 63 / DFLT     Operates for bold+italic just like ITCL and
    BOCL do for bold/italic alone. Default -1 = none, i.e. algorithmic.

    If ITCL is set, but no BOIT, then the ITCL font is emboldened algo-
    rithmically. If BOCL is set, but not BOIC, then the BOCL font is
    tilted algorithmically.


__ @{b} Tags which apply to@{ub} @{"PRINT" link prin}__

(A) CPEN fg bg / DFLT       The foreground and background pens. Default 1 0

(B) UPEN pn                 The pen for underlines / strike thrus. Default 1

(C) JAMM 1 / 2 / COMP / INVERSE / DFLT     The jam type to send text to
    the currently attached window / rastport. Default 2, i.e. Jam2, prints
    foreground and background. You can also have 1, i.e. Jam1, COMP, i.e.
    complement existing characters underneath the blit, or INVERSE, to print
    with fg and bg pens reversed.  Default 1 (i.e. Jam1).


__ @{b} Tags which apply to @{"PREVIEW" link prev} / @{"PRINT" link prin} / @{"FORMAT" link form} variously @{ub} __

(D) TILT dx dy max_lhs_lap max_rhs_lap   - applies to FORMAT and PRINT
    dx = -32 to +32, dy = 0 to 64. If dx or dy = 0, no tilt. If you set tilt
    here, the PRINTed line will be tilted. If any character boxes were
    already tilted by PREVIEW, they will be tilted again.

    When a character is tilted, either by PREVIEW or PRINT, it may lap its
    baseline. If the leftmost or rightmost character on a line is tilted,
    PRINT will attempt to space it horizontally as per its baseline. But if
    say the descender (if any) tilts to the left past the baseline, it will
    spill out into the margin. And vice versa for the ascender at the right.
    Normally, this is quite satisfactory provided that there are margins,
    and they are wide enough.

    By default, TILT has max_lhs_lap and max_rhs_lap set to 0, which means
    PRINT does not let any pixels from tilted characters spill into the
    margins. You can use TILT to specify maximum allowed spreading, if you
    have magins into which pixels may spill. This gives a more pleasing
    effect. (In a future version I will also have tags to allow "visual"
    margins and kerning).

    Even if you specify 0 for dx and dy in TILT (which you generally will),
    you should still specify non-zero max_lhs_lap and max_rhs_lap values
    if possible, so boxes tilted by PREVIEW will spread out ok.

    Note: all tags can be changed in between multiple calls to PREVIEW,
    FORMAT and PRINT. This is one of the strengths of ucode.library.
    However, when a line is FORMATted, and when it is PRINTed, you should
    arrange things so that the TILT tag has parameters the same both when
    FORMAT formats the line, and when PRINT prints it. Else, you may find
    that PRINT clips some pixels off it, or does not justify it correctly.

(E) SHYY  YES / NO DFLT    Applies to FORMAT. If SHYY is set to YES, then
    FORMAT can use soft hyphens when it formats the text boxes into line
    boxes. Else, it will not use soft hyphens.   Default YES.

(F) UNDL  $mask / DFLT                       } apply to PRINT
    UPAT  $p1 $p2 $p3 $p4 $p5 / DFLT         }

    ucode.library can add various underlines to your text when you call
    PRINT. To make underlines operative, you must supply a bitmask
    with UNDL, like this:

    UNDL mask bit 0 strike thru         } e.g. for single underline +
                  1 double underline    } single overline  ...10100 = $14
                  2 double overline     }
                  3 underline           } i.e.  'TAGS' uuser 'UNDL 14'
                  4 overline            }

          default UNDL is 0

    UPAT specifies the pattern for each of the above in order. For solid
    lines FFFF FFFF FFFF FFFF FFFF (the default). For all solid except
    single underline dotted  FFFF FFFF FFFF CCCC FFFF.

(G) TABS  null-delimited-list / DFLT    Applies to FORMAT

    The Unicode book says it "recognises" tabs, but gives no particulars.
    By default, FORMAT has tabs of 64, 128, 192, ....
    You can specify TABS as a list in ascending order, up to 15 values,
    followed by a null delimiter.

    FORMAT will format characters with tabs relative to the start of the
    line. This may or may not be what you want. It a line is LTR, the tabs
    are taken from the end of the line.

    It is not a good idea to have tabs in a line with mixed LTR and RTL.
    In a future release I will have tabs for numbers, that tab to the
    implied decimal point. You could simulate this by packing with leading
    2007 (number space) characters, but I don't recommend that.

    In fact, I don't recommend that you use tabs in unicode text. To lay out
    columns of text, it is much better to use UcodeSlave's WBOX command.
    To lay out columns of numbers, you could use WBOX for the numbers
    with right justify and FIXW, and then WBOX again for the decimal point
    onwards with left justify and FIXW.

(H) JSFY  LEFT / RGHT / CENT / FULL max / FULP max / DFLT
    JSFY applies to FORMAT.

    JSFY allows you to justify a line. If you want to justify lines
    variously, then re-call FORMAT starting at different lines, with JSFY
    set as desired.

    LEFT  means left justify
    RGHT  means right justify   (normal for RTL languages or number columns)
    CENT  means centred
    FULL  means full justify all lines
    FULP  means full justify all lines, except lines followed by blank lines

    FULL and FULP must be followed by a number from 0 to 64, being the
    maxium number of pixels to add to the 0020's in a line for full
    justification. If you specify 0, there is no limit. In general FULP
    gives better-looking paragraphs than FULL. I understand that full
    justification is starting to become old-fashioned.

(I) WSPC  n / DFLT    applies to FORMAT
    WSPC specifies the width of 0020 characters in pixels. FORMAT will also
    add a character space before and after 0020's and all other space
    characters at least half the width of an en. The default is an en.

(J) CSPC  n / DFLT    applies to FORMAT
    CSPC specifies the width in pixels between characters. In fact, the
    requirements for character spacing are quite intricate.  Default 2.

@endnode

@node char  "[char]    ARexx Command CHARSET"
@{b}CHARSET@{ub}                     Specify charset for PREVIEW ASCII input

Format:

     CHARSET uuser code

Result:

     rc = 0 = success
     rc = 2 = bad

If CHARSET fails, you can call @{"UERROR" link uerr} to determine the reason. If you
supply a valid code, it is unlikely to fail.

CHARSET affects input if @{"PREVIEW" link prev}'s @{"FMAT" link "tags"100} is set by the
TAGS command to ASCII. If it is set to UTF16 or UTF8, then there is only
one possible charset, i.e. Unicode, which will ultimately abolish all other
charsets.

By default, if you specify ASCII, then Latin-1 applies. If you specify
0 for the code, then Latin-1 will apply. But if you specify a non-zero
value from the table below, then that charset will apply. Here are the
charsets which you can choose from:

        2 ISO-8859-2      41 GB2312        72 CP1250
        3 ISO-8859-3      42 GB2312_EUC    73 CP1251
        4 ISO-8859-4      44 JIS0212       74 CP1252
        5 ISO-8859-5      45 JIS0212_EUC   75 CP1253
        6 ISO-8859-6      47 KSX1003       76 CP1254
        7 ISO-8859-7      48 Johab         77 CP1255
        8 ISO-8859-8      49 KSX1001       78 CP1256
        9 ISO-8859-9      50 KSX1001_EUC   79 CP1257
       10 ISO-8859-10     54 CP1026        80 CP1258
       11 ISO-8859-11     55 CP500         81 CP874
       13 ISO-8859-13     56 CP875         83 CP932
       14 ISO-8859-14     57 CP437         87 CP936
       15 ISO-8859-15     58 CP737         89 CP949
       22 KOI8-R          59 CP775         91 CP950
       23 ISCII-1         60 CP850         92 CP1006
       24 ISCII-2         61 CP852         93 CP424
       25 ISCII-3         62 CP855         94 CP856
       26 ISCII-4         63 CP857
       27 ISCII-5         64 CP860
       28 ISCII-6         65 CP861
       29 ISCII-7         66 CP862
       30 ISCII-8         67 CP863
       31 ISCII-9         68 CP865
       34 Shift-JIS       69 CP865
       38 GB12345         70 CP866
       39 GB12345_EUC     71 CP869

Caution: not all of these may work properly in this preliminary release.

@endnode

@node quer  "[quer]    ARexx Command QUERY"
@{b}QUERY@{ub}                                               get information

Format:

     QUERY uuser code [secondary_code]

Result:

     -rc = the information requested by the code, and where applicable the
           secondary code (see bolow)

      rc = 2 = bad if code = 9 to 33 and no owned window attached
      rc = 3 = bad parameters
      rc = 4 = bad if code = 26 to 33 and window has no scrollers
      rc = 5 = bad, @{"PREMAKE" link prem} must have been called before QUERY uuser 50-89
      rc = 6 = bad, @{"PREVIEW" link prev} must have been called before QUERY uuser 50-89
      rc = 7 = bad, @{"FORMAT " link form} must have been called before QUERY uuser 60-89
      rc = 8 or 9 - various uses for QUERY uuser 50-89

Codes:

 0  -rc = 0 if UcodeSlave is in @{"UNQUIT" link unqu} mode
    -rc = 1 if UcodeSlave is in @{"QUIT" link quit} mode

 1  -rc = 0 if UcodeSlave is in @{"UNUTRACE" link unut} mode
    -rc = 1 if UcodeSlave is in @{"UTRACE" link utra} WINDOW mode
    -rc = 2 if UcodeSlave is in TRACE FILE mode

 2  -rc = number of uusers currently registered

 3  -rc = 0 number of uusers refreshing

 4  + secondary_code of any uuser
    -rc = 0 no uuser whose number = secondary_code
    -rc = 1 uuser whose number = secondary_code in normal operation
    -rc = 2 uuser whose number = secondary_code waiting for reply
            to @{"IDCMP" link idcm} / @{"SETWINDOW" link setw} with WAIT
    -rc = 3 UcodeSlave waiting for @{"BEGINREFRESH" link begi} from uuser whose
            number = secondary_code
    -rc = 4 UcodeSlave waiting for @{"ENDREFRESH" link begi} from uuser whose
            number = secondary_code

 5  -rc = number of windows / rastports

 6  -rc = number of windows / rastports not attached to any uuser

 7  + secondary_code of any window / rastport number
    -rc = 0 if no window/rasport has number = secondary_code
    -rc = 100 if window / rastport whose number = secondary_code is not
            attached to any uuser
    -rc = >0 and <100 if window / rastport whose number = secondary_code
            has uuser number = -rc

 8  -rc = 0 if no window / rastport currently attached to uuser
    -rc > 0 if window / rastport whose number = -rc is attached to uuser

 9  -rc = the number of the attached window / rastport      }
10  -rc = xpos of attached window (0 if rastport)           }
11  -rc = ypos of attached window (0 if rastport)           }
12  -rc = width of attached window / rastport               }
13  -rc = height of attached window / rastport              }  these
14  -rc = internal width of attached window / rastport      }  return
15  -rc = internal height of attached window / rastport     }  rc = 2
16  -rc = foreground pen of attached window / rastport      }  if no
17  -rc = background pen of attached window / rastport      }  window /
18  -rc = xpos of WBOX of attached window / rastport        }     rastport
19  -rc = ypos of WBOX of attached window /rastport         }  attached
20  -rc = width of WBOX of attached window / rastport       }
21  -rc = height of WBOX of attached window / rqastport     }
22  -rc = half the address of the attached window / rastport}
23  -rc = the attached window's IDCMP value (0 if rastport) }
24  -rc = pointer xpos rel to attached window interior + 10000 }
          (c.f. 120/126)(10000 added so always +ve)         }
25  -rc = pointer ypos rel to attached window interior + 10000 }
          (c.f. 121/127)(10000 added so always +ve)         }

26  -rc = horz scroller total     }
27  -rc =               visible   }   These return rc = 4
28  -rc =               top       }   if attached window
29  -rc =               step      }   has no scrollers
30  -rc = vert scroller total     }
31  -rc =               visible   }
32  -rc =               top       }
33  -rc =               step      }

34  -rc = xpos of most recent successful BSCROLL...MONITOR call
35  -rc = ypos of most recent successful BSCROLL...MONITOR call


@{b}ELOAD must have been successfully called for items 36-39, else rc = 2@{ub}

36  -rc = width in pixels of widest glyph in ucode_group
37  -rc = ascender in pixels of glyph with highest ascender in ucode_group
38  -rc = descender in pixels of glyph with lowest descender in ucode_group
39  -rc = 1st unicode in ucode_group


@{b}PREVIEW must have been successfully called for items 40-89, else rc = 5
if PREMAKE not called, 6 if PREVIEW not called@{ub}

40  -rc = boxes in ucode_preview
41  -rc = widest word segment, if can break at soft hyphens } 41-44 not
42  -rc = number of inter-chr spaces in 42                  } yet
43  -rc = widest unbroken word                              } implemented
44  -rc = number of inter-chr spaces in 43                  }
45  -rc = line number of 1st box hilighted
46  -rc = box number of 1st box hilighted
47  -rc = line number of last box hilighted
48  -rc = box number of last box hilighted

(49 unused)


@{b}FORMAT must have been successfully called for items 50-89, else rc = 7
       (FORMAT must have been called after the most recent PREVIEW call)@{ub}

50  -rc = number of lines in ucode_preview
51  -rc = width of widest line
52  -rc = height of highest line
53  -rc = line number of next line to be PRINTed (0+)

(54-59 unused)


60  +secondary_code = output line number (0+), if illegal val rc = 8
    returns rc = 0, sets output line number for codes 61 to 69
    rc = 9 if 61 - 69 called before calling 60. @{b}Every time FORMAT is
    called, 60 must be called before 61-69 can be called.@{ub}

61  -rc = ascender of output line
62  -rc = descender of output line
63  -rc = width of output line
64  -rc = boxes in output line
65  -rc = input line number of 1st box in output line
66  -rc = input character number (0+) of input line num of 1st box in inp ln
67  -rc = xpos where output line last printed (rc = 8 if not yet printed)
68  -rc = ypos where output line last printed (rc = 8 if not yet printed)

(69 unused)


@{b}Whenever@{ub} PREVIEW is called with NEW, the text it sends is given an input
number of 0. When subsequent calls to PREVIEW with ADD are made, the text
each sends is given an input number of 1+. Within each input number, each
individual character is given a character number of 0+, being its address
offset from the beginning of the input which holds it. Note that more than
one "character" may be in an output box (if they are a base character +
diacritic marks). And not all "character"s get character boxes (e.g. 0020's
don't usually get character boxes). Only the base character's box will be
found by 70 or 71, diacritic character's boxes will not be found. If a call
to 70 or 71 fails, and the other was already called, both will become as if
never called.

70  +secondary_code = input number (0+), if illegal val rc = 8
    returns rc = 0, sets input number for codes 72 to 79
71  +secondary_code = character number (0+) in input line, if illegal rc = 8
    returns rc = 0, sets chr number within input line for codes 72 to 79
    (rc = 8 if 72-79 called before calling 70 and 71. Every time FORMAT is
    called, 70 and 71 must be called before 72-79 can be called)

72  -rc = output line (0+) containing input line character
73  -rc = box (0+) in output line containing input line caracter
74  -rc = character box width
75  -rc = character box height
76  -rc = window / rastport number where character box last printed
          (rc = 9 if not yet prnted, rc = 0 if can't find window/rport num)
77  -rc = xpos where character box last printed (rc = 9 if not yet printed)
          If xpos could be -ve, you should include lines like this:
          xpos = -rc
          if ypos > 32767 then ypos = 65536 - ypos
78  -rc = ypos where character box last printed (rc = 9 if not yet printed)
          If ypos could be -ve, you should include lines like this:
          ypos = -rc
          if ypos > 32767 then ypos = 65536 - ypos

(79 unused)


@{b}Whenever FORMAT is called, numbers 80-82 must be called before 83-89 can
be called,@{ub} else rc = 8. The lines below allow you to determine what
character (if any) from a PRINT was clicked, if IDCMP returns -rc = 128.
The idea is to set 80 to the current window, call MOUSE and set 81 and
82 to the xpos and ypos of the mouse. Then, 83 and 84 will return the input
line and character within that input line which was clicked. QUERY will be
able to take account of what WBOX was operative when boxes were printed, and
to allow for clipping, &c. Only character boxes at least partly visible on
the window / rastport can be return by 83-84. You can then find out more
about the clicked character box by using the outputs of 83-84 as inputs to
70-71.

80  +secondary_code = window / rastport number, if illegal rc = 8
    sets window / rastport number for 83-84
81  +secondary_code = xpos within window (0+)
    sets xpos for 83-84  (secondary_code will usually be a mouse xpos)
82  +secondary_code = ypos within window (0+)
    sets ypos for 83-84  (secondary_code will usually be a mouse ypos)

83 -rc = input line number of character whose output box was printed
    such that 80-82 was within where it was printed (rc = 9 if no box was
    printed there).

84 -rc = input character number with input line whose output was printed
    such that 80-82 was within where it was printed (rc = 9 if no box was
    printed there).

(85-89 are not used)


The following codes pertain to the internal contents (attributes) of
the ucode_path object which UcodeSlave creates for each uuser when it
@{"REGISTER" link regi}s.

90  the actual maximum height of glyphs  } These are the actual sizes
91  the maximum glyph ascender           } which pertain to the nominal
92  the maximum glyph descender          } glyph height
93  the nominal glyph height                  }
94  the glyph width descriptor (0-8)          } These data set by
95  the glyph weight descriptor (1-9)         } TLUset
96  the glyph style descriptos ("AA" to "ZZ") }

(97-119 are not used)

The following codes relate to the most recent IDCMP call. 126-127 require
an owned window to be attached (another may have been attached when the
IDCMP call took place!), or else rc = 2. 10000 is added to mousex and mousey
calls to make them always +ve, so deduct 10000 from the values returned.
im_IAddress is halved for the same reason, so double it.

120 the im_MouseX+10000 from the most recent IDCMP
    (c.f. 24 which is the "live" posn)
121 the im_MouseY+10000 from the most recent IDCMP
    (c.f. 25 which is the "live" posn)
122 the im_Qualifier from the most recent IDCMP
123 half the im_IAddress from the most recent IDCMP
124 bits 0-31 of the im_Seconds from the most recent IDCMP
125 bits 0-31 of the im_Micros from the most recent IDCMP
126 the im_MouseX+10000 from the most recent IDCMP, relative to the window
    interior (there must be an owned window attached)
127 the im_MouseY+10000 from the most recent IDCMP, relative to the window
    interior (there must be an owned window attached)

Miscellaneous items...

128 the maximum ascender from the most recent GRAB/CPRINT call
129 the maximum descender from the most recent GRAB/CPRINT call


(130+ are so far not used)

@endnode

@node plin  "[plin]    ARexx Command PLINE"
@{b}PLINE@{ub}    Specify next line number to be PRINTed
~~~~~
Format

  PLINE uuser [lnum]

Results

   rc = 2 = bad, @{"PREMAKE" link prem} not yet called
   rc = 3 = bad, @{"FORMAT " link form} not yet called (or not since most recent @{"PREVIEW" link prev})

or if successful

  -rc = the number of the next line to be @{"PRINT" link prin}ed (0+).


lnum is a line number, from 0 upwards. If lnum is higher than the number
of any line in the ucode_preview, then UcodeSlave will point the
ucode_preview just past the last line, so PRINT will fail next time it is
called.

If PLINE omits lnum, then -rc will be the number of the next line to be
printed, which will be unaltered.


When FORMAT has been called, the ucode_preview is ready to have its lines
PRINTed by successive PRINT calls, starting from line 0. Your script can
however vary the order in which lines are PRINTed. For example, to
re-commence PRINTing from the first line (line 0):

 PLINE uuser 0

@endnode

@node move  "[move]    ARexx Command MOVE"
@{b}MOVE@{ub}     Re-PRINT text after a window is resized / scrolled
~~~~
Format

  MOVE uuser 0                 re-draw window
  MOVE uuser 1                 update window if resized
  MOVE uuser 2 dx dy           scroll window
  MOVE uuser 3 dx dy           scroll WBOX

Results

  rc = 0 = success
  rc = 2 = bad, @{"PREMAKE" link prem} not yet called
  rc = 3 = bad, @{"FORMAT" link form} not yet called (or not since most recent FORMAT call)
  rc = 4 = bad, 0-3 must follow uuser
  rc = 5 = bad, no window / rastport attached

dx and dy refer to the number of pixels to scroll towards the top left in
the horizontal and vertical direction. dx and dy can be negative (to scroll
away from the top left).

When your script makes calls to @{"PRINT" link prin}, your ucode_preview remembers the
window/rastport, window dimensions, @{"WBOX" link wbox}, pens etc. of where each line was
PRINTed.

When your script calls MOVE, there must be a window (or rastport) attached
to the uuser. MOVE will scan the ucode_preview for all lines attached to
that window, and will re-print / refresh / scroll them as required.

@{b}You should always put@{ub} @{"LOCK" link lock} and @{"UNLOCK" link unlo} @{b}before and after the MOVE command,
if it is operating on a re-sizeable window.@{b}


@{b}MOVE 0@{ub}

MOVE 0 simply re-prints all lines which were PRINTed to the attached window.
So if the window contents are kaput, you can re-draw all the text in the
ucode_preview by calling MOVE 0


@{b}MOVE 1@{ub}

You should call MOVE1 whenever a window wants refreshing. Here is what to
do when you get an IDCMP_REFRESHWINDOW from an @{"IDCMP" link idcm} command:

     'beginrefresh' uuser
     'endrefresh' uuser
     'lock' uuser
     'move' uuser 1
     'unlock' uuser

This is the quickest and most reliable way to refresh a window. Between
'lock' and 'unlock' you can also put any @{"RECTANGLE" link rect}, @{"AREA" link area}, etc. commands
required to refresh the window.


@{b}MOVE 2@{ub}

You should call MOVE 2 whenever the entire window is to be scrolled. This
would normally happen when the user moves the window's scrollers.


You need to supply the dx and dy values - the amounts the window scrolls, in
the direction of the top left of the window. (The window's contents scroll
in the opposite direction from the way the scroller moves).


MOVE 2 will scroll the window, re-position the top left of the WBOX's of
all lines PRINTed in the window, and render the parts of lines which have
been exposed by the scrolling.


@{b}MOVE 3@{ub}

You should call MOVE 3 whenever the contents of a @{"WBOX" link wbox} is scrolled. You
must of course have called WBOX to set the WBOX being scrolled. Your script
can use the @{"BSCROLL" link bscr} command to organise the use of scrollers for WBOXs, or
your script can auto-scroll the WBOX. Whenever BSCROLL requests for the
WBOX to be scrolled, you can call MOVE 2 to scroll it.

You need to supply the dx and dy values - the amounts the WBOX scrolls, in
the direction of the top left of the WBOX. (The WBOX's contents scroll
in the opposite direction from the way the scroller moves).

@endnode

@node bscr  "[bscr]  ARexx Command BSCROLL"
@{b}BSCROLL@{ub}  Draw/Monitor ad hoc scrollers on owned windows
~~~~~~~
Format

  BSCROLL uuser VERT/HORZ/BOTH DRAW
  BSCROLL uuser VERT/HORZ/BOTH UPDATE  [xvis xpos] [yvis ypos]
  BSCROLL uuser VERT/HORZ/BOTH MONITOR [xvis xstp xpos] [yvis ystp ypos]

Result

  rc = 2 = bad, bad parameters
  rc = 3 = bad, no owned window attached
  rc = 4 = bad, no @{"WBOX" link wbox} set
  rc = 5 = bad, WBOX too small for scroller(s)

Result, if BSCROLL...DRAW or BSCROLL...UPDATE is successful

  rc = 0 = sucessful

Result, if BSCROLL...MONITOR is successful

  rc = 0 = pointer was not on scrollers
  rc = 1 = no scroller was changed, do not call again
  rc = 2 = horz scroller xpos changed, do not call again
  rc = 3 = vert scroller ypos changed, do not call again
  rc = 4 = horz scroller xpos changed, call again
  rc = 5 = vert scroller ypos changed, call again

BSCROLL allows you to have scrollers for WBOXs. Unlike window scrollers,
the WBOX scrolers drawn by BSCROLL are not BOOPSI objects, but simply
passive areas on the window, and must be monitored as they don't return
messages.

Here's how it works:

1. BSCROLL can only be called for owned windows

2. The owned window must have a @{"WBOX" link wbox} specifially set (other drawing routines
   assume a default of 0,0,10000,10000 if no WBOX is specified).

3. In practice, your script would set a WBOX for the text, and a larger WBOX
   enclosing the text WBOX and the scrollers. You would call WBOX with the
   smaller values before doing things with the text, and then WBOX with the
   larger values when calling BSCROLL.

   Vertical scrollers have width 16 pixels, and a minimum height 36.
   Horizontal scrollers have height 9 pixels, and minimum width 64.
   If there are both vertical and horizontal, minimum width 80.

   So if you have a WBOX for text, set by WBOX uuser x y w h
   Then:

      for a vertical scroller        WBOX uuser x y w+16 h
      for a horizontal scrollwe      WBOX uuser x y w h+9
      for both vert+horz scrollers   WBOX uuser x y w+16 h+9

      a vertical scroller has    ytotal  h-22 pixels
      a horizontal scroller has  xtotal  w-40 pixels

4. The first step is to call BSCROLL...DRAW, which draws the scroller(s),
   but without its slider.

5. Then, given ytotal/xtotal in pixels in step 3, calculate ypos/xpos,
   xvisible/yvisible, and xstep/ystep.

   You can then draw the sliders with one of:


      BSCROLL uuser VERT UPDATE yvis ypos
      BSCROLL uuser HORZ UPDATE xvis xpos
      BSCROLL uuser BOTH UPDATE xvis ypos yviz ypos


   Note the following rules apply:

      xtotal >= xvisible + xpos
      ytotal >= yvisible + ypos
      ystep  <= yvisible
      xstep  <= xvisible

6. Your script must then call IDCMP frequently. When it gets a left mouse
   button down event (i.e. -rc = 128), then you must call WBOX if required
   to set the WBOX to that used when it called BSCROLL...DRAW and
   BSCROLL...UPDATE, and then call BSCROLL...MONITOR

   If BSCROLL...MONITOR returns with -rc = 0, then the user is not using the
   scroller. But if -rc > 0, then the script should do the following:

   (a) if -rc was 2   call QUERY...34 to get the new xpos
       then call MOVE...3 with dx = old xpos - new xpos
       then go back to calling @{"IDCMP" link idcm}


   (b) if -rc was 3   call QUERY...35 to get the new xpos
       then call MOVE...3 with dy = old ypos - new ypos
       then go back to calling IDCMP


   (c) if -rc was 4, then as per (a), but instead of going back to
       IDCMP, keep calling BSCROLL...MONITOR until it stops returning -rc=4

   (d) if -rc was 5, then as per (b), but instead of going back to
       IDCMP, keep calling BSCROLL...MONITOR until it stops returning -rc=5


7. You may also wish to respond to the arrows with movements of
   the scrollers & scrolling. The arrows would change xpos/ypos by xstep/
   ystep. Use BSCROLL...UPDATE to update the scrollers, and @{"MOVE" link move}...3 to
   scroll the WBOX.


This sounds rather complex, but it is actually quite straight forward.
Nearly all programs for displaying info (such as UcodeSlave is designed for)
get into a loop of waiting for keyboard and mouse inputs. When a left
mouse button down event (a click) is received, the program would retrieve
the pointer position at the time of the click, and then look through all
the things on the window to check what got clicked. As part of this process,
the script can call BSCROLL...MONITOR. If it returns -rc = 0, then go on
looking for what was clicked. If it returns -rc > 0, then the item clicked
is found, so then your script acts accordingly by using MOVE...3 to scroll
the WBOX's contents until the user releases the left mouse button.

If text is on a borrowed window, you cannot use BSCROLL to monitor it, but
presumably your script will call something equivalent to do so. Your script
can then call MOVE...3 to scroll the WBOX on the borrowed window.

UcodeSlave has a primitive GUI do do things with its owned windows. BSCROLL
is part of this. But with borrowed windows, UcodeSlave only renders to
windows, but does not get messages (IDCMPs) from them.

@endnode

@node hili  "[hili]    ARexx Command HILIGHT"
@{b}HILIGHT@{ub}  Highlight PRINTed text
~~~~~~~
Format

  HILIGHT uuser [line1 box1 line2 box2]

Results

  rc = 0 = success
  rc = 2 = bad, PREMAKE not called
  rc = 3 = bad, FORMAT not called (or not since last PREVIEW call)

line1, box1, line2, box2 are numbered from 0. If the parameters are
omitted, hilighting is switched off. If a box number is more than the
boxes in that line, it will be taken as hilighting to the end of the
line. If a line number is more than the last line, hilighting will be taken
to the end of the text. Hilighting can extend across WBOXs, and even
across windows. Each time HILIGHT is called, any previous HILIGHT is
switched off, as well as switching the new HILIGHT on.

The ucode_preview when formatted has as an attribute a range of boxes to be
hilighted, from line1 box1 to line2 box2 is printed hilighted, that is their
foreground pen, and background pen if JAM2, is printed in a complementary
colour.

For owned windows, the script would normally call @{"SELECT" link sele} instead
of HILIGHT, if the user is selecting text with the mouse. If the equivalent
is happening for borrowed windows, then the script can call HILIGHT to
reflect what is selected so far.

@endnode

@node sele  "[sele]    ARexx Command SELECT"
@{b}SELECT@{ub}   Select a range of PRINTed boxes
~~~~~~
Format

  SELECT uuser [NEW/OLD]

Results

  rc = 2 = bad, no owned window attached
  rc = 3 = bad, @{"PREMAKE" link prem} not yet called
  rc = 4 = bad, @{"FORMAT" link form} not yet called (or not since last @{"PREVIEW" link prev} call)
  rc = 5 = bad, bad command parameters

Or, results if successful

  if NEW and not on a WBOX     returns -rc = 0, and any existing @{"HILIGHT" link hili}
                                 remains

  if NEW and on WBOX but not   returns -rc = 1, and nothing will be
  a character box (chrbox)       HILIGHTed

  if NEW or OLD and selecting  returns -rc = 2
  is continuing

  if NEW or OLD and selecting  returns -rc = 3
  is complete


If NEW/OLD is omitted, NEW is assumed. If SELECT returns with -rc = 2, call
SELECT again with OLD.

If SELECTing is complete (-rc = 3), then call QUERY 45-48 to find line1,
box1, line2, box2 of what is HILIGHTed.

Nearly all programs for displaying info (such as UcodeSlave is designed for)
get into a loop of waiting for keyboard and mouse inputs. When a left
mouse button down event (a click) is received, the program would retrieve
the pointer position at the time of the click, and then look through all
the things on the window to check what got clicked. As part of this process,
the script can call SELECT. If it returns -rc = 0, then go on looking for
what was clicked. If it returns rc > 0, then the item clicked is found.
If -rc = 1, no action is required. If -rc = 2, you must go on calling
SELECT until it returns with -rc = 3. This will result in the text being
highlighted.

If you want to see if the pointer is on a character box without hilighting
it, or you want to see if it is on a character box on a borrowed window,
then, get the pointer xpos,ypos with @{"QUERY" link quer} 120-121 and use QUERY 80-84.

If text is on a borrowed window, you cannot use SELECT to monitor it, but
presumably your script will call something equivalent to do so. Your script
can then call @{"HILIGHT" link hili} to hilight the selected text on the borrowed window.

UcodeSlave has a primitive GUI do do things with its owned windows. SELECT
is part of this. But with borrowed windows, UcodeSlave only renders to
windows, but does not get messages (IDCMPs) from them.

@endnode

@node copy  "[copy]    ARexx Command COPY"
@{b}COPY@{ub}   COPY HILIGHTed text to a file
~~~~
Format

  COPY uuser path

Results

  rc = 0 = Success
  rc = 2 = Bad, @{"PREMAKE" link prem} not called
  rc = 3 = Bad, @{"FORMAT" link form} not called (or not since most recent @{"PREVIEW" link prev} call)
  rc = 4 = Bad, no boxes HILIGHTed
  rc = 5 = Bad, no path supplied
  rc = 6 = bad, can't open file
  rc = 7 = Bad, can't write to file

A range of text must be HILIGHTed (e.g. by the @{"SELECT" link sele} or @{"HILIGHT" link hili} commands)
before COPY will work.

the path is relative to the CD, i.e. presumably the directory where
UcodePath was started from. Normally, though, your script would specify
a path in the CLIPS: directory.

I was a bit puzzled how to save Unicode to the clipboard since I couldn't
find any chunk specs for it. So, I "invented" the UT16 chunk, which
simply consists of:

  'UT16'
  the number of bytes
  UTF16 characters

This is very like the CHAR chunk, which is used for plain chunks of ASCII.

The file which gets saved by COPY puts its UTF16 in forced left-to-right
Unicode plaintext - no formatting information is supplied.

The @{"PREVIEW" link prev}...PASTE command can read files created by a COPY command.

@endnode

@node spre  "[spre]    ARexx Command SPREVIEW"
@{b}SPREVIEW@{ub} Save ucode_preview contents to file
~~~~~~~~
Format

  SPREVIEW uuser path

Results

  rc = 0 = success
  rc = 2 = bad, @{"PREMAKE" link prem} not called
  rc = 3 = bad, @{"PREVIEW" link prev} not called
  rc = 4 = bad, path missing
  rc = 5 = bad, can't open file
  rc = 6 = bad, bad write (file will probably exist, but be empty)


path will be relative to the CD when UcodeSlave is called, i.e. presumably
the directory UCODE:   It is best to give an absolute path.

THe file created can then later be loaded with @{"LPREVIEW" link lpre} and @{"FORMAT" link form}ted
and @{"PRINT" link prin}ed. Note that all glyph information is contained in the
ucode_preview saved, so even if the program that loads it does not have
the same glyph files in UCODE:U0000, or if it doesn't have any access to
any Amiga fonts that may have been grabbed into the ucode_preview via
XUSET...FONT calls, the program that loads the ucode_preview can still
FORMAT and PRINT it. This makes SPREVIEW...LPREVIEW a useful way to exchange
data between applications.

A further use of SPREVIEW is for displaying large amounts of text. A
ucode_preview is a memory hungry thing, and can only display a few thousand
character boxes before it gets too big. The idea is to divide the text
into pages, and PREVIEW and SPREVIEW each. Then, pages can be LPREVIEWed
into the ucode_box, and FORMATted and PRINTed as required. Note that
FORMAT and PRINT operate much more quickly than PREVIEW.

@endnode

@node lpre  "[lpre]    ARexx Command LPREVIEW"
@{b}LPREVIEW@{ub} Load ucode_preview contents from a file
~~~~~~~~
Format

  LPREVIEW uuser path

Results

  rc = 0 = success
  rc = 2 = bad, @{"PREMAKE" link prem} not called
  rc = 3 = bad, path missing
  rc = 4 = bad, can't open file
  rc = 5 = bad, bad load (hard disk currupt?)
  rc = 6 = bad, file too big to fit in ucode_preview
  rc = 7 = bad, bad file contents (checksum failed)


path will be relative to the CD when UcodeSlave is called, i.e. presumably
the directory UCODE:   It is best to give an absolute path.

A file to be loaded by LPREVIEW must have been saved by @{"SPREVIEW" link spre}. Once
LPREVIEW has been called, the script may then call @{"FORMAT" link form} and @{"PRINT" link prin}.

@endnode

@node clon  "[clon]    ARexx Command CLONE"
@{b}CLONE@{ub}    Clone the ucode_path
~~~~~
Format

  CLONE uuser ADD/SUB/n

Results

  rc = 2 = bad, out of memory
  rc = 3 = bad, can't SUB - no clones exist
  rc = 4 = bad, can't choose n, clone n does not exist
  rc = 5 = bad, ADD/SUB/n missing

Or, if successful

  -rc = clone number (0+) now attached.


When a uuser @{"REGISTER" link regi}s, UcodeSlave makes a ucode_path for that uuser. The
ucode_path is a sort of master programming object, and all calls to
ucode.library make use of it. A ucode_path can spawn copies (clones) of
itself in a linked list. Each clone uses very little memory.

CLONE...ADD adds another clone to the linked list, and attaches that clone
if successful. CLONE...SUB removes a clone from the linked list (along with
any subdisiary objects it contained). If the SUBbed clone was attached to
uuser, then the base ucode_path will be attached. CLONE...n (n is 0+)
attached the nth clone in the linked list to uuser. If n is 0, that will
be the base ucode_path. CLONE...SUB cannot remove the base ucode_path (only
DEREGISTER can do that). Creating a clone does not use any chip memory,
only public memory.

When a clone is created, it will inherit the attributes of the clone that
was attached when CLONE...ADD was called. (But not the @{"XUSET" link adus}...DIMS
attributes, they will be set to default values). But the memory buffers
formed by XUSET...ADD and XUSET...FONT will not be inherited. When the
clone is created, it will start with no subsidiary buffers. The memory
buffers created by XUSET..ADD and XUSET..FONT are not shared by the clones,
they each belong to one clone only, i.e. the clone that was attached when
USET was called.

When you call @{"USET" link uset}, the clone that is currenly attached is the one that gets
@{"USET" link uset}. The other clones are unaffected. So if you call @{"PREVIEW" link prev} or GRAB,
the clone attached will get whatever glyphs are required, and the glyph
attributes will be as per the last time USET was called for that clone.


The uses of clones are as follows:

1. Suppose your script wants to allocate memory by way of @{"XUSET" link adus}...ADD or
   XUSET...FONT temporarily. If you use the base ucode_path, then
   any memory buffers you make remain until you @{"DEREGISTER" link dere}. If you
   XUSET...SUB from them, they are free to be re-used by other XUSET..ADD or
   XUSET..FONT calls, but their memory is not actually freed.

   If you use a clone for XUSET...ADD or XUSET...FONT, then the memory
   buffers created belong to that clone. Those buffers are likewise not
   released simply by XUSET...SUB, but likewise become available for re-use.
   But if you remove the clone with CLONE...SUB, then its memory buffers
   are freed.

2. You can attach a different clone if you want different glyph attributes
   each time you call PREVIEW. This is much quicker than calling USET.

3. You can even switch clones (and hence glyph attributes) from character
   to character when calling PREVIEW, by using special embedded EscU in
   the text - see "Special Esc Sequences".

If your script calls @{"DEREGISTER" link dere}, it automatically SUBs any clones that have
not already been SUBbed.

@endnode

@node cata "[cata]   ARexx Catalog Management Commands"
@{b}ARexx Catalog Management Commands@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

@{"CSTART " link csta} Create the catalog
@{"CCHOOSE" link ccho} Choose which language from a set of disk files
@{"CLANG  " link clan} Set the language of the catalog
@{"CLOAD  " link cloa} Load a diskfile into the catalog
@{"CSHOW  " link csho} Show lines from a catalog in a scroller window
@{"CWRAP  " link cwra} Rewrap lines in a catalog
@{"CPRINT " link cpri} Print a line from a catalog

UcodeSlave's catalog system allows you to load ASCII files in a standard
format into memory, and display them. Although the system can use any ASCII
files at all, it is designed to be used like this:

1. The script expects to find a directory called "catalogs"
2. In the catalogs directory are a series of sub-directories named after
   various languages, e.g.

      catalogs/english
      catalogs/italiano

   etc.

3. Then, within the language directory are files with suffix ".catalog",
   and the same name in each, e.g.

      catalogs/english/sometext.catalog
      catalogs/italiano/sometext.catalog

   with the text translated accordingly.

@{b}Catalog Diskfile format@{ub}

A catalog file can have any text at all which is readable by a plaintext
editor such as C:ED. But for best results, observe these conventions:

1. A line of text beginning with ## is treated as a comment and ignored.
2. A line beginning with ~ is treated as a continuation of the previous
   line.
3. Lines may contain  &....;  items as per HTML4, and to get an ampersand
   character, the line must have &amp;

   e.g. for Greek lower case alpha a line might have

        &alpha;   or   &#X03B1;


You can use a text editor to examine the files:


   UCODE:Catalogs/english/Demo.catalog
   UCODE:Catalogs/italiano/Demo.catalog
   UCODE:Catalogs/greek/Demo.catalog

for examples. As you can see from the greek catalog, typing non-Latin text
in that format is to say the least laborious, so I will as a matter of
urgency to soon bring out a special editor for easily making catalog disk
files.

@endnode

@node csta "[csta]   ARexx CSTART Command"
@{b}CSTART@{ub}    Create the catalog
~~~~~~
Format

    CSTART uuser bufsiz maxlines


Results

    rc = 0 = success
    rc = 2 = bad, CSTART already successfully called
    rc = 3 = bad, bufsize must be 100 to 100000
    rc = 4 = bad, maxlins must be 10 to 10000
    rc = 5 = bad, out of memory


You script must call CSTART before it calls any other catalog routines.

bufsiz is the buffer size - specify a size at least that of the largest
disk file you are likely to @{"CLOAD" link cloa}. (Or, if you plan to load several at once,
at least as big as the total size).

maxlines is the maximum number of lines that you will create by the @{"CWRAP" link cwra}
command, or indirectly by the @{"CSHOW" link csho} command. In general, a tenth of the
bufsize is more than enough.

Your script can only call CSTART once. Once a uuser has called CSTART
successfully, further calls to CSTART will cause an error. CSTART creates
a memory buffer or  bufsiz + (4 * maxlines) + 44  bytes. That memory is
finally released only when the uuser calls @{"DEREGISTER" link dere}.

The memory buffer CSTART creates is a programming object called a
"catalog". Apart from creating it by calling CSTART, your script need not
know about it.


@{b}Can a uuser have more than one catalog?@{ub}

No - once your script has successfully called CSTART, you'll get an error
(rc = 2) if it calls CSTART again.


@{b}Can a catalog be resized?@{ub}

No - its size is fixed. But, you can call @{"CLOAD" link cloa} again and again with it.
CLOAD can even load several disk files at once into the catalog, if it is
big enough.

@endnode

@node ccho "[ccho]   ARexx CCHOOSE Command"
@{b}CCHOOSE@{ub}    Choose which language from a set of disk files
~~~~~~~
Format

   CCHOOSE uuser [AUTO/MANUAL] dir\\\\file


Results

   rc = 0 = no language found for this dir\\\\file, language unchanged

   rc < 0 = -rc languages found, language set to whichever chosen

   rc = 2 = bad, @{"CSTART" link csta} not yet called
   rc = 3 = bad, bad command syntax
   rc = 4 = bad, out of memory
   rc = 5 = bad, can't lock dir part
   rc = 6 = bad, dos.library Examine failed (unlikely)
   rc = 7 = bad, no owned window attached
   rc = 8 = bad, attached window has no scrollers


@{b}dir\\\\file@{ub}

@{b}dir@{ub}  is 0 to 63 characters, being the path of a directory with language
files in it - presumably, that path would end with 'catalogs', though this
is not actually compulsory.

@{b}\\\\@{ub}  represents where language names would fit in the path:
presumably, the language names ('english', 'italiano', etc.) would be
the subdirectories of the @{b}dir@{ub} part.

@{b}file@{ub}  'file' would be the name of an ASCII file sought in each
'language' sub-directory of 'dir'. file would presumably have the suffix
'.catalog'. 'file' must consist of 1 to 63 characters.

For example, consider this command:

    'CCHOOSE' uuser 'MANUAL' 'UCODE:Catalogs\\\\Demo.catalog'

In the above exmample, CCHOOSE would find all sub-directories of the
'UCODE:Catalogs' directory. Suppose it finds:

    UCODE:Catalogs/english/Demo.catalog
    UCODE:Catalogs/italiano/Demo.catalog
    UCODE:Catalogs/greek/Demo.catalog

It would then see if the file 'Demo.catalog' exists in each of these three
directories, and if it does, they become available for selection.


@{b}AUTO or MANUAL@{ub}

(a) If no language is found
    CCHOOSE returns with rc = 0, and the catalog language is unaltered.
    (In that case, a call to @{"CLOAD" link cloa} with the same dir\\\\file would fail).

(b) If 1 language is found
    That one language will be made the catalog language.
    (In that case, a call to CLOAD with the same dir\\\\file would succeed).

(c) If more than 1 language is found

    (i) if the command was ...AUTO

        If the command was AUTO, CCHOOSE looks through the (up to 10)
        languages in the user's Locale preferences starting from the most
        preferred. If a match is found with any of the languages for
        which 'file' exists, and if so, that language becomes the
        catalog language.

        If no such match-up takes place, then CCHOOSE acts as if the
        command was ...MANUAL.


    (ii) if the command was ...MANUAL, or ...AUTO has failed

        CCHOOSE looks to see if there is a currently attached owned window
        with scrollers. If there is not, CCHOOSE returns with an error
        (rc = 6 or 7). But if there is, then CCHOOSE puts all the languages
        in the window, and the user must click one to select it. That
        language becomes the catalog language.


From the above, you will see that there must always be a currently attached
owned window with scrollers if the command is ...MANUAL. If it is AUTO,
there need only be a currently attached window with scrollers if no
automatic match can be found.


@{b}Must 'dir' end with 'Catalog'?@{ub}

No - 'dir' can be any 0 to 63 characters which dos.library can get a shared
lock on.

@{b}Must the sub-dirs of 'dir' be language names?@{ub}

No - they can be any valid directory names.

@{b}Must 'file' be just a file name?@{ub}

No - it can have further sub-directories. e.g.

    UCODE:Catalogs\\\\Foo/Bar.catalog

would be ok.

@{b}Must 'dir' have suffix '.catalog'?@{ub}

No - dir can be any valid 1 to 63 characters of any sub-path ending in a
file name.

@{b}How long does the chosen language stay in the catalog?@{ub}

It stays until your script calls CCHOOSE or @{"CLANG" link clan} or @{"DEREGISTER" link dere}.
(However, if you give a path without a \\\\ in it to @{"CLOAD" link cloa}, then the
catalog's language has no effect.

@endnode

@node clan "[clan]   ARexx CLANG Command"
@{b}CLANG@{ub}    Set the language of the catalog
~~~~~
Format

    CLANG uuser [language]
    CLANG uuser [num]


Results

    rc = 0 = success
    rc = 2 = bad, @{"CSTART" link csta} not yet called

CLANG allows you to set a particular language to the catalog, e.g.:

   'CLANG' uuser 'english'

You can also specify a number from 0 to 9, which refers to the user's
Locale preferences. There can be up to 10 such preferences set. But n.b.
some of these may be null, in which case the catalog's language will be
null (if it is, @{"CLOAD" link cloa} assumes 'english').

e.g.:

   CLANG uuser 0

If the user's Locale preference has the most preferred language as
'italiano', then the catalog is set to 'italiano'.

If both [language] and [num] are omitted, it will be as if '0' were
specified, i.e. the most preferred language.

@endnode

@node cloa "[cloa]   ARexx CLOAD Command"
@{b}CLOAD@{ub}    Load a disk file into the catalog
~~~~~
Format

  CLOAD uuser [NEW/ADD] dir\\\\file
  CLOAD uuser [NEW/ADD] path


Results

  rc <= 0 = success, -rc = number of strings loaded

  rc = 2 = bad, bad command syntax
  rc = 3 = bad, @{"CSTART" link csta} not called
  rc = 4 = bad, malformed dir\\\\file
                (dir must be 0-63 chrs, file must be 1-63 chrs)
  rc = 5 = bad, can't open dir/language/file
  rc = 6 = bad, file is empty
  rc = 7 = bad, file too big to fit in catalog
  rc = 8 = bad, can open but not read dir/language/file


CLOAD loads a diskfile into the catalog. If the command was ...NEW, then
the file loaded will be the only lines in the file. So, if CLOAD...NEW
returns -rc = 7, then the catalog will contain lines 0 to 6.

If the command was ...ADD, then the diskfile will be added to the lines
already there. So, suppose for example there were already lines 0-19 in
the catalog, and if CLOAD...ADD returns 8, then the lines just loaded
will become lines 20-27.

Be sure to read @{"CSTART" link csta} concerning the format of catalog diskfiles. Any
comment lines do not count (and don't get loaded), and lines beginning
with ~ count as part of the line before. Blank lines count as lines.
e.g:


  ## this is a comment              <- not a line
                                    <- line 0
  Hello, world                      <- line 1
                                    <- line 2
  My name is Ken - I am writing a   <- line 3
  ~Unicode implementation.
                                    <- line 4
  My name isn&rsquo;t Fred.         <- line 5


From the above, you can see that "lines" are really actually paragraphs.
So, before displaying them by calling @{"CPRINT" link cpri}, you may want to re-wrap
them by calling @{"CWRAP" link cwra}. If you show them by calling CSHOW, then @{"CSHOW" link csho} calls
CWRAP automatically.

If you call CLOAD with  dir\\\\file  format, is is a good idea to call
CCHOOSE with the same dir\\\\file first, to ensure that the catalog has
a valid language in it (which it will, if @{"CCHOOSE" link ccho} returns with rc < 0).

You can also simply specify a path without any \\\\ in it, to load the
specified file.

The file you load can be in any format at all; but if it is not in the above
standard format, @{"CSHOW" link csho} or @{"CPRINT" link cpri} may not give pleasing results.

If CLOAD...ADD fails, the previous lines in the catalog (if any) will
remain intact. If CLOAD...NEW fails, the catalog will be empty.

@{b}Can you call CLOAD...ADD if the catalog is currently empty?@{ub}

Yes. UcodeSlave does not forbid this. Any lines loaded will be numbered
from 0.

@endnode

@node csho "[csho]   ARexx CSHOW Command"
@{b}CSHOW@{ub}    Show lines from a catalog in a scroller window
~~~~~
Format

    CSHOW uuser first last [CLICK/UNCLICK]


Results

    rc = 0 = success, no line clicked (or UNCLICK)
    rc < 0 = success, -rc - 1 = line number clicked
                      (e.g. if -rc = 5, line 4 clicked)

    rc = 2 = bad, @{"CSTART" link csta} not yet called
    rc = 3 = bad, no owned window attached
    rc = 4 = bad, attached window has no scrollers
    rc = 5 = bad, last line more than the number of lines in the catalog
    rc = 6 = bad, first line > last line
    rc = 7 = bad, bad command syntax


CSHOW is a tremendously useful command. It puts a range of lines on a
window, all wrapped to fit horizontally, and monitors the vertical scroller
and the up and down arrows. If the user resizes the window, CSHOW re-wraps
the lines.

CSHOW exits if the user clicks the clos window gadget, or presses the <Esc>
key. If the command was ...CLICK, it also exits if the user clicks a
line on the window. (If the user clicks the window, but not on a line,
CSHOW does not return).

n.b. The line number returned is the line number in the catalog @{i}before@{ui}
wrapping, not after - this is always what you want. You can use CSHOW for
all sorts of things.

I plan to add all sorts of extensions to CSHOW, but even as it is, it is
tremendously useful.


@{b}Underlining a Character@{ub}

If there is a $005F (underline), it will not be treated as a spacing
character, but will underline the character before it. (If it is at the
start of a line, it will be a spacing character after all).


@{b}Limitation on Line numbers@{ub}

When you first call CSTART, you specify a maxlines value. If the value you
specify is too small, then CSHOW can only show that many lines after
wrapping. e.g. suppose your original CSTART was:


  'cstart' uuser 10000 500


and, after calling CLOAD successfully, you issue the command


  'cshow' uuser 0 199


Now if the user makes the window very narrow, the lines as re-wrapped may
become more than 500. If that happens, the last lines become invisible,
until the user makes the window wider again so the number of lines as
wrapped becomes less than 501.

@{b}Not as good as @{"PREVIEW" link prev}...@{"FORMAT" link form}...@{"PRINT" link prin}@{ub}

CSHOW is not as good as PREVIEW...FORMAT...PRINT, since it simply shows a
row of glpyhs, not true unicode with character shaping, etc. I will however
add the ability to shape characters to CSHOW.

So, while CSHOW is somewhat inferior, its beauty is it is so easy to
program. The demos of PREVIEW...FORMAT...PRINT are much more complex to
program than the demos of CSHOW.


@{b}Plans@{ub}

As well as adding character shaping to CSHOW, I plan to add cutting and
pasting, and also pop-up information.

I also plan to implement CSHOW for just a @{"WBOX" link wbox}, as well as the whole
window.

@endnode

@node cwra "[cwra]   ARexx CWRAP Command"
@{b}CWRAP@{ub}    Rewrap lines in a catalog
~~~~~
Format

    CWRAP uuser width first last [cspc] [UND/NUND] [fixt] [ASCI/CSET]

Results

    rc < 0   -rc = number of lines as wrapped

    rc = 2 = bad, @{"CSTART" link csta} not yet called
    rc = 3 = bad, last > number of strings in catalog
    rc = 4 = bad, first string > last string
    rc = 5 = bad, width must be > 0
    rc = 6 = bad, cspace must be < 33
    rc = 7 = bad, UND or NUND expected
    rc = 8 = bad, fixt must be 0 or 1 to 255
    rc = 9 = bad, ASCI or CSET expected


The purpose of CWRAP is to preview a set of lines in the catalog, and
set line starts such that each line fits within a specified width.

What actually happens, is that the the catalog (as well as holding the
CLOADed text) has a set of longwords, which CWRAP sets to point to the
start of where each line will be. Lines are wrapped in accord with the
Unicode line breaking algorithm. Unlike @{"FORMAT" link form}, CWRAP can't handle
conditional hyphens, so the CLOADed text should not contain them. But
CWRAP does handle &nbsp; characters correctly.

CWRAP sets -rc to the number of lines as wrapped, so if -rc is, say, 17,
then you can call @{"CPRINT" link cpri}...WRAP for lines 0 to 17.

@{b}Options@{ub}

(you can't omit an option before one you include)

cspc   i.e. the character spacing in pixels. 0 to 32, default 2.

UND/NUND   If UND, the 005F (underline) characters underline the
       character before them, if there is one. If NUND, 005Fs are treated
       as spacing characters. Default UND.

fixt   If 0, character spacing is proportional. If 1 to 255, characters are
       spaced at that many pixels. (They get clipped if they don't fit).
       Default 0.

ASCI/CSET  If ASCI, the currently operative @{"FORMAT" link form} command has no effect.
       If CSET, characters will be adjusted as per FORMAT. Default ASCI.


The wrapped lines stay in the catalog, until your script calls @{"CSHOW" link csho}, or
@{"CLOAD" link cloa}...NEW, or again calls CWRAP.

@endnode

@node cpri "[cpri]   ARexx CPRINT Command"
@{b}CPRINT@{ub}    Print a line from a catalog
~~~~~~
Format

    CPRINT uuser RAW/WRAP num xpos ypos [cspc] [UND/NUND] [fixt]
                            [ASCI/CSET] [PREVIEW/PRINT]

Results

    rc <= 0 = success, -rc = string width

    rc = 2 = bad, @{"CSTART" link csta} not called
    rc = 3 = bad, bad lnum
    rc = 4 = bad, bad syntax
    rc = 5 = bad, bad parameter value
    rc = 6 = bad, no window attached


Prints a string from the catalog in the attached window or rastport.

'num' is the number of the string - if CPRINT...RAW, num is the string
number (0+) in the strings as CLOADed. But if CPRINT...WRAP, num is the
string number in the wraps from a @{"CWRAP" link cwra}.

In the case of ...RAW, the num must be 0 to the value returned by the most
recent @{"CLOAD" link cloa} - 1, whereas in the case of ...WRAP, the num must be from 0 to
the value returned by the most recent CWRAP - 1.

xpos and ypos are signed values relative to the @{"WBOX" link WBOX} as per @{"About WBOX" link abou}.

@{b}Options@{ub}

(you can't omit an option before one you include)

cspc   i.e. the character spacing in pixels. 0 to 32, default 2.

UND/NUND   If UND, the 005F (underline) characters underline the
       character before them, if there is one. If NUND, 005Fs are treated
       as spacing characters. Default UND.

fixt   If 0, character spacing is proportional. If 1 to 255, characters are
       spaced at that many pixels. (They get clipped if they don't fit).
       Default 0.

ASCI/CSET  If ASCI, the currently operative @{"FORMAT" link form} command has no effect.
       If CSET, characters will be adjusted as per FORMAT. Default ASCI.

PREVIEW/PRINT  If PRINT, printing actually takes place, whereas if PREVIEW,
       CPRINT returns quickly with -rc set to the string width, but no
       actual printing takes place. Default PRINT.


@{b}String Dimensions@{ub}

CPRINT returns the width in pixels in -rc.
Call @{"QUERY" link quer} uuser 128 to get the ascender from the most recent CPRINT.
Call @{"QUERY" link quer} uuser 129 to get the descender from the most recent CPRINT.

@endnode

@node ared "[ared]   ARexx Glyph Editing Commands"
@{b}UcodeSlave Glyph Editing Commands@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Normally, if you wish to edit the glyphs, you will use the GlyphEditor
program. However, UcodeSlave has facilities for you to do editing via
ARexx scripts - this can be useful to do the same operation repetitively.

In order to edit glyphs, the first step is to create a programming object
called a "ucode_group", which is a subsidiary object of the ucode_path
object. the first step in editing will be to call ELOAD, which creates a
ucode_group. Finally, or from time to time, you will also presumably call
ESAVE, which saves the contents of ucode_group to the glyph diskfiles.

  @{"ELOAD  " link eloa}   Load a ucode_group for editing
  @{"ESAVE  " link esav}   Save a ucode_group after editing
  @{"EGRFONT" link egrf}   Grab font glyphs to a ucode_group

(there will be lots more editing commands in the next release)

@endnode

@node eloa  "[eloa]    ARexx Command ELOAD"
@{b}ELOAD@{ub}    Load a ucode_group for editing
~~~~~
Format

   ELOAD uuser $unic

Results

   rc = 0 = success
   rc = 2 = failure  (call @{"UERROR" link uerr} for the reason)


$unic is the first Unicode of the file to be edited. e.g. to edit the file
with Unicodes 0400 - 07FF, $unic would be 0400. $unic can be 0000, 0400,
0800, .... FC00. But the file specified (with attributes matching the
currently USET attributes) must exist, or the ELOAD command will fail.

To edit a glyph file, UcodeSlave requires you to issue an ELOAD command
which loads a file with attributes matching the currently USET attrobutes
into a ucode_group structure. If your script has not issued an ELOAD
command before, then UcodeSlave makes a ucode_group structure, which takes
a lot of memory (385040 bytes), though it only happens once, and for further
ELOAD calls, the same ucode_group gets re-used. The ucode_group memory is
not released until your script issues a DEREGISTER command. (Though if you
use a @{"CLONE" link clon}, and CLONE...SUB the clone, the memory is freed).

@endnode

@node esav  "[esav]    ARexx Command ESAVE"
@{b}ESAVE@{ub}    Save ucode_group as edited
~~~~~
Format

   ESAVE uuser

Results

   rc = 0 = success
   rc = 2 = no ucode_group, or ucode_group was loaded when different
            attributes were USET
   rc = 3 = could not open / write to file  (unlikely)


You must not @{"USET" link uset} different attributes between ELOAD and ESAVE, or ESAVE
will fail. Solution: USET the attributes back to what they were when
ELOAD was called.

@endnode

@node egrf  "[egrf]    ARexx Command EGRFONT"
@{b}EGRFONT@{ub}    Grab glyphs from a font to a ucode_group
~~~~~~~
Format:

   EGRFONT uuser ALL/EMPTY $asc1 $asc2 $unic

Results:

   rc = 0 = success
   rc = 2 = bad parameter values
   rc = 3 = rules for $asc1 and $asc broken (see below)
   rc = 4 = $unic not in ucode_group, of incompatible with $asc1,$asc2
   rc = 5 = no ucode_group exists
   rc = 6 = no font currently open

EGRFONT uses the font currently opened by @{"OFONT" link "adus"164}. It takes the
range of glyphs $asc1 to $asc2 from that font, and puts it in consecutive
unicodes starting with $unic.

$asc1 and $asc2 must both be in either the range 21 to 7E, or A1 to FF.
$asc1 must be <= $asc2
$unic, and $unic + ($asc2 - $asc1), must both be in the ucode_group's
   unicodes (obviously).
@endnode

@node arex "[arex]   Sample ARexx Scripts"
@{b}Sample ARexx Scripts@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
I have written the scripts in such a way as to make it as clear as possible
how they work, rather than for maximum efficiency. Some of them are a bit
half-baked.


@{b}REGISTER DEREGISTER QUIT UNQUIT@{ub}

All demos have the basic framework following, to find UPort, register, do
the script's thing, deregister, and quit:


    if show('P','UPort') then do
        address 'UPort'
        'unquit'
    end

    else do
        address command 'run UCODE:UcodeSlave'
        address command 'WaitForPort UPort'
        address 'UPort'
        'unquit'
    end

    'register'
    uuser = -rc
    if rc < 0 then do


            @{b}(Do whatever the script does)@{ub}


        'deregister' uuser

    end

    'quit'

    exit


@{b}Demo01  - Part 1 - USET@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Demo01 USETs the ucode_path attributes, and sets the pens:

        'uset' uuser 11 NM SS 1
        'pens' uuser 1 0

(Strictly, the above USET is redundant, since it merely USETs the ucode_path
to its default sttributes. 'pens' is also redundant, since the defaults pens
are 1 0).


@{b}Demo01 - Part 2 - WINDOW WNAME@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Now the demo must open a window to put text on. Here are the key lines:

    'window' uuser
    window = -rc
    if window > 0 then do

        'wname' uuser 'UcodeSlave demo 1'


            @{b}Draw on the window, wait for reply@{ub}


        'closewindow' uuser

    end


@{b}Demo01 - Part 3 - LOCK GRAB UNLOCK@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Now the demo draws some unicodes to the window. Here are the key lines:

        'lock' uuser
        'grab' uuser '10 16 0105 4 0181 02A4 03E6 0409 0534 05E6 0633 0906'
        'unlock' uuser

It is advisable to LOCK a window whenever a program does drawing.


@{b}Demo01 - Part 4 - IDCMP BEGINREFRESH ENDREFRESH@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Finally, the demo waits for a response.

Note that IDCMP returns the following values in -rc

        147  =  closewindow
        159  =  refresh

Here are the key lines:

        char = 0
        do until char = 147

            'idcmp' uuser
            char = -rc

            if char = 159 then do

                'beginrefresh' uuser
                'endrefresh' uuser

            end

            if char < 0 then char = 147

        end

Note that if ever IDCMP returns 159 = refreshwindow, a script must send
the following commands:


        BEGINREFRESH

            @{b}0 or more drawing commands@{ub}

        ENDREFRESH


Scripts must send BEGINREFRESH and ENDREFRESH if IDCMP returns -rc = 159,
even if the script does not intend to refresh the window.


@{b}Demo 02 - 13@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~

Demo 02 - 13 are merely demos of UcodeSlave's primitive GUI. UcodeSlave is
really meant for putting Unicode on borrowed windows, however its GUI may
possibly be useful for some purposes.


@{b}Demo02@{ub}  Demo02 puts 2 windows on the screen, and monitors one of
                 them until it receives a closewindow, when it closes both.

@{b}Demo03@{ub}  Demo03 only works if there are 2 screens. It puts a window
                 on each screen, and monitors one of them for a closewindow.

@{b}Demo04@{ub}  The WINDOW command can make either a window, or a rastport.
                 Demo04 makes a window and a rastport, and draws a Unicode
                 glyph on the rastport. It then uses the BLIT command to
                 copy the glyph from the rastport to 2 places on the window.

@{b}Demo05@{ub}  Demo05 puts up 4 windows, and monitors all of them. The
                 key line for doing this is:

                     'setwindow' uuser 'wait' w1 w2 w2 w3

                 where w1, w2, w3 and w4 are the numbers of the 4 windows.
                 When SETWINDOW...WAIT returns a message, UcodeSlave calls

                     'query' uuser 8

                 to see which window sent the mssage.

                 SETWINDOW...WAIT monitors windows in its list, and gets an
                 IDCMP message from the next window to send one. If that
                 message is anything but a closewindow, it puts another
                 Unicode glyph on the window that sent the message. (in
                 order to do that, it dirst has to use AREA to clear the
                 area where the previous glyph was). If the message is
                 a closewindow, it closes the window. When all four windows
                 are clised, the script exists.

@{b}Demo06@{ub}  Demo06 demonstrates the AREA and RECTANGLE commands, for
                 filling an area with a pen, or drawing bevelled or
                 unbevelled boxs.

@{b}Demo07@{ub}  Demo07 demonstrates how to "borrow" a window. In practice,
                 this will be presumably how Amiga applications will use
                 UclodeSlave. An application will send Arexx commands
                 telling UcodeSlave to borrow a window and draw on it.

@{b}Demo08@{ub}  Demo08 is in two parts - Demo08a and Demo08b. These show
                 how one script can time out an IDCMP command sent by
                 another script.

@{b}Demo09@{ub}  Demo09 demonstrates the WMOVE command for moving and
                 resizing windows.

@{b}Demo10@{ub}  Demo10 demonstrates the WFRONT, WBACK, SFRONT and SBACK
                 for moving windows or screen to the front or back.

@{b}Demo11@{ub}  Demo11 demonstraes the SETIDCMP command for changing the
                 IDCMPs that a window can get. In this case, the script
                 adds INTUITICKS, which UcodeSlave's windows don't normally
                 get.

@{b}Demo12@{ub}  Demo12 demonstrates the QUERY command. The QUERY command
                 gets many different sorts of data that a script might
                 want.

@{b}Demo13@{ub}  Demo13 shows how to use QUERY to get the pointer position.


@{b}Demo14@{ub}  WBOX
~~~~~~

Demo 14 demonstrates the WBOX command, for specifying the area within a
window where drawing takes place. It is vital that you should read and
understand @{"About WBOX" link abou} if you are to write UcodeSlave scripts.

The key line of Demo14 is:

        WBOX 20 7 200 90

While WBOX is set to that area, all drawing commands have their xpos and
ypos relative to that area, and no drawing takes place outside that area.

Incidentally, UcodeSlave always knows what size the area inside the window
borders is, i.e. the window interior (WINT), and UcodeSlave always clips
to the WINT automatically, so even if a WBOX is partly or wholly outside the
WINT, no drawing takes place either outside the WBOX, or outside the WINT.


@{b}Demo15@{ub}  SCROLLERS
~~~~~~

Demo15 demonstrates the SCROLLER command. UcodeSlave tries to make it easy
for you to use windows with scrollers. But it's not as easy as all that -
using scrollers properly is perhaps the hardest aspect of UcodeSlave
scripting.

I recommend that you get a printout of Demo15, and study it carefully
until you can fully understand @{i}exactly@{ui} how it works. Then,
self test by trying to write a script yourself to do what Demo15 does.

The really tricky bit is of course to respond correctly when a window gets
resized. There are two basic strategies whwn a window is resized:

   1. Have a fixed sized display, which gets more or less covered or
      uncovered as the window is resized.

   2. Have a variably sized display, which shrinks or expands as the window
      is resized. (It may have a minimum size below which it won't go).

In general, strategy 1 is easier, but strategy 2 is often more pleasing to
the user if you can manage it. Demo15 uses strategy 2. If you were
writing Demo15 yourself, you would find that a particularly challenging
aspect is to re-position the scrollers properly if the window is resized.
Many programs simply take the easy way out and jump the scrollers to the
top left if the window is resized, but it is particularly pleasing to the
user if the scollers stay in their appropriate places after the window is
resized.

This demo does not also respond by moving the scrollers when the user
presses the arrow keys on the keyboard, a feature which many Amiga users
like. This is because I didn't want to make demo15 too hard to understand.
However, you will find that later Demos incorporate this ability.

An application might sometimes use a combination of the above strategies -
for example, in my GlyphViewer program, when the user resizes the
window, the buttons shrink or expand (strategy 2), while the glyphs get
covered or uncovered (strategy 1). This makes the interface particularly
pleasing to the user (I hope).


@{b}Demos 16 - 21@{ub}  Advanced usage of USET  (XUSET)
~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Demos 16 - 21 show how to use XUSET to

 - pre-load commonly used glyphs for faster printing
 - load glyphs from an Amiga font
 - algorithmic resizing and emboldening of glyhps


@{b}Demo22@{ub}   PREMAKE TAGS PREVIEW FORMAT PRINT PLINE
~~~~~~

UcodeSlave gives you complete access to ucode.library routines. So far, I
have covered the GRAB routine, which simply pokes Unicode glyphs onto a
window. But Unicode is much more than a set of glyphs. It involves such
things as diacritical marks, bidirectionality, character shaping, character
joining, and much else besides. ucode.library along with UcodeSlave is
actually a complete Unicode-aware character layout "engine".

My "SampleStrings" program showcases many of the capabilities of the
ucode_preview.

I have already introduced all the aspects of ucode.library's first major
programming object, the @{b}ucode_path@{ub}, which you control mainly with the
USET command.

The second major programming object is the @{b}ucode_preview@{ub}. whereas the
ucode_path is automatically made for you when your script REGISTERs, you
must specifically make a ucode_preview with a PREMAKE command.

Conceptually, using a ucode_preview consists of 3 steps:


   PREVIEW   feed Unicodes into the ucode_preview
   FORMAT    make the ucode_preview arrange itself into lines
   PRINT     make the ucode_preview print one of its lines onto a window


to be a bit more specific, the following are the main commands for using a
ucode_preview:


   PREMAKE   make the ucode_preview
   TAGS      set options for PREVIEW FORMAT PRINT
   PREVIEW   fill ucode_preview with character boxes
   FORMAT    sort ucode_preview character boxes into lines
   PRINT     print the next line of a ucode_preview
   PLINE     jump to another ucode_preview line for next PRINT


Here are the key lines from Demo22


PREMAKE      'premake' uuser 10000
TAGS         'tags' uuser 'DFLT FMAT ascii EMBD ascs amps tags nowhite'
PREVIEW      'preview' uuser 'new str Hello, world!'
FORMAT       'format' uuser 200
PRINT        'print' uuser 10 5
PLINE        'pline' uuser 0


Make sure you understand demo22 before moving on to more complex examples.


@{b}Demos 23 - 28, 30 - 32@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Demos 23 - 28, 30 - 32 introduce features of the ..PREVIEW..FORMAT..PRINT
process as follows:

@{b}Demo23@{ub}   Embedded &...; items

@{b}Demo24@{ub}   Embedded tags
@{b}Demo24a@{ub}  Embedded Escs

@{b}Demo25@{ub}   Bidirectionality

@{b}Demo26@{ub}   Diacritical marks

@{b}Demo27@{ub}   Using QUERY to get information about the ucode_preview

@{b}Demo28@{ub}   Justification

@{b}Demo30@{ub}   Special Esc sequences I

@{b}Demo31@{ub}   Special Esc sequences II

@{b}Demo32@{ub}   Special Esc sequences III


@{b}Demos 29, 42 - 44, 53 - 54@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Demos 29, 42 - 44, 53 - 54 introduce aspects of highlighting / cutting and
pasting.

A series of lines printed from a ucode_preview is object-like. It can be
loaded and saved, reshaped, and a section of it chosen for hilighting or
copying to the clipboard.

ucode_preview printouts are too complex to cut and paste dynamically, but
it is possible to:

  - hilight a range of character boxes
  - choose a range to copy (not cut)
  - copy the range to the clipboard
  - paste what is copied to the clipboard as input to a PREVIEW command.

These Demos introduce aspects of this process

@{b}Demo29@{ub}   HILIGHT - hilight a range of character boxes

@{b}Demo42@{ub}   SELECT  - Selecting text

@{b}Demo43@{ub}   SELECT within a WBOX that auto-scrolls

@{b}Demo44@{ub}   SELECT within a WBOX with a scroller

@{b}Demo53@{ub}   SELECT and COPY

@{b}Demo54@{ub}   PREVIEW...PASTE


@{b}Demos 33 - 41, 45@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Demos 33 - 41, 45 introduce aspects of refreshing / reshaping / scrolling.

A series of lines printed from a ucode_preview is object-like. It can
reprint (refresh) itself, reshape itself (e.g. if a window is resized), or
scroll itself (e.g. if a window or WBOX is scrolled).

These Demos introduce aspects of this process

@{b}Demo33@{ub}  MOVE 0   - redraw

@{b}Demo34@{ub}  MOVE 1   - redraw with a new WINT  (window resized)

@{b}Demo35@{ub}  MOVE 1   - redraw with a new WINT, WBOX (window reorganised)

@{b}Demo36@{ub}  MOVE 2   - scroll all in a window  (widow scrolled)

@{b}Demo37@{ub}  MOVE 1 and MOVE 2 together

@{b}Demo38@{ub}  PICT and MOVE 3  - scroll a WBOX

@{b}Demo39@{ub}  PICT and MOVE 3  - further aspects

@{b}Demo40@{ub}  Scrolling and sizing a window and its WBOX  I

@{b}Demo41@{ub}  Scrolling and sizing a window and its WBOX  II

@{b}Demo45@{ub}  Scrolling and sizinf a window and its WBOX  III


@{b}Clones@{ub}

As I already said, one of the main programming objects controlled by
ucode.library is the ucode_path. When your script REGISTERs, it gets its
very own ucode_path. The basic role of the ucode_path is to supply glyphs
from the Ucode glyph files.

It can be useful to have "clones" of your ucode_path. These share some
internal structures, so each clone uses very little memory. Each clone can
be set to a different set of attributes, which can save time by not making
continual calls to USET. There are other uses of clones also.

These scripts introduce some features of clones:

@{b}Demo46@{ub}  CLONE  I

@{b}Demo47@{ub}  CLONE  II


@{b}Loading and Saving ucode_preview contents@{ub}

A ucode_preview is a self contained thing, so once it has a set of character
boxes, you can save it, and later reload it. The computer or script that
reloads it need not have access to any of the glyph files or fonts that the
script that saved it had. Thus, a saved ucode_preview is a useful way to
port unicode between applications, since an application need only include
a minimal number of files (and no glyph files) in order for any Amiga to
be able to run ucode.library and load and show prviously saved
ucode_previews.


@{b}Demo48a@{ub}   Makes and saves a ucode_preview

@{b}Demo48b@{ub}   Loads and lays out and displays the saved ucode_preview


@{b}The catalog@{ub}

I previously mentioned the main programming objects managed by ucode.library,
i.e. the ucode_path and the ucode_preview.

There is a third programming object that UcodeSlave itself manages, i.e.
a catalog. (See details in the docs for the CSTART command).

(note: in the next release of Ucode I will put the management of the
catalog in ucode.library, and call it a ucode_catalog. But this will make
no difference to existing UcodeSlave commands; PREVIEW will also be able to
get input from ucode_catalogs).

The catalog is a bit more sophisticated than the GRAB command, but much
easier than the ..PREVIEW..FORMAT..PRINT.. commands. Thus, it is a
compromise that many script writers will find just right for their
purpose. In particular the CSHOW command (see Demo56 below) is particularly
easy, yet very powerful.


The details are in the docs for the CSTART command.


@{b}Demo49@{ub}   CSTART  CLOAD  CWRAP  CPRINT

Demo 49 introduces the commands for managing catalogs, and printing their
contents.


@{b}Demo50@{ub}   CSHOW

Demo50 shows how easy the CSHOW is.


@{b}Demo56@{ub}   CCHOOSE

Demo 56 completes the demonstration of the catalog management commands.


@{b}Demos 51 - 52@{ub}   Editing commands

Demos 51 - 52 show the basic process of using UcodeSlave to edit glyph
files. However, so far I haven't written the commands to actually do
anything. The next release of UcodeSlave will have many editing commands.


@{b}Demo 55@{ub}  CHARSET


In some utopian future all pages on the internet will be in UTF8 format
(or perhaps UTF16). At present, nearly all pages are in Latin-1, which is
a subset of Unicode (and 21-7E are in UTF8 format).

For those pages which use non- Latin-1 character sets, there is a large
number of heritage character encodings.

ucode.library can set the xxp_cset attribute of the ucode_path with any
of the heritage charsets.

Demo 55 shows how to use the CHARSET command to set the xxp_cset attribute.

@endnode

@node how3 "[how3]  Calling ucode.library"
@{b}Calling ucode.library@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
These docs sometimes assume that you know things in the docs for
@{"UcodeSlave" link slav}.

  @{"Tutorial for ucode.library      " link tuto}
  @{"Window boxes                    " link wint}
  @{"Autodocs for ucode.library      " link auto}


@{b}The ucode.library Programming Environment@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
ucode.library is a normal Amiga System library which is called the same
way as any other library. However, ucode.library must be able to find
its data files, which must be in a directory pointed to by the assign
UCODE:

Ucode's installer script puts the Ucode directory in the path

    UCODE:

so ucode.library expects to find a drawer named "U0000" in an assign called
"UCODE:", and if it does not, all ucode.library calls will fail. There must
also be a valid (but not necessarily up to date) List file in U0000 - see
@{"UcodeFix" link ufix}.

ucode.library is generally kept at address UCODE:ucode.library, so to open
it you would point A1 to

  uname: DC.B 'UCODE:ucode.library',0

@endnode

@node tuto "[tuto]      How to call ucode.library - a Tutorial"
@{b}How to call ucode.library - a Tutorial@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
This tutorial will refer to sample programs in UCODE:Assembler_stuff.

@{b}UCODE: must exist@{ub}

The assign UCODE: must exist, pointing to a directory Ucode which contains
a valid (but not necessarily up to date) List file in a directory called
UCODE:U0000. Ucode's installer script (Ucode-Install) puts an assign of
UCODE: in your Amiga's S:User-Startup file.


@{b}Must be a process@{ub}

Only a process may use ucode.library - it must NOT be opened by a task
which cannot make dos.library calls.


@{b}Include Files@{ub}

Programs which call ucode.library must have the following INCLUDE files:


    INCLUDE  "UCODE:Includes/ucode.i"
    INCLUDE  "UCODE:Includes/ucodeasms.i"


ucode.i contains the constants required for progams calling ucode.library,
while ucodeasms.i contains the library vector offsets (LVOs).


@{b}Opening ucode.library@{ub}

ucode.library is opened in the usual way. There is a value xxp_uver which
is the version number of ucode.library, which you can use like this:


    uname:  DC.B    'UCODE:ucode.library',0

      .................


            MOVEA.L  _AbsExecBase,A6
            MOVEQ    #xxp_uver,D0
            LEA      uname,A1
            JSR      _LVOOpenLibrary(A6)


@{b}The ucode_path@{ub}

After a process opens ucode.library, the first call is always to TLUstart,
which creates a programming structure called a "ucode_path". The ucode_path
gives your program access to the glyph files. The main attributes of the
ucode_path are: the nominal height; the width; the style; and the weight.
You call TLUset to alter these attributes from their default values.

Nearly all calls to ucode.library (except of course TLUstart) require as a
parameter the ucode_path address returned from a TLUstart call. A
ucode_path can have "clones" which can have different attributes from the
base ucode_path, and can be be used for any calls to ucode.library.

The last call a process would make to ucode.library before closing it would
be TLUfinish, which releases the ucode_path. Your ucode_path tracks all
resouces your task creates by mean of ucode.library calls using that
ucode_path (or its clones). TLUfinish releases all those resources, along
with the ucode_path and its clones if any.


@{b}Just glyphs, or true Unicode@{ub}

For many purposes, you can just use ucode.library to put a string of glyphs
on a window. For this purpose:

     TLUgrabrport    puts a glyph on a window
     TLUstring       puts a string of glyphs on a window

These routines are very easy to use. The GlyphViewer and FontMaker programs
that comes with Ucode merely use the bove.

But for true unicode (with bidirectionality, adding diacritics, character
shaping, etc.) you need to use a programming object called a "ucode_preview".
The SampleStrings program that comes with Ucode makes use of a ucode_preview.


@{b}The ucode_preview@{ub}

To get the most from ucode.library, you need a ucode_preview. First, call
TLUmake to make the ucode_preview. (You never need to specifically release
a ucode_preview - it happens automatically when you call TLUfinish).

Once you have your ucode_preview, and of course the strings of unicode you
want to show, the process is:

     call TLUpreview     to arrange the input into character boxes
     call TLUformat      to sort the character boxes into lines
     call TLUprint       to put each line onto a window

These calls can be interspersed with each other. Each of these three
routines has many options.


@{b}Advanced use of TLUset@{ub}

As well as using TLUset to set ucode_path's main attributes, you can use
TLUset for grabbing glyphs from fonts, and for various ways of optimising
things. TLUset can also direct ucode_path to resize or embolden or tilt
glyphs as it supplies them. You can also use TLUset to pre-load commonly
used glyphs into memory, to make things run faster.


@{b}Charset@{ub}

Ideally, all character data in future would be in UTF8 or UTF16 format.
But in the meantime there are many heritage character encodings. For
example, shift-jis, big5, Latin-2, etc. I have made files with the
essential data for each of these, and you can call

    TLUcharset

to set ucode_path to the charset you want.

ucode_path also understands all the &...; things in HTML4, such as &ldquo;
&rdquo; and the like. You can also embed a range of Esc sequences in your
input, which ucode_path will skip or act upon as required.


@{b}Ucode's window box system@{ub}

You need to be familiar with @{"Window Boxes" link wint} to understand how ucode.library
routines automatically clip and/or scroll things for you.


@{b}Demonstration Programs@{ub}

Here are some demonstration programs which have very full built-in docs.
If you study each in order (along with the autodocs), you will find how to
program ucode.library.


UCODE:Assembler_Stuff/Demo01.a

   Minimal use of ucode.library. Opens a window, puts a glyph on it, and
   waits for the user to click the close window gadget.


UCODE:Assembler_Stuff/Demo02.a

   Calling TLUset; glyph resizing


UCODE:Assembler_Stuff/Demo03.a

   Advanced use of TLUset


UCODE:Assembler_Stuff/Demo04.a

   Dimensioning and printing strings


UCODE:Assembler_Stuff/Demo05.a

   Grabbing glyphs from Amiga fonts


UCODE:Assembler_Stuff/Demo06.a

   First steps in using a ucode_preview
   (Simplified version of Demo08.a)


@{b}There are some subroutines@{ub} in UCODE:Includes, which you can use. Demo07.a,
Demo08.a and Demo09.a make use of these subroutines.


UCODE:Assembler_Stuff/Demo07.a

   The source code for the @{b}GlyphView@{ub} program


UCODE:Assembler_Stuff/Demo08.a

   The source code for the @{b}SampleStrings@{ub} program


UCODE:Assembler_Stuff/Demo09.a

   The source code for the @{b}FontMaker@{ub} program

@endnode

@node wint  "[win]    Window Boxes"
@{b}Window Boxes@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~

@{b}Note@{ub}

It is @{b}essential@{ub} that you understand the information in this node. If you
find it confusing, then it would be a good idea to work through the use
of the ARexx @{"WBOX" link wbox} command in the UCODE:ARexx_Stuff demos.
(There is no "WINT" command in ucode.library's ARexx, since UcodeSlave
works out wints automatically).


@{b}ucode.library's rendering routines@{ub}

  @{"TLUgrbarport" link ugra}
  @{"TLUstring   " link ustr}
  @{"TLUprint    " link upri}

require the following data in their calling registers:

  wint  -  the rastport's owning window's interior dimensions (or the whole
           rastport, if no window owns the rastport)
  wbox  -  the region within the rastport to be rendered to, relative to the
           wint


@{b}The "wint" - Window Interior@{ub}

ucode.library's rendering system uses the "wint" - the area inside a
window's borders, or the entire rastport, if the rastport is not attached
to a window.

A wint is a @{i}pointer@{ui} to a set of 4 words:

  UWORD  the left of the wint, relative to the rastport
  UWORD  the top of the wint, relative to the rastport
  UWORD  the width of the wint  (must be > 0)
  UWORD  the height of the wint (must be > 0)

The rastport is normally attached to a window, so the wint is the window
interior (the area within the window borders) as the window is currently
sized:


          |<---- current window width ---->|

            |<--- current wint width --->|


          +--------------------------------+             -
          |                                |             ^
wint -->  | +----------------------------+ |    -        |
 top      | |                            | |    ^        |
          | |                            | |    |        |
          | |                            | |    |      current
          | |                            | |  current  window
          | |                            | |   wint    height
          | |                            | |  height     |
          | |                            | |    |        |
          | |                            | |    |        |
          | |                            | |    v        |
          | +----------------------------+ |    -        |
          |                                |             v
          +--------------------------------+             -

            ^
            |
            |
           wint
           left


If a rastport is not attached to a window, the wint occupies the entire
rastport, and the wint never changes. But if the rastport is attached to a
window (the usual case), then the wint is the area inside the window
borders, and every time the window is resized, the wint changes.

Assuming a window's address is in A0, here is how you would build its
wint in the stack:

          SUBQ.L   #8,A7
          MOVE.W   wd_Width(A0),4(A7)
          MOVEQ    #0,D0
          MOVE.B   wd_BorderLeft(A0),D0
          MOVE.W   D0,(A7)
          ADD.B    wd_BorderRight(A0),D0
          SUB.W    D0,4(A7)
          MOVE.W   wd_Height(A0),6(A7)
          MOVE.B   wd_BorderTop(A0),D0
          MOVE.W   D0,2(A7)
          ADD.B    wd_BorderBottom(A0),D0
          SUB.W    D0,6(A7)

A wint is deemed to be null if its width = 0, when it will be as if you
supplied 0 for the wint pointer.

ucode.library allows you to supply 0 for a wint pointer. If you do, then
ucode.library assumes a wint equal to the entire rastport size. (Caution:
if you supplied 0 for a wint pointer, it will set wint width to the least of
its BitMap's BytesPerRow * 8, or its BitMap's (Plane1 - Plane0) * 8. To my
knowledge this will always work, but if it mightn't for some reason, don't
set wint to 0.

The top left of a wint will presumably never change, but the width and
height will change as its window is resized.


@{b}The "wbox" - window box@{ub}

ucode.library's rendering system assumes a window's interior is divided up
into 1 or more wboxes (Or the wint might be a sort of window on an imaginary
larger area divided into wboxes).

A wbox is a @{i}pointer@{ui} to a set of 4 words, as follows:

          WORD     the left of the wbox, relative to the wint  (can be -ve)
          WORD     the top of the wbox, relative to the wint   (can be -ve)
          UWORD    the width of the wbox   (must be > 0, < 10001)
          UWORD    the height of the wbox  (must be > 0, < 10001)

Note that the xpos and ypos of the wbox are signed words - the WBOX's xpos
and ypos are relative to the wint, but the wbox need not be within the
wint: it can lap the edges of the wint; or even be entirely outside the
wint.


          +----------------------------+
          |+-------------------------+ |
          ||                         | |<----the window (rastport)
          || +------------------+    | |
          || |                  |    |<------the wint
          || | the wbox         |    | |
          || | (+ve xpos, ypos) |    | |
          || |                  |    | |
          || +------------------+    | |
          |+-------------------------+ |
          +----------------------------+


A wbox is deemed to be null if its width = 0, when it will be as if you
supplied 0 for the wbox pointer.

ucode.library allows you to supply 0 for a wbox pointer. If you do, then
ucode.library assumes the wbox is (0,0,10000,10000), i.e. the entire
window interior, with clipping only to wint, not wbox.

If you do not want to divide the wbox into wboxes, simply supply 0 for the
wbox pointer.


@{b}wboxes can overlap the wint@{ub}

In the diagram below, there is a wbox with a -ve xpos. This is quite
legal, but ucode.library will automatically clip anything drawn to the
wbox, so that nothing appears outside the wint.


          +----------------------------+
          |+-------------------------+ |
          ||                         | |<--- the window (rastport)
      +---++-----------+             | |
      |   ||           |             | |
      |   ||           |<------------------- wbox with -ve xpos
      |   ||           |             | |
      |   ||           |             |<----- the wint
      |   ||           |             | |
      +---++-----------+             | |
          ||                         | |
          |+-------------------------+ |
          +----------------------------+

The wbox can lap the width on any side, or any combination of sides.
ucode.library will always clip whatever is drawn correctly.


@{b}Examples of how text is clipped@{ub}


Suppose @{"TLUprint" link upri} is to draw lines into a wbox.


Here are the lines   ABCDEFGHIJKLM
                     NOPQRSTUVWXYZ


Here is the wbox     +---------------+
                     |               |
                     |               |
                     |               |
                     +---------------+


If xpos is half-way across, and ypos half-way down, ucode.library would
clip it like this:

                     +---------------+
                     |               |
                     |     ABCDEFGHIJ|
                     |     NOPQRSTUVW|
                     +---------------+

If you change xpos and ypos left and down, it might be clipped like this:

                     +---------------+
                     |               |
                     |               |
                     |GHIJKLM        |
                     +---------------+

But suppose the wbox in the second example ovelaps with the wint like this:

              ------------+
                          |
                     +----+----------+
                     |    |          |
                     |    |          |
                     |    |          |
                     +----+----------+
                          |

Then the text gets clipped both to the wint and the wbox, like this:

              ------------+
                          |
                     +----+----------+
                     |    |          |
                     |    |          |
                     |GHIJ|          |
                     +----+----------+
                          |


It might seem a pain to have to include the wint and wbox in all rendering
calls, but ucode.library actually saves you a very large amount of work,
as you never need to check whether things fit.


@{b}Another Example@{ub}

When you call TLUgrabrport/TLUstring/TLUprint, you supply an xpos and ypos
for the print position. The xpos and ypos are relative to the wbox.

So, for example: if the current window size is    600 X 200
The window's wd_BorderLeft,Right,Top,Bottom are   4 16 12 2
Then wint is                                      (4,16,584,182)

Now suppose the wbox is                           (29,11,200,40)
and TLUprint is called with xpos, ypos            23,27


TLUprint, given the above xpos, ypos, wint and xpos...

  ... would place the line at rastport         xpos   4 + 29 + 23
                                               ypos  37 + 11 + 16

  ... would clip any text beyond               xpos   4 + 29 + 23 + (584-1)
                                                 or   600 - (12+1)
                                               ypos  37 + 11 + 16 + (182-1)
                                                 or   200 - (2+1)

All the caller has to do is supply xpos, ypos, wint and wbox. TLUprint
(or whichever other rendering routine) will do all necessary clipping
automatically.


@{b}To sum things up...@{ub}

Provided the wint is set correctly, TLUgrabrport/TLUstring/TLUprint trim
whatever is rendered so that

         - nothing appears outside the wint boundaries
         - nothing appears outside the wbox boundaries

And note again that the xpos, ypos can be -ve, and wbox xpos, ypos can be
-ve. (but wint xpos, ypos must be +ve); also note gain that text can be
partly or entirely outside the wbox, and the wbox can be partly or etirely
outside the wint.


@{b}Responding to Window Resizing and Scrolling@{ub}

A window (or rastport) would only ever have one wint, though that wint
changes in width and height as the window is resized, but the wint's
xpos and ypos would never change.

But your program can place many wboxes in a window, as it lays out the
contents of that window. The width and height of wboxes would normally
either be proportional to the wint width and height (if the window contents
shrink and expand with window resizing), or else the width and height of
all the wboxes would stay constant. If the contents of a window scroll, then
your program would presumably change the xpos &/or ypos of all the wboxes
in concert. If the contents of just one wbox scroll, then the ypos and
xpos of the things rendered in that wbox would presumably change in
concert.

The @{"TLUmove" link umov} routine scrolls the contents of a wbox or a wint
automatically, as well as redrawing wbox contents as required if the window
size (and with it the wint) changes.


@{b}Is it allowed to set a wint smaller than the true wint?@{ub}

Yes.


@{b}Can wboxes overlap?@{ub}

Yes.

But if you call @{"TLUmove" link umov} with wboxes overlapping, the results
may not be pleasing (though it would not crash).


@{b}What if the user resizes a window part-way though rendering?@{ub}

Do not allow that to happen. i.e. set IDCMP verifies, or otherwise lock
the windows while rendering is taking place.


@{b}ClipBlit@{ub}

Nearly all ucode.library's rendering is done by calling graphics.library's
ClipBlit routine. This means that, even if you supply an incorrect wint,
the worst that can happen is that the window's borders can get written
over. Mind you, that's bad enough, but at least it doesn't crash.

@endnode

@node auto "[auto]    Autodocs for ucode.library"
@{b}Autodocs for ucode.library@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
High level routines

@{"TLUstart    " link usta} Make a ucode_path
@{"TLUfinish   " link ufin} Release a ucode_path
@{"TLUset      " link ustt} Set attributes of ucode_path
@{"TLUfindpath " link ufnd} Find best fit / set ucode_warper for a set of attributes
@{"TLUgrabrport" link ugra} Render a glyph to a rastport
@{"TLUdims     " link udim} Get dimensions of a glyph
@{"TLUstring   " link ustr} Render a sting of glyphs to a rastport
@{"TLUbreak    " link ubre} Suggest a breakpoint for TLUstring
@{"TLUsetwarper" link ustw} Set attributes of the ucode_warper
@{"TLUerror    " link uerr} Find why a ucode.library routine failed
@{"TLUmakefont " link umaf} Make an Amiga font from a selection of glyphs
@{"TLUclone    " link uclo} Clone a ucode_path
@{"TLUpop      " link upop} Remove the last clone (if any) of a ucode_path
@{"TLUmake     " link umak} Make a ucode.library programming object
@{"TLUpreview  " link upre} Initialise a ucode_preview
@{"TLUcharset  " link ucha} Select a charset for TLUpreview calls
@{"TLUformat   " link ufor} Format a ucode_preview into lines
@{"TLUprint    " link upri} Print next line of a ucode_preview
@{"TLUsaveprev " link usav} Save the contents of a ucode_preview to a file
@{"TLUloadprev " link uloa} Load a TLUsaveprev'ed file into a ucode_preview
@{"TLUmove     " link umov} Re-draw / re-size / scroll what TLUprint has drawn
@{"TLUhilight  " link uhil} Set a range of boxes in a ucode_preview as hilighted
@{"TLUcopy     " link ucop} Copy TLUhilighted'ed boxes to a file

Primitive routines

@{"TLUpact     " link upac} Change a nominal glyph height into an actual one
@{"TLUpnom     " link upno} Change an actual glyph height into a nominal one
@{"TLUpbas     " link upba} Get the baseline position of glyphs of a given nominal height
@{"TLUpoint    " link upoi} Look up various data tables
@{"TLUgrab     " link upoi} Get a glyph into a ucode_glyph
@{"TLUtransfer " link upoi} Render a ucode_glyph into a rastport
@{"TLUwarp     " link upoi} Warp the contents of a ucode_glyph
@{"TLUsave     " link upoi} Save the contents of a ucode_group to a data file
@{"TLUsavelist " link upoi} Save the FixFonts list

@endnode

@node usta   "[usta]    Autodoc for TLUstart"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUstart@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

   NAME
       TLUstart -- make a ucode_path


   SYNOPSIS
       upath = TLUstart(planes, width, height)
          D0            D0:8   D1:16   D2:16

       APTR TLUstart(UBYTE, ULONG, ULONG)


   FUNCTION

       Nearly all ucode_library calls require a pointer to a ucode_path as
       one of their inputs. TLUstart creates a ucode_path and its internal
       sub-structures, ready for making further ucode.library calls.

       Most applications will specify 0 for each of the inputs.


   INPUTS

     planes  = the bitplanes of a BitMap which will be made and attached to
       a RastPort (i.e. a ucode_rport) inside the ucode_path. planes can be
       1 to 8, or else specify planes = 0 for the same number of bitplanes
       the default public screen (8 if there is no default public screen).
       The memory for the ucode_rport's bitplanes is the only chip memory
       that ucode.library calls ever use.

     width = the width of the ucode_rport. If width = 0, the same as the
       default public screen's width. (640 if no default public screen).
       TLUprint cannot print lines wider than width, and any line which
       would exceed width will be clipped.

     height = the height of the highest character box that is ever to be
       rendered using the ucode_path. This cannot be greater than 128.
       Default = 70, which iv very unlikely to be exceeded.
       diacritics and under/over lines.


   RESULT

     A pointer to the ucode_path created. If TLUstart fails, call @{"TLUerror" link uerr}
     to find out why.


   SEE ALSO

     @{"TLUfinish" link ufin}  @{"TLUerror" link uerr}  @{"TLUset" link ustt}

@endnode

@node ufin  "[ufin]    "Autodoc for TLUfinish"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUfinish@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

   NAME
       TLUfinish -- release a ucode_path


   SYNOPSIS
       TLUfinish(upath)
                 A0

       VOID TLUfinish(APTR)


   FUNCTION
       Frees all the memory of a ucode_path created by @{"TLUstart" link usta}, along with
       any clones it may have had. All the subsidiary structures inside the
       TLUfinish will also be released.


   INPUT
       upath = pointer to a ucode_path created by @{"TLUstart" link usta}


   RESULT
       none


   SEE ALSO
       @{"TLUstart" link usta} @{"TLUclone" link uclo} @{"TLUpop" link upop}

@endnode

@node ustt  "[ustt]    "Autodoc for TLUset"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUset@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

   NAME
       TLUset -- Set attributes of ucode_path


   SYNOPSIS
       TLUset(height, width, style, weight, flags, gunic, upath,
              D0:8    D1:8   D2:16  D3:8    D4     D5     A0

                               blist, klist, flist)
                               A1     A2     A3

       VOID TLUset(UBYTE, UBYTE, UWORD, UBYTE, ULONG, ULONG,
                               APTR, APTR, APTR, APTR)


   FUNCTION
       TLUset sets the main attributes of the ucode_path. When ucode.library
       functions require glyphs, the request for a glyph is handled by the
       ucode_path, which returns glyphs with the attributes set by the most
       recent TLUset. By default, glyphs are loaded from diskfiles, but
       the TLUset call can also arrange for commonly required glyphs of the
       required attributes to be stored in memory for quick retrieval.

       These are the glyph attributes:


         height     a nominal height, from 5 to 31. The actual height can
                    be a little higher (e.g. the actual height of glyphs
                    of nominal height 11 can be up to 14). The nominal
                    height is made up of an ascender (above the baseline),
                    and a descender, below the baseline. (e.g. glyphs of
                    nominal height 11 have ascender 8 and descender 3).

         width      widths are expressed as numbers from 0 to 8, standing
                    for ultra condenseed, extra condendsed, condensed,
                    semi condensed, normal, semi expanded, expanded, extra
                    expanded, and ultra expanded.

         style      style consists of 2 characters from AA to ZZ (must be
                    upper case). These can have any meaning, but the
                    following ar the generic styles

                       SS  sans serif
                       WS  with serif
                       TT  "teletype" - fixed width
                       SC  script (italic)
                       FA  fantasy

         weight     weights vary from 1 to 9, with 4 = normal, 7 = bold.


       In addition to the above attributes, a ucode_path has a subsidiary
       structure called a ucode_warper, which tells the ucode_path to "warp"
       characters as they are supplied. Warping can be vertical or
       horizontal stretching, or horizontal or vertical emboldening.

       There are also some minor attributes of the ucode_path,
       corresponding to the UcodeSlave's @{"XUSET...DIMS" link adus} command.
       There is no ucode.library routine corresponding to the XUSET...DIMS
       command, but rather assembly language programs must poke the values
       directly into the ucode_path's fields after TLUset is called.

       A ucode_path maintains within itself 0 or more linked memory buffers,
       which are used for storing glyphs in memory for quick access. These
       buffers are created as required by TLUset calls, and once a buffer
       exists, the ucode_path does not relinquish that memory until a
       @{"TLUfinish" link ufin} call releases the ucode_path. So, if glyphs are removed,
       the memory buffers which contained them become empty, and available
       for holding other glyphs. The buffers collectively are called the
       ucode_block.

       If glyphs of a certain set of attributes are put in a memory buffer,
       then whenever the ucode_path's attributes are set the same as they
       were when the glyphs were loaded, and the ucode_warper is in the
       same state, then when ucode_path is asked to retrieve those glyphs
       it will retrieve them from the memory buffers rather then files,
       which is quicker (but, of course, takes up memory).

       There can be another memory in the ucode_path, called a ucode_group.
       Once a ucode_group is formed, it is not released until @{"TLUfinish" link ufin}
       releases the ucode_path. When TLUset is called, the ucode_group can
       be made (if it doesn't already exist) and filled (or re-filled) with
       all the glyphs in a glyph file. If ucode_path is required to supply
       a glyph, and the ucode_group contains a version of it matching the
       attributes and ucode_warper is set to null, then the glyph will be
       got from the ucode_group. The ucode_group is only useful for editing
       a glyph file, and for all other purposes it is more memory efficient
       to use the ucode_block to cache glyphs in memory.

       When @{"TLUstart" link usta} creates a ucode_path, it has attributes: height 11,
       width 4, style 'SS', weight 1.

       When ucode_path supplies a glyph, it adopts the following stategy:

         (i)   If the ucode_warper is set to null, it seeks the glyph in
               the ucode_group, if there is one.
         (ii)  It seeks the glyph in the ucode_block among those that were
               loaded when the ucode_path was TLUset to the same attributes
               and ucode_warper values as currently TLUset.
         (iii) It seeks in the glyph files.
         (iv)  If no matching glyph file was found, it changes the requested
               style to SS (if it wasn't already) and tries again.
         (v)   If no matching glyph file was found, it changes the requested
               width to 4, and tries again.
               width to 4, and tries again.
         (vi)  If no matching glyph file was found, it changes the requested
               weight to 1, and tries again.

       If all of the above fails, or a glyph file was found but couldn't be
       loaded (unlikely), then it returns $FFFD.

       If you call TLUset, and supply a flist which involves Indic or Arabic
       characters, a problem may arise. That is, that the height above the
       baseline and thickness of joiners between characters may differ from
       that which will apply to the glyphs in UCODE:U0000. In the ARexx
       command @{"XUSET...DIMS" link adus} command several minor attributes of a
       ucode_path can be specified. When doing assembly programming, you
       will need in the same circumstance to poke values into the following
       fields of the ucode_path after you call TLUset:

          xxp_inht  xxp_ijht  xxp_drwv  xxp_bohw  xxp_itdx  xxp_iker
          xxp_arht  xxp_ajht  xxp_drwh  xxp_bovw  xxp_itdy

       See the UCODE:Includes/ucode.i file for the descriptions of these
       fields in the ucode_path structure. Whenever you call TLUset, it
       fills them with default values. You can then poke other values in
       these fields if you wish.


   INPUTS
       height = nominal height, from 5 to 31      (initially 11)
       width  = width descriptor, from 0 to 8     (initially 4 = normal)
       style  = style descriptor, from AA to ZZ   (initially SS = sans serif)
       weight = weight descriptor, from 1 to 9    (initially 1 = lightest)
       flags  = an OR of any set flags, which can be:

                xxp_lwarp  means use ucode_warper as is. If xxp_lwarp is
                           not set, TLUset will fill the ucode_warper with
                           nulls. Now suppose you call @{"TLUsetwarper" link ustw} to
                           set non-null values in the warper. You should
                           then immediately call TLUset with xxp_lwarp set.
                           xxp_lwarp set. From then until you make the next
                           call to TLUset, all glyphs supplied by ucode_path
                           will be warped as per the ucode_warper.
                xxp_bmake  set if a blist is supplied
                xxp_bkill  set if a klist is supplied
                xxp_fmake  set if a flist is supplied
                xxp_gmake  set if a gunic is supplied

       gunic  = ignored, unless the xxp_gmake flag is set. If it is, then
                gunic is the unicode of any glyph in the glyph file which
                is to be loaded into a ucode_group. Thus, to load the
                file NMSS104, which contains glyphs for unicode 0400 to
                07FF, you could supply gunic 0400.

       upath  = pointer to a ucode_path created by @{"TLUstart" link usta}

       blist  = ignored, unless the xxp_bmake flag is set. If it is, then
                blist points to a list of unicode glyphs to be added to the
                ucode_block, in the following format

                  0 or more records with  byte 0-1 first unicode in range
                                          byte 2-3 last unicode in range
                                                   (or byte 0-3,4-7 if the
                                                   unicodes are surrogates)

                  finally, a 0000 delimiter

                after TLUset is called, the blist can be discarded.

                If any or all of the glyphs in the list are already in the
                ucode_block in the attributes and ucode_warper attributes
                matching those being TLUset, they will not be re-loaded.
                If a record has surrogates, their high surrogate values must
                be the same as each other.

       klist  = ignored, unless the xxp_bkill flag is set. If it is, then
                klist points to a list in the same format as a blist, of
                glyphs to be removed from memory. Only glyphs which were
                loaded when TLUset was called when the same attributes and
                ucode_warper settings were being TLUset, as are now being
                TLUset, will be removed by a klist. If any or all of the
                glyphs in the klist ar not in the ucode_block, then TLUset
                will simply ignore them. Glyphs removed by a klist will
                leave blank memory in the ucode_block's memory buffers,
                which can be used to add blists or flists. If more than 1 of
                klist, blist and klist are supplied, then TLUset does the
                klist first, then the blist, then the flist.

       flist  = ignored, unless the xxp_fmake flag is set. If it is, then
                flist points to a list of unicode glyphs to be added to the
                ucode_block, in the following format

                0 or more sub-flists of two types, which can be
                inter-mingled, as follows:


                either   byte 0-3  the address of a font loaded by
                                   diskfont.library

                         then, 0 or more records as follows

                         byte 0    first ASCII value within the font }not
                         byte 1    last ASCII value within the font  }both 0
                         byte 2-3  first of a block of unicodes which fonts
                                   are to be grabbed to. Or, byte 2-5 if
                                   surrogates. (Dummy glyphs, i.e.
                                   D800-DBFF can be grabbed, but if so, the
                                   0000 delimiter must immediately follow).

                         finally, a 0000 delimiter

                and/or   byte 0-3  the value 00000001

                         then, 0 or more records as follows

                         byte 0-1  An alternative style which is to be
                                   loaded to a ucode_block instead of the
                                   style being TLUset
                         byte 2    An alternate width
                         byte 3    An alternate weight
                         byte 4-5  The first Unicode value bytes 0-3 refer to.
                         byte 6-7  The last unicoe value bytes 0-3 refer to.
                         (If surrogates, the unicode pair is bytes 4-7,8-11)
                         (Dummy glyphs, i.e. D800-DBFF, can be grabbed)

                         finally, a 0000 delimiter

                finally, a 00000000 delimiter, after all sub-fontlists


   RESULT
       none


   SEE ALSO
       @{"TLUsetwarper" link ustw} @{"TLUclone" link uclo} @{"TLUfindpath" link ufnd}

@endnode

@node ufnd  "[ufnd]    Autodoc for TLUfindpath"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUfindpath@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

   NAME
       TLUfindpath -- Find best fit / set ucode_warper, for a set of
                      attributes


   SYNOPSIS
       result = TLUfindpath(height, width, style, weight, flags, gunic,
                            D0:8    D1:8   D2:16  D3:8    D4     D5

                               sunic, upath, blist, klist, flist)
                               D6,    A0     A1     A2     A3

       BOOL TLUfindpath(UBYTE, UBYTE, UWORD, UBYTE, ULONG, ULONG, ULONG,
                                      SPTR, APTR, APTR, APTR);


   FUNCTION
       TLUfindpath has the same inputs as @{"TLUset" link ustt}, along with one extra
       input, i.e. sunic, a sample Unicode value.

       What it does, it seeks the best fit it can, in that it looks for a
       glyph file that contains the sample unicode. If it doesn't find one,
       it returns bad. If it does, it will also set the ucode_warper if
       the match is not a perfect one. It then calls @{"TLUset" link ustt} with the
       parameters and perhaps ucode_warper that it comes up with.

       Unlike @{"TLUset" link ustt}, TLUfindpath can fail, which it does if no file at all
       contains the sample unicode.


   INPUTS
       height  }
       width   }  same as for @{"TLUset" link ustt}
       style   }
       weight  }
       flags   }
       gunic   }
       upath   }
       blist   }
       klist   }
       flist   }

       sunic = sample Unicode - see FUNCTION above


   RESULTS
       result = success/failure boolean


   SEE ALSO
       @{"TLUset" link ustt} @{"TLUsetwarper" link ustw}

@endnode

@node ugra  "[ugra]    Autodoc for TLUgrabrport"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUgrabrport@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

   NAME
       TLUgrabrport -- Render a glyph to a rastport


   SYNOPSIS
       dims = TLUgrabrport(xpos, ypos, wbox, wint, ucode, fpen,  bpen,
       D0                  D0    D1    D2    D3    D4     D5     D6

                            upath, rport)
                            A0     A1

        UWORD TLUgrabrport(WORD, WORD, APTR, APTR, ULONG UBYTE UBYTE,
                            APTR, APTR)


   FUNCTION
       Renders a glyph to a rastport. If rport is attached to a window, then
       it is the caller's responsibility to set IDCMP verifies if
       appropriate.

       xpos, ypos, wbox and wint refer to ucode.library's rendering system.
       See @{"Window Boxes" link wint} for a full explanation.

       ucode.library pokes the glyph onto its own little rastport (i.e.
       ucode_rport), and then uses graphics.library's ClipBlit to blit from
       the ucode_rport to rport. This is how ucode.library does all its
       rendering.

       rport must have a bitmap attached to it (of course).

       A rectangular area exactly equal to the dimensions of the glyph will
       be rendered with the specified pens colours.

       It is possible that everything will work ok, but no output will
       appear on the rastport - that can occur if the Unicode did not
       have a glyph (e.g. 007F has no glyph), or the xpos,ypos and wbox were
       so positioned that the glyph was clipped entirely off the wint.


   INPUTS
       xpos   = the signed x offset from the wbox

       ypos   = the signed y offset from the wbox. The ypos is measured from
                the top of the max ascender of the glyph, so if you render
                several glyphs, their baselines will line up.


       wbox   = a pointer to a structure consisting of 4 words, i.e.
                   a signed word, the xpos of the wbox relative to the wint
                   a signed word, the ypos of the wbox relative to the wint
                   a non-zero unsigned word, the width of the wbox
                   a non-zero unsigned word, the height of the wbox
                if wbox is null, or its width is zero, then wbox will be
                0,0,10000,10000.

       wint   = a pointer to a structure consisting of 4 words, i.e.
                   an unsigned word, being the xpos of the rport interior
                   an unsigned word, being the ypos of the rport interior
                   a non-zero unsigned word, being the rport interior height
                   a non-zero unsigned word, being the rport interior width
                if wint is null, or its width is zero, then ucode.library
                will assume 0,0,width,height where width and height are
                the dimensions of the rastport's bitmap.

       ucode  = the Unicode of the glyph to be rendered.

       fpen   = the foreground pen

       bpen   = the bckground pen

       upath  = pointer to a ucode_path created by @{"TLUstart" link usta}

       rport  = a RastPort (which must have a bitmap atached)


   RESULT
       dims   = 0 if TLUgrabrport could not grab a glyph for that Unicode,
                or that Unicode was undefined. If dims is non-zero, then it
                contains the following data about the glyph:

                     bit 0-7    width
                         8-15   ascender
                         16-23  descender
                         24-30  baseline  (relative to ypos)
                         31     1         (returns $80000000 if glyph null)


   SEE ALSO
       @{"TLUdims" link udim} @{"TLUstring" link ustr}

@endnode

@node udim  "[udim]    Autodoc for TLUdims"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUdims@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

   NAME
       TLUdims -- Get the dimensions of a glyph


   SYNOPSIS
       dims = TLUdims(ucode, upath)
       D0             A0     A0

       ULONG TLUdims(ULONG, APTR);


   FUNCTION
       Returns the dimensions of the glyph, without rendering it. TLUdims
       operates very quickly.


   INPUTS
       ucode = the unicode of the glyph to be examined

       upath  = pointer to a ucode_path created by @{"TLUstart" link usta}


   RESULT
       dims   = 0 if TLUdims could not grab a glyph for that Unicode,
                or that Unicode was undefined. If dims is non-zero
                then it contains the following data about the glyph:


                     bit 0-7    width
                         8-15   ascender
                         16-23  descender
                         24-30  baseline
                         31     1         (returns $80000000 if glyph null)
                                          (some unicodes do not have glyphs)

   SEE ALSO
       @{"TLUgrabrport" link ugra}

@endnode

@node ustr  "[ustr]    Autodoc for TLUstring"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUstring@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

@{b}Note:@{ub}

I will soon re-write TLUstring to make it run much faster. It will also
have many more options (e.g. the ability to add diacritics to characters).


   NAME
       TLUstring -- Render a string of glyphs to a rastport


   SYNOPSIS
       dims = TLUstring(xpos, ypos, wbox, wint, flags, fpen,  bpen,
       D0               D0    D1    D2    D3    D4     D5     D6

                            cspace, upath, rport, string, eos)
                            D7,     A0     A1     A2      A3

       UWORD TLUstring(WORD, WORD, APTR, APTR, ULONG, UBYTE UBYTE,
                               UBYTE, APTR, APTR, APTR, APTR)


   FUNCTION
       Renders a string of glyphs to a rastport. If rport is attached to a
       window, then it is the caller's responsibility to set IDCMP verifies
       if appropriate.

       n.b. The glyphs are simply naively rendered left to right, even if
       they are meant to be diacritical marks or RTL characters. TLUstring
       is a quick and easy way to display a string of glyphs, but for true
       Unicode rendering, see @{"TLUpreview" link upre}.

       xpos, ypos, wbox and wint refer to ucode.library's rendering system.
       See @{"Window Boxes" link wint} for a full explanation.

       ucode.library pokes the string onto its own little rastport (i.e.
       ucode_rport), and then uses graphics.library's ClipBlit to blit from
       the ucode_rport to rport. This is how ucode.library does all its
       rendering.

       rport must have a bitmap attached to it (of course).

       It is possible that everything will work ok, but no output will
       appear on the rastport - that can occur if no Unicode in the string
       had glyphs (e.g. 007F has no glyph), or the xpos,ypos and wbox were
       so positioned that the string was clipped entirely off the wint.


   INPUTS
       xpos   = the signed x offset from the wbox of the leftmost character

       ypos   = the signed y offset from the wbox. The ypos is measured from
                the top of the maximum ascender of the glyph, so if you
                render several glyphs, their baselines will line up.


       wbox   = a pointer to a structure consisting of 4 words, i.e.
                   a signed word, the xpos of the wbox relative to the wint
                   a signed word, the ypos of the wbox relative to the wint
                   a non-zero unsigned word, the width of the wbox
                   a non-zero unsigned word, the height of the wbox
                if wbox is null, or its width is zero, then wbox will be
                0,0,10000,10000.

       wint   = a pointer to a structure consisting of 4 words, i.e.
                   an unsigned word, being the xpos of the rport interior
                   an unsigned word, being the ypos of the rport interior
                   a non-zero unsigned word, being the rport interior height
                   a non-zero unsigned word, being the rport interior width
                if wint is null, or its width is zero, then ucode.library
                will assume 0,0,width,height where width and height are
                the dimensions of the rastport's bitmap.

       flags  = the following flags can be set

                bits 0-7  the fixed width, if non-zero

                     15   preview if set. Quickly returns with the result in
                          D0, but no rendering takes place. Used for
                          previewing a string's dimensions before printing.

                     31   ASCII if set, else UTF16. If ASCII, then the
                          @{"TLUcharset" link ucha} is operative.

                     30   (ignored unless bit 31 is set). If set, HTML4-type
                          &....; things are recognised, e.g. &ldquo; in the
                          string would cause a left double quote to be
                          printed. To print an ampersand, you'd need to
                          embed &amp;

                     29   UTF8 if set, else UTF16.

                     28   Normally, if an underscore appears in the text,
                          it is not treated as a spacing character, but
                          the character before it is underscored. If you
                          set bit 28, then that feature is disabled, and
                          underscores are treated as spacing characters.

                     27   Normally, rendering takes place until a null
                          is encountered. But if flag bit 27 is set, then
                          rendering takes place until a null is encountered,
                          or address eos is reached, whichever comes first.
                          (Normally, eos would be the result returned by
                          @{"TLUbreak" link ubre}).


       fpen   = the foreground pen

       bpen   = the background pen

       cspace = the inter-character space in pixels

       upath  = pointer to a ucode_path created by @{"TLUstart" link usta}

       rport  = a RastPort (which must have a bitmap atached)

       string = pointer to the string to be rendered

       eos    = pointer to the end of the string to be rendered
                (ignored unless flag bit 27 is set)


   RESULT
       dims   = the following data about the string

                     bit 0-15   the string box width
                         15-23  string box ascender
                         24-31  string box descender

                After TLUstring returns, if dims was 0, you can call
                @{"TLUerror" link uerr} to see if there was an error,
                and if so, what.


   SEE ALSO
       @{"TLUdims" link udim} {"TLgrabrport" link ugra}

@endnode

@node ubre  "[ubre]    Autodoc for TLUbreak"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUbreak@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

   NAME
       TLUbreak -- suggest a break point for TLUstring

   SYNOPSIS
       break = TLUbreak(width, flags, cspace, upath, string, eos
       D0               D0     D4     D7      A0     A2      A3

       APTR TLUbreak(UWORD, ULONG, UBYTE, APTR, APTR, APTR);


   FUNCTION
       quickly previews a string as it would be printed by @{"TLUstring" link ustr}. If
       the line is narrower than width, TLUbreak returns with D0 pointing
       past the last byte of the string. If the line is wider than width,
       TLUbreak returns with D0 pointing to a breakpoint set as per
       the Unicode line breaking algorithm (i.e. at a word boundary). If it
       is not possible to break at a word boundary, TLUbreak will break
       at the best alternative. If width is narrower than the width of
       the first character, D0 will point past that character (in that case,
       a call to @{"TLUstring" link ustr} would trim the rhs of the character).

       After TLUbreak returns, you would presumably call @{"TLUstring" link ustr}, with
       flag bit 27 set, string the same as for TLUbreak, and eos set to the
       result from TLUbreak. You would then re-call TLUbreak with string
       being the result from the last call, and so on until the string is
       exhausted.


   INPUTS
       width  = width of the line in pixels
       flags  = as per glags of @{"TLUstring" link ustr}, bit 15 ignored
       cspace = inter-character space
       upath  = pointer to a ucode_path returned by a call to @{"TLUstart" link usta}
       string = a string suitable for input to @{"TLUstring" link ustr}
       eos    = (ignored unless flags bit 27 is set). An address to delimit
                the string. If flags bit 27 is set, then string finishes at
                eos or a null, whichever comes first


   RESULT
       break  = the address of the proposed breakpoint

   SEE ALSO
       @{"TLUstring" link ustr}

@endnode

@node ustw  "[ustw]    Autodoc for TLUsetwarper"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUsetwarper@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

   NAME
       TLUsetwarper -- Set attributes of the ucode_warper


   SYNOPSIS
       TLUsetwarper(height1, width1, weight1, height2, width2,
                    D0       D1      D3       D4       D5

                                 weight2 upath)
                                 D6      A0

       VOID TLUsetwarper(UWORD, UBYTE, UBYTE, UWORD, UBYTE, UBYTE, APTR);


   FUNCTION
       height1, width1 and weight1 are parameters you are about to use for
       a call to @{"TLUset" link ustt}. TLUsetwarper will set the attributes of the
       ucode_warper such that glyphs supplied by the ucode_path will, after
       warping, be as close as possible to the glyphs as they would have
       been if you used height2, width2 and weight2 as attributes for @{"TLUset" link ustt}.

       After you call TLUsetwarper, you must immediately call @{"TLUset" link ustt}
       with D0, D1 and D3 the same as for TLUsetwarper, and presumably with
       the xxp_lwarp flag set.


   INPUTS
       height1 = the glyph height to be @{"TLUset" link ustt}
       width1  = the glyph width to be TLUset
       weight1 = the glyph weight to be TLUset
       height2 = the height to which ucode_warper is to change glyphs
       width2  = the width to which ucode_warper is to change glyphs
       weight2 = the weight to whihc ucode_warper is to change glyphs
       upath  = pointer to a ucode_path created by @{"TLUstart" link usta}


   RESULT
       none


   SEE ALSO
       @{"TLUset" link ustt} @{"TLUfindpath" link ufnd}

@endnode

@node uerr  "[uerr]    Autodoc for TLUerror"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUerror@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   NAME
       TLUerror -- Find out why a ucode.library routine failed


   SYNOPSIS
       ernum = TLUerror(upath)
       D0               A0

       ULONG TLUError(APTR);


   FUNCTION
       Returns a code, being the error that occurred (if any) the last time
       upath was used to call a ucode.library routine. However, if there
       is no ucode_path, then TLUerror returns the reason (if any) why
       @{"TLUstart" link usta} failed the last a call to ucode.library's TLUstart failed.


   INPUTS
       upath  = pointer to a ucode_path created by @{"TLUstart" link usta}, or 0 if
                TLUstart has failed and tere is no ucode_path.


   RESULT
       ernum  = 0 if there was no error, or else a code. Here are the
                possible codes.


  1 @{"TLUstart" link usta} failed - library version s/be >= 37
  2                   can't open graphics.library
  3                   can't open intuition.library
  4                   out of memory
  5 out of memory
  6 @{"TLUsavelist" link upoi} failed - can't open U0000/List for writing
  7                   can't write to U0000/List
  8 @{"TLUmakefont" link umaf} failed - bad filename
 10                   can't open FONTS:name/size for writing
 11                   can't write to FONTS:name/size
 12                   can't create dir FONT:name
 13                   can't open diskfont.library
 14                   NewFontContents failed
 15                   can't open FONTS:name.font for writing
 16                   can't write FONTS:names.font
 17                   can't lock FONTS:
 18 can't open a glyph file for reading
 19 can't read a glyph file / glyph file kaput
 20 can't open U0000/List for reading
 21 can't read U0000/List or U0000/List kaput
 22 @{"TLUsaveprev" link usav} failed - bad write
 23 @{"TLUloadprev" link uloa} failed - bad read
 24                    - ucode_preview too small to hold file
 25                    - bad file contents
 26 @{"TLUcopy" link ucop} failed - bad write
 27 @{"TLUpreview" link upre} + @{"xxp_xut16" link "upre"116} - malformed UT16 chunk
 28 @{"TLUpreview" link upre} + @{"xxp_xut16" link "upre"116}/xfile - bad read
 29 @{"TLUcharset" link ucha} failed - unrecognised code
 30                   - can't open map file
 31                   - can't read map file
 32                   - map file had invalid contents
100 (not an error) file saved by @{"TLUsave" link upoi} newly created - call FixFonts

@endnode

@node umaf  "[umaf]    Autodoc for TLUmakefont"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUmakefont@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   NAME
       TLUmakefont -- Make an Amiga font from a selection of glyphs


   SYNOPSIS
       result = TLUmakefont(flist, fname, upath)
       D0                   A0     A1     A2

       BOOL TLUmakefont(APTR, APTR, APTR);


   FUNCTION
       flist is a list of 256 words, being the unicodes mapped to the "ASCII"
       values 00 - FF. The first 32 words will be ignored. Any null words,
       or words whose glyphs cannot be loaded, will result in a zero width
       glyph at that point.


   INPUTS
       flist  = pointer to a list of 256 words, of which the first 32 is
                ignores.

       fname  = a pointer to a null delimited font name with .font
                appended, e.g. 'myname.font',0

       upath  = pointer to a ucode_path created by @{"TLUstart" link usta}

   BUGS
       I propose to amend this routine so that it will not ignore non-zero
       unicodes in positions corresponding to 01-1F or 7F-9F.

   RESULT
       result = success (boolean). If TLUmakefont fails, call @{"TLUerror" link uerr} to
                find out why.

@endnode

@node uclo  "[uclo]    Autodoc for TLUclone"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUclone@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   NAME
       TLUclone -- Clone a ucode_path


   SYNOPSIS
       clone = TLUclone(upath)
       D0               A0

       UWORD TLUclone(APTR);


   FUNCTION
       Almost all calls to ucode.library require a ucode_path to be supplied.
       Once you have made a ucode_path by calling @{"TLUstart" link usta}, you can then
       call TLUclone to make clones of the original ucode_path. Each
       clone takes hardly any memory of its own, and no chip memory at all.
       This happens, because the clones share nearly all of their internal
       structures - the only thing they don't share, is their ucode_block
       structure.

       Clones are linked together in a chain. Every ucode_path structure
       has its xxp_base field pointing to the base member of the chain, and
       each clone, starting from the base, has its xxp_clon field pointing
       to the next clone in the chain, until the last member has its
       xxp_clon field set to null. If you called TLUclone, using any member
       of the chain as upath, then the last member of the chain becomes
       the second last, and its xxp_clon will point to the new clone, and
       TLUclone will return with D0 the number of the clone just made. If you
       call @{"TLUpop" link upop}, then the last member of the chain will be released, and
       the second last member becomes the last. If there is only one member
       of the chain - i.e. the base ucode_ path has its xxp_clon field null,
       then @{"TLUpop" link upop} has no effect. Only @{"TLUfinish" link ufin} can release the base
       member of the chain. If there are clones when you call @{"TLUfinish" link ufin},
       then it will release not only the base ucode_path, but any clones of
       it that happen to exist.

       Any call to ucode.library - even @{"TLUfinish" link ufin} - can use any clone for
       its upath input.

       As I already said, the clones do not share their embedded ucode_block
       structures. That is one of the uses of clones - if you put a whole
       lot of glyphs in memory (using @{"TLUset" link ustt}), but you want to remove them
       from memory, then you can use a clone to put them into memory. You
       can then @{"TLUpop" link upop} the clone when you want to remove the glyphs from
       memory.

       Another use of clones is in @{"TLUformat" link ufor} calls, because
       you can switch from clone to clone when building a preview, for
       example having one clone for @{"TLUset" link ustt} normal text, and another TLUset
       for italic text, or text of another size, or whatever.

       Can tasks share a ucode_path? Yes, but there must not be two tasks
       making simultaneous use of a ucode_path or a ucode_preview. So, you
       would have to arrange permissions among the tasks sharing a ucode_path
       so that no two of them were making a call using the ucode_path (or
       any of its clones) at the same time. Ditto if you want tasks to
       share a ucode_preview.


   INPUTS
       upath  = pointer to a ucode_path created by @{"TLUstart" link usta}


   RESULT
       clone  = 0 if the call failed (out of memory).
                If TLUclone returns 1+, then it is the number by which the
                clone is to be known, being its number along the chain,
                counting the base ucode_path as 0

   SEE ALSO
       @{"TLUpop" link upop} @{"TLUstart" link usta} @{"TLUfinish" link ufin}
       @{"TLUset" link ustt} @{"TLUpreview" link upre}

@endnode

@node upop  "[upop]    Autodoc for TLUpop"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUpop@{ub}

   NAME
       TLUpop -- Remove the last clone (if any) of a ucode_path


   SYNOPSIS
       TLUpop(upath)
              A0

       VOID TLUpop(APTR)


   FUNCTION
       Removes the last clone in the chain; the upath used to call TLUpop
       can be any member of the chain.

       See @{"TLUclone" link uclo} for more about TLUpop.

       Can you pop any other clone than the end of the chain? Yes - here is
       how. The clones are linked together, starting from the base
       ucode_path, via their xxp_clon fields. And each member of the chain
       has its xxp_base field pointing to the base ucode_path. What you must
       do, is re-arrange the links, to remove the clone to be popped to the
       end of the chain, and then call TLUpop. But the base member must
       remain the base member.


   INPUTS
       upath  = pointer to a ucode_path created by @{"TLUstart" link usta} (can be a clone,
                and can be the clone to be popped)


   RESULT
       none


   SEE ALSO
       @{"TLUclone" link uclo} @{"TLUstart" link usta} @{"TLUfinish" link ufin}

@endnode

@node umak  "[umak]    Autodoc for TLUmake"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUmake@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   NAME
       TLUmake -- Make a ucode.library programming object


   SYNOPSIS
       thing = TLUmake(what, param upath)
       D0              D0    D1    A0

       APTR TLUmake(ULONG, ULONG, APTR);


   FUNCTION
       The only purpose of TLUmake (from the programmer's point of view) is
       to make a ucode_preview. Before you can call @{"TLUpreview" link upre}, you must
       have a ucode_preview to supply to it.

       What size do you make the ucode_preview? In general, about 200,000
       bytes would be suitable. In general, you should have a maximum of
       (say) 3000 character boxes in a ucode_preview. 200,000 bytes would
       generally be more than enough for that.

       If you use TLUmake to create a ucode_preview, it will not be released
       until you release the upath supplied to make it by calling @{"TLUfinish" link ufin}.
       But if you wast to make a temporary ucode_preview which you can
       release without calling @{"TLUfinish" link ufin}, it is permitted to make
       a ucode_preview "by hand" like this, assuming D0 holds the required
       memory size, and you wish to save the ucode_preview's address in
       upreview:

          MOVE.L    _AbsExecBase,A6
          MOVEQ     #MEMF_PUBLIC,D1
          MOVE.L    D0,-(A7)
          JSR       _LVOAllocVec(A6)
          MOVE.L    D0,A0
          MOVE.L    (A7)+,D0
          MOVE.L    A0,upreview
          BEQ       bad
          MOVE.L    D0,xxp_prvl(A0)
          MOVE.W    #xxp_uver,xxp_libv(A0)

       You can then use upreview for @{"TLUpreview" link upre} &c calls. Finally you would
       need to release it like this:

          MOVE.L    _AbsExecBase,A6
          MOVE.L    upreview,A1
          JSR       _LVOFreeVec(A6)


   INPUTS
       what  = #ucode_path to make a ucode_preview
               i.e.   MOVEQ    #ucode_preview,D0

               Remember, programs calling ucode.library must have the lines
                     INCLUDE "UCODE:includes/ucode.i"
                     INCLUDE "UCODE:includes/ucodeasms.i"


       param = memory size of the object

       upath = pointer to a ucode_preview created by @{"TLUstart" link usta}


   RESULT
       thing = pointer to the object created, or 0 if bad (i.e. out of
               memory)

@endnode

@node upre  "[upre]    Autodoc for TLUpreview"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUpreview@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

   NAME
       TLUpreview -- fill a ucode_preview with character boxes


   SYNOPSIS
       result = TLUpreview(utags, utext, uprev, upath)
       D0                  A0     D0     D1     D2

       BOOL TLUpreview(APTR, APTR, APTR, APTR)


   FUNCTION
       The process of rendering Unicode to a rastport works like this:

       @{b}The ucode_path specifies the size and style of glyph...@{ub}
       @{"TLUstart" link usta} makes a ucode_path
       @{"TLUset  " link ustt} sets the attributes of a ucode_path

       @{b}The ucode_preview contains the character boxes and rendering data@{ub}
       @{"TLUmake " link umak} makes a ucode_preview@{ub}
       TLUpreview  takes Unicode, and makes it into character boxes@{ub}

       @{b}The character boxes are sorted into lines and printed@{ub}
       @{"TLUformat" link ufor} sorts a ucode_preview into lines
       @{"TLUprint" link upri} prints lines from a ucode_preview to a rastport

       Or, to put it another way, printing is a four stage process:

           @{"TLUset    " link ustt}  -> choose size and style of characters
           TLUpreview   -> makes character boxes
           @{"TLUformat " link ufor}  -> makes character boxes lines
           @{"TLUprint  " link upri}  -> prints line boxes

       However, the above process is not just a "linear" process. @{"TLUset" link ustt} and
       TLUpreview may be called several alternating times as a series of
       Unicode inputs are made into a ucode_preview. @{"TLUformat" link ufor} and @{"TLUprint" link upri}
       calls can also be interleaved into this process.

       The text on the rastport can also be seen as a "living" thing - an
       object - and so even after @{"TLUprint" link upri} is called, you will see below
       the @{"TLUmove" link umov} routine for re-drawing it as it is scrolled or resized,
       and @{"TLUhilight" link uhil} and other routines for cutting and pasting.


       @{b}Here is an explanation of all TLUpreview's tags....@{ub}


       @{b}xxp_xappe@{ub} -- (append) -- append to existing boxes

       xxp_xappe can have a value of T or F (-1 or 0)
       By default, xxp_xappe = F

       If xxp_xappe = F, then the character boxes TLUpreview makes will be
       the only character boxes in the uocde_preview. When you first use
       @{"TLUmake" link umak} to make a ucode_preview, it will just be an empty box, so
       the first time you supply it to a TLUpreview call, you *MUST* have
       xxp_xappe = F. But, from then on, you can call with xxp_xappe = F to
       restart with an empty box, or you can call with xxp_xappe = T to
       append the new boxes to whatever boxes are already there.

       If xxp_appe = F, and TLUpreview returns in error, then the next
       TLUpreview call using that ucode_preview *MUST* set xxp_appe = F.

       If xxp_appe = T, and TLUpreview returns in error, then the boxes
       will be exactly as they were before calling TLUpreview. However
       the TLUpreview will not be formatted, and you will have to call
       @{"TLUformat" link ufor} (perhaps after other TLUpreview calls) before
       attempting to call @{"TLUprint" link upri}.


       @{b}xxp_xfrmt@{ub} -- (format) -- input text format

       xxp_xfrmt can be  +1 = UTF16   -1 = UTF8   0 = ASCII
       By default, xxp_xfrmt = 0 = ASCII

       UTF8 and UTF16 are Unicode-friendly text formats, explained in the
       @{"Unicode Book" link "unic"}, or online at www.unicode.org

       In some future utopian age, all plaintext will be in UTF8 or UTF16
       format, which all Unicode-aware applications can understand and use
       with maximum efficiency. But in practice, plaintext hardly ever
       occurs in UTF8 or UTF16, but rather in ASCII. So, that is the default
       input that TLUpreview expects.

       Now ASCII can only specify values of 00 - 7F, but Unicode values
       can be 0000 - FFFF, plus extensions. So there are extant a large
       number of forms of dirty ASCII to somehow extend ASCII's range.

       You will see below the @{"TLUcharset" link ucha} command, which sets
       the way that the TLUpreview routine is to understand input text when
       it is in ASCII. When xxp_xfrmt is UTF16 or UTF8, then @{"TLUcharset" link ucha} has
       no effect.


       @{b}xxp_xfile@{ub} -- (file) -- get input from a file

       xxp_xfile can be 0, or = a file handle (BPTR)
       by default, xxp_xfile = 0

       By default, TLUpreview gets input text from memory, and TLUpreview is
       called with D0 pointing to the text.

       But it may be more conventient for the caller to open a file, and
       pass its file handle to TLUpreview via an xxp_xfile tag. In that case,
       TLUpreview will ignore the input D0, and read input text from the
       file until the file is exhausted, or TLUpreview stops reading text
       for some other reason, depending on the operative tags.

       n.b. after TLUpreview finishes with the xxp_xfile handle, it does
       NOT close the file.


       @{b}xxp_xut16@{ub} -- (UT16 chunk) -- get input from a UT16 chunk

       xxp_xut16 can be 0, or = a file handle (BPTR)
       by default, xxp_xut16 = 0

       If xxp_xut16 is set ~= 0, then the TLUpreview ignore the D0 when it
       was called.

       Under the @{"TLUcopy" link ucop} command below, you will see
       my method of cutting and pasting of Unicode plaintext. The process
       of pasting is accomplished by the xxp_xut16 tag.

       Here's how it works. The caller must open the IFF file, which if
       copied would be presumably be in CLIPS: somewhere. If would then
       process its chunks. If it finds a UT16 chunk, it would call
       xxp_preview with xxp_xut16 = the file handle.

       The caller must also use dos.library's Seek routine to position the
       file such that the first 4 bytes that TLUpreview reads will be the
       chunk header, i.e. 'UT16'. Otherwise, TLUpreview will return in
       error.

       Regardless of how little or how much of the UTF16 chunk TLUpreview
       actually uses (depending on other tags), TLUpreview does NOT close
       the file, but always positions it immediately after the end of the
       entire UT16 chunk.

       If xxp_ut16 ~= 0, then this overrides various other tag values, i.e.

          xxp_xfrmt = +1 = force UTF16 (obviously)
          xxp_xbidt =  0 = force LTR   (standard for UT16 chunks)
          xxp_xmirq =  F = do not mirror mirroring characters


       @{b}xxp_xclon@{ub} - (clone) - clone for normal text
       @{b}xxp_xemph@{ub} - (emphasised) - clone for "bold" text
       @{b}xxp_xtilt@{ub} - (tilted) - clone for "italic" text
       @{b}xxp_xboit@{ub} - (bolditalic) - clone for "bold"+"italic" text

       xxp_xclon/emph/tilt/boit can be set to -1, or a clone number
       the default for all of these is -1

       If xxp_xclon = -1, then the input D2 (upath) will be used for
       getting glyphs. But if not, then the value of 0+ will refer to the
       clone number (as returned by @{"TLUclone" link uclo}, or 0 if the base ucode_path)
       used for grabbing normal characters

       If xxp_xemph = -1, then if TLUpreview wants a "bold" glyph, it will
       get a normal one, and algorithmically embolden it. But if not, then
       the value of 0+ will refer to the clone number (as returned by
       @{"TLUclone" link uclo}, or 0 if the base ucode_path) used for grabbing "bold"
       characters.

       If xxp_xtilt = -1, then if TLUpreview wants an "italic" glyph, it
       will get a normal one, and algorithmically tilt it. But if not, then
       the value 0+ will refer to the clone number (as returned by @{"TLUclone" link uclo},
       or 0 if the base ucode_path) used for grabbing "italic" characters.

       If xxp_xboit = -1, then if TLUpreview wants a "bold"+"italic" glyph,
       it will (a) if xxp_xtilt ~= -1, get an "italic" one, and
       algorithmically embolden it. (b) if xxp_xtilt = -1 and xxp_xemph ~=-1
       it will get a bold one amd algorithmically tilt it. (c) If both
       xxp_xtilt = -1 and xxp_xemph = -1, it will get a normal glyph and
       algorithmically tilt and embolden it. But, if xxp_xboit ~= -1, then
       the value 0+ will refer to the clone number (as returned by @{"TLUclone" link uclo},
       or 0 if the base ucode_path) used for grabbing "bold"+"italic"
       characters.
                                     _oOo_

       To understand the above, you need to see that each clone of a
       ucode_path can be @{"TLUset" link ustt} differently, and TLUpreview can use them
       variously. They can even be set to different heights - TLUpreview
       will align their baselines ok. You will see below under @{"xxp_xescs" link "upre"362}
       that you can switch clones from character to character if you want.
       And, of course, you can make successive calls to TLUpreview with
       different clones in D2 each time, or with calls to @{"TLUset" link ustt} between
       calls to TLUpreview (slower than using clones if lots of switching).


       @{b}xxp_xbidt@{ub} - (bidi = bidirectionality) - bidi override
       @{b}xxp_xbibf@{ub} - (bidi brought forward)

       xxp_xbidt can be 0 = force LTR, +1 = force RTL, -1 = Unicode bidi
       default xxp_xbidt = -1

       xxp_xbibf can be 0+ = Unicode bidi N1 brought forward, or -1 = ignore
       default xxp_xbibf = -1

       Unicode has an exceedingly complex set of rules for determining
       bidirectionality (e.g. English reads LTR, Hebrew reads RTL). You
       can override Unicode bidi by specifying xxp_bidt = 0 or +1. If you
       specify xxp_bidt = -1, then TLUpreview will apply Unicode bidi. I
       spent a lot of time making this work properly - and you would think
       that the Unicode book's accompanying disk or www.unicode.org would
       give some test files but they don't, so I'm not absolutely sure I've
       gotten it right. Also, I implemented version 2.1, and then version
       3.1 came out which is even more vomitously kludgy. But I'm settling
       for the 2.1 version. And now, the unicode consortium have deprecated
       the use of 202A-202E anyway - the bastards - so no one will use
       them anyway. But even without 202A-202E it is still very complex.

       When TLUpreview returns, it puts the value of the Unicode bidi N1
       variable in the xxp_bicf field of the ucode_path you supplied in
       D2 (upath), so if you call TLUpreview again with xxp_appe = T, and
       the text in that call is to be displayed contiguously with that in
       the first call, and both have xxp_xbidi = -1, then you should read
       the xxp_bicf from the first call, and supply it as the xxp_bibf of
       the second call. xxp_bibf only applies if xxp_bidt = -1.

       For more on directionality, see also @{"TLUcopy" link ucop}.

       Note that if the @{"xxp_xut16" link "upre"116} <> 0, then xxp_bidt
       is always forced to be 0.


       @{b}xxp_mirq@{ub} - (mirror quotes) - 00AB-00BB/2018-201F if RTL

       xxp_mirq can be F (don't mirror), or T (do mirror).
       default T

       The treatment of quotes is very muddled in the Unicode book. Version
       2.1 was totally obscure, as admitted by version 3.1, which more or
       less says do what you like(?). So, I thought the best thing is to
       supply a tag (i.e do what you like).

       Now, under Unicode bidi, quotes take the directionality of the thing
       quoting, not the quote. If that directionality is LTR, there is no
       problem. But, if the directionality is RTL, then there are three
       possibilities

         - the supplier of the text provides them as if the quoted text was
           LTR, and they are to be mirrored.

         - the supplier of the text provides them already mirrored

         - the supplier doesn't know the Unicode bidi rule, and supplies
           them mirrored for an LTR quoter, but an RTL quote.

       But that's not the end of it, as the the Unicode book shows that
       there are many ways of using the quote characters in different LTR
       languages.

       Anyway, if you set xxp_mirq = F, TLUpreview leaves your quotes alone,
       but if you set xxp_mirq = T (which is the default since it is the
       usual situation), TLUpreview does its best to come up with something
       sensible.

       If your program starts with <Q> and </Q> tags, then your program can
       call the shots, so I suggest it sends quotes exactly as it wants them,
       and sets xxp_mirq = F.

       Note that if @{"xxp_xut16" link "upre"116} <> 0, then it forces
       xxp_xmirq to be F.


       @{b}xxp_xfixx@{ub} - (fixed width) - force fixed width character boxes

       xxp_xfixx can be 0, or 1-32 = pixels, or 33+ = reference character
       default 0

       If xxp_xfixx is 0, then character boxes ar their normal widths. If
       xxp_xfixx is 1 to 32, then character boxes will be that width in
       pixels. If xxp_xfixx is 33+, then character boxes will be the width
       of the glyph whose Unicode is that value.

       If a character box is too wide to fit the xxp_xfixx value, then
       TLUpreview chops it off at the right. If it is narrower, the old
       box is at the left of the new box. If it has a right "joiner" (Arabic
       and Indic characters), the joiner is extended.

       The effect of setting xxp_xfixx on characters that are natually fixed
       (e.g. 2500-257F) to a different width may not be pleasing. I may
       eventually work out some sort of system for these characters, like
       my system for extending the joiners of Arabic and Indic characters.
       2500-257F would also need vertical alignment and joining (messy).


       @{b}xxp_xsmal@{ub} - (small) - small capitals

       xxp_xsmal can be T or F
       default F

       If xxp_xsmal is F, A-Z appear normally. If T, then TLUpreview gets
       special small caps glyphs from dummy glyphs at illegal unicode
       positions DC0A-DC23. You can use @{"TLUset" link ustt} with flist to replace these
       with other glyphs if you wish.

       Under @{"xxp_xescs" link "upre"362} you will see that you can switch small
       caps on and off dynamically.


       @{b}xxp_xoldn@{ub} - (old number) - old-style numbers

       xxp_xoldn can be T or F
       default F

       If xxp_xsmal is F, 0-9 appear normally. If T, then TLUpreview gets
       special old-style numerals (which make numbers in text look better)
       from dummy glyphs at illegal unicode positions DC00-DC09. You can
       use @{"TLUset" link ustt} with flist to replace these with other glyphs if you wish.

       Under @{"xxp_xescs" link "upre"362} you will see that you can switch old style
       number on and off dynamically.


       @{b}xxp_xalli@{ub} - (all Italic) - force Italic

       xxp_xalli can be T or F
       default F

       If xxp_alli is F, characters appear normally. It T, then all
       characters are Italic (see also @{"xxp_xtilt" link "upre"150}).

       Under @{"xxp_xescs" link "upre"362} you will see that you can
       switch Italic on and off dynamically.


       @{b}xxp_xallb@{ub} - (all bold) - force bold

       xxp_xallb can be T or F
       default F

       If xxp_allb is F, characters appear normally. It T, then all
       characters are bold (see also @{"xxp_xemph" link "upre"150}).

       Under @{"xxp_xescs" link "upre"362} you will see that you can
       switch bold on and off dynamically.


       @{b}xxp_xdcom@{ub} - (decompose) - decompose composite characters

       xxp_xdcom can be T or F
       default T

       If xxp_xdcom is F, then all characters will get their glyphs from
       those positions in the file.

       Now many characters are composites of a plain character a a dicritic
       mark, e.g.

          A acute = A    + acute
          00C1      0041   0301

       Composite characters generally look better if you set xxp_xdcom = T.
       In that case, TLUpreview, if it gets 00C1, will act as if it had got
       0041 0301. 0041 0301 looks better, but is perhaps less compact. Also,
       decomposing is slightly slower than TLUpreviewing undecomposed.


       @{b}xxp_xescs@{ub} - (escapes) - Escapes / Tags / Whitespace

       xxp_xescs can have value 0, plus 0 or more of these bits set:

                 bit 0   1 = process some embedded Escs        default 0
                 bit 1   1 = process &...; as if in HTML4
                             and stop if < found               default 0
                 bit 2   1 = (if bit 1 set) process some <..>  default 0
                 bit 3   1 = remove white space                default 0

       TLUpreview will skip any embedded Amiga Esc sequences it finds, no
       matter what value xxp_xescs has. But, if xxp_xescs has bit 0 set,
       then it will also act upon certain of those Esc sequences. See
       @{"Esc Sequences" link "tags"129} for details.


       TLUpreview will normally print 0026 as an ampersand if it finds it.
       But, if xxp_xescs has bit 1 set, then & will be treated as if it
       were found in a HTML4 page. e.g. &beta; will be printed as if it
       were 03B1.

       TLUpreview will normally print 003C as a "<" character. But, if
       xxp_xescs has bit 0 set to 1, it will stop if it encounters a 003C.

       If xxp_xescs bit 1 is set, and xxp_xescs bit 2 is also set, then
       TLUpreview will normally stop if if finds a 003C (i.e. a "<"). But,
       in just a few cases, it will actual process the "<" and what
       follows as a HTML tag. See @{"HTML Tags" link "tags"212} for details.

       TLUpreview will normally make boxes for all white spaces it finds,
       with widths but no scanlines, which will cause @{"TLUprint" link upri} to leave
       white space as required. But, if xxp_xescs bas bit 3 set to 1, then
       all sequences of 1 or more white space character will be replaced
       by a single white space character. This is normally 0020, but see
       xxp_xfpre below.



       @{b}xxp_xfpre@{ub} - (for <PRE>) - white space removal

       xxp_xfpre can be -1, or a Unicode value
       default -1

       If @{"xxp_xescs" link "upre"362} has bit 3 set to 0, then xxp_xfpre is always
       ignored.

       But if it is 1, and xxp_xfpre is -1, then xxp_xfpre is still ignored,
       and sequences of 1 or more white spaces are replaced by a single
       0020.

       If xxp_xescs (above) has bit 3 set to 1, and xxp_xfpre is 0, then
       sequences of 1 or more white spaces are replaced by nothing. If
       xxp_xfpre is >0, they are replaced by the Unicode value of xxp_xfpre.


       @{b}Termination Conditions@{ub}

       TLUpreview always stops if it encounrters a null unicode.
       It also stops if the ucode_preview runs out of memory.
       It also stops if xxp_xfile ~= 0, and the file is exhausted.
       It also stops if xxp_xut16 ~= 0, and the UT16 chunk is exhausted.

       It will also stop if any of these termination condition tags are T,
       and the condition is satisfied. All are set F by default.


       @{b}xxp_xwspc@{ub} stop if any white space except 0020 fount
       @{b}xxp_xspcc@{ub} stop if 0020 found
       @{b}xxp_xshyq@{ub} stop if SHY found
       @{b}xxp_xanyq@{ub} stop if anything exc a Unicode with a glyph found
       @{b}xxp_xeolq@{ub} stop if 000A, 000D or 2028 found
       @{b}xxp_xeopq@{ub} stop if 000C, 000F or 2029 found
       @{b}xxp_xtabq@{ub} stop if 0009 found

       It will also stop if

       @{b}xxp_xboxl@{ub} > 0 (default 0), and the number of boxes in
                            the ucode_preview is >= that number.


       @{b}xxp_xaddr@{ub}

       This is also a termination condition. Its default value is 0. It it
       is >0, then:

       - it will stop if xxp_xfile and xxp_xut16 are both 0, and TLUpreview
         has read that many bytes from memory.

       - otherwise, it will stop if it has read that many bytes from file.


   INPUTS
       utags = pointer to the tags

       utext = pointer to the input text
               (ignoreod if tags xxp_xtext ~= 0 or tag xxp_xut16 ~= 0)

       uprev = pointer to a ucode_preview made by @{"TLUmake" link umak}

       upath = pointer to a ucode_preview made by @{"TLUstart" link usta}


   RESULT
       result = 0 or -1 (boolean)
                If bad, call @{"TLUerror" link uerr} to find out why


   SEE ALSO
       @{"TLUmake" link umak} @{"TLUset" link ustt} @{"TLUformat" link ufor} @{"TLUprint" link upri}

@endnode

@node ucha  "[ucha]    Autodoc for TLUcharset"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUcharset@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   NAME
       TLUcharset -- Select a charset for TLUpreview...ASCII calls


   SYNOPSIS
       result = TLUcharset(code, upath)
       D0                  D0    A0

       BOOL TLUcharset(UWORD, APTR)


   FUNCTION
       code can be 0, which simply sets the charset to the default, i.e.
       Latin-1. Else, various other charsets will apply, according to the
       list below.

       TLUcharset sets the charset attribute to the ucode_path. When
       @{"TLUpreview" link upre} asks ucode_path for a glyph, and is getting characters in
       UTF16 or UTF8, then charset has no effect. But if TLUpreview is
       getting characters in "ASCII", then charset if operative.

       There is a set of diskfiles at path UCODE:Maps which contain data
       for various charset schemes. When you call TLUcharset, ucode.library
       checks whether the ucode_path you specify already has that file in
       a memory buffer, and if so, makes it the charset attribute of the
       ucode_path. But if it is not in memory, it loads the file into
       memory and makes it the attribute. Some charset codes require several
       files.

       All charset files held in memory by any clone of a ucode_path are
       available to be set to all other clones. But different clones may be
       set to different charsets. Once a charset file is loaded, it stays in
       memory until @{"TLUfinish" link ufin} releases the ucode_path and its clones.

       These are the charsets currently available:

        2 ISO-8859-2      41 GB2312        72 CP1250
        3 ISO-8859-3      42 GB2312_EUC    73 CP1251
        4 ISO-8859-4      44 JIS0212       74 CP1252
        5 ISO-8859-5      45 JIS0212_EUC   75 CP1253
        6 ISO-8859-6      47 KSX1003       76 CP1254
        7 ISO-8859-7      48 Johab         77 CP1255
        8 ISO-8859-8      49 KSX1001       78 CP1256
        9 ISO-8859-9      50 KSX1001_EUC   79 CP1257
       10 ISO-8859-10     54 CP1026        80 CP1258
       11 ISO-8859-11     55 CP500         81 CP874
       13 ISO-8859-13     56 CP875         83 CP932
       14 ISO-8859-14     57 CP437         87 CP936
       15 ISO-8859-15     58 CP737         89 CP949
       22 KOI8-R          59 CP775         91 CP950
       23 ISCII-1         60 CP850         92 CP1006
       24 ISCII-2         61 CP852         93 CP424
       25 ISCII-3         62 CP855         94 CP856
       26 ISCII-4         63 CP857
       27 ISCII-5         64 CP860
       28 ISCII-6         65 CP861
       29 ISCII-7         66 CP862
       30 ISCII-8         67 CP863
       31 ISCII-9         68 CP865
       34 Shift-JIS       69 CP865
       38 GB12345         70 CP866
       39 GB12345_EUC     71 CP869

       Caution: not all of these may work properly in this preliminary
       release.

   INPUTS
       code  = 0 for Latin-1, or code from the above table

       upath = pointer to a ucode_preview made by @{"TLUstart" link usta}

   RESULT
       result = 0 / -1 (boolean)


   SEE ALSO
       @{"TLUset" link ustt} @{"TLUpreview" link upre}

@endnode

@node ufor  "[ufor]     Autodoc for TLUformat"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUformat@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   NAME
       TLUformat -- arrange a ucode_preview into character boxes


   SYNOPSIS
       result = TLUformat(width, wspace, cspace, flags, tabs, line0, uprev)
       D0                 D0     D1      D2      D3     D4    D5     A0

       BOOL TLUformat(UWORD UBYTE UBYTE ULONG APTR UWORD APTR)


   FUNCTION
       TLUformat MUST NOT be called for a ucode_preview, until @{"TLUpreview" link upre}
       has been successfully called for that ucode_preview.

       TLUformat MUST NOT be called with line0 <> 0 if TLUpreview has been
       called since the last call to TLUformat.

       Once one or more @{"TLUpreview" link upre} calls have put character boxes into a
       ucode_preview, call TLUformat in order to sort the character boxes
       into lines. The ucode_preview can then be used for calls to @{"TLUprint" link upri}.

       When you specify line0 = 0 (which you must do for the first call to
       TLUformat), then the boxes are sorted such that the line boxes fit
       width. Lines are sorted such that lines are broken at a white space,
       or at a SHY. But if no white space or SHY occurs before width is
       exceeded, then the line will be broken elsewhere. If the first
       character box is too wide for the width, it will be put on the line,
       and then @{"TLUprint" link upri} will truncate it.

       Character boxes are placed in lines according to their bidirectional
       properties which are set by @{"TLUpreview" link upre}. By default, line with base
       level LTR are left justified, and lines with base level RTL are
       right justified. This is not always what you want, especially if
       lines of different base directionality are interepersed. So, you
       can use flags to specify the treatment of line justification.

       To use TLUformat properly, you may need to call it first with
       line0 = 0 and inputs approprite to that line. You may then want to
       "walk though" the lines, and re-call TLUformat with progressively
       increasing line0's, setting properties appropriate for each block
       of lines. If you examine the ucode/ucode.i file, you will find that
       information about lines is to be found in xxp_lind structures. You
       can "walk through" from xxp_lin0 to xxp_linf, and in xxp_linp you
       will find the first box of each line, and that box's xxp_pvtx
       you will find 2 words, the first being the call of TLUformat (0+)
       when the box was created, and the offset from the start of of the
       input text (0+) that was the source for the character box.


       These are the bits you can set in "flags":

       bit 0-7  max pixels added to space width if full justify
                (0 if no limit)
       bit 8    set to full justify all lines not followed by blank lines
       bit 9    set to full justify all lines
       bit 10   set to right justify all lines
       bit 11   set to centre all lines

       bit 12   set to forbid line breaks at SHYs (00AD = SHY = soft hyphen)

       bit 16   set to strike though all lines    } These can be used
       bit 17   set to double underline all lines } in combination
       bit 18   set to double overline all lines  }
       bit 19   set to single underline all lines }
       bit 20   set to single overline all lines  }

       bit 24   set for vertical packing (not yet fully implemented)

       bit 25   if a line is full justified, and the first &/or last
                character box is tilted, then by default the line is
                justified in the assumption that the bits of the line
                boxes (if any) that lap the baseline will go into the
                margins. If you don't want that, set bit 25.


       You might want to put the character boxes into several sets of lines
       with different lengths. There are two basic reasons for doing this:


       1. The characters fall naturally into different blocks to be printed
          into different areas. In that case:

          (a) Call @{"TLUpreview" link upre} with the first block and tag xxp_xappe = F.
              Then, re-call TLUpreview for each block, and xxp_xappe = T.
          Be sure to put an LF at the end of each block.

          (b) Call TLUformat with width set to suit the first block. Then,
              walk though the xxp_linds in the ucode_preview, getting the
          xxp_linp of the 1st word of xxp_pvtx, and re-calling TLUformat
          with line0 set to the first line of each block.


       2. The characters all belong in the same block, but you want to flow
          them into various boxes - e.g. to flow around a picture. Then:

          (a) Call @{"TLUpreview" link upre} for the whole block, with xxp_appe = F.

          (b) Call TLUformat with width set for the first block. Then,
              walk through the xxp_linds in the ucode_preview, seeing how
          many fit into the first display block. Then, call TLUformat
          with line0 set to the first line of the second block, and width
          set to the width of the second block. Continue until all the lines
          are flowed into the boxes.


       Note that if you call @{"TLUpreview" link upre} for a ucode_preview, then all
       TLUformat information is lost in that ucode_preview, and you must
       call TLUformat with line0 set to 0 before you can call @{"TLUprint" link upri}.


   INPUTS
       width  = maximum width of line boxes

       wspace = word spacing, i.e. width in pixels of 0020 and 00A0 chrs

       cspace = character spacing in pixels
                TLUformat adds character space after all non-blank characters
                except those at the end of lines. If a non-blank character
                is <= in width to "n" (006E), then it will not have a
                character space put before or after it, else it will.

       flags  = flags as above.

       tabs   = null delimited list of words with ascending values, being
                the tab positions where 0009 characters jump to. The default
                tab values are 64,128,192.... In LTR lines, tabs jump
                right, while in RTL they jump left.

       line0  = 0, to start re-formatting lines from the beginning. Else,
                start re-formatting lines from line0.

       uprev  = pointer to a ucode_preview made by @{"TLUmake" link umak}


   OUTPUT
       success = 0 / -1 (boolean). (failure = out of memory)


   SEE ALSO
       @{"TLUpreview" link upre} @{"TLUprint" link upri}

@endnode

@node upri  "[upri]    Autodoc for TLUprint"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUprint@{ub}

   NAME
       TLUprint -- Print next line of a ucode_preview


   SYNOPSIS
       height = TLUprint(xpos, ypos, wbox, wint, jam, fpen, bpen, data,
       D0                D0    D1    D2    D3    D4   D5    D6    D7

                                  upath, rport, uprev)
                                  A0     A1     A2

       UWORD TLUprint(WORD, WORD, APTR, APTR, UBYTE, UBYTE, UBYTE, ULONG,

                                  APTR, APTR, APTR)


   FUNCTION
       TLUprint prints one line from a ucode_preview.

       @{"TLUformat" link ufor} points the ucode_preview's xxp_linc to the xxp_lin0, i.e.
       the first xxp_lind to be printed. (You can poke the address of any
       other xxp_lind into xxp_linc, if you want to print lines in another
       order. Remember that all addresses in a ucode_preview are relative
       to the start of the ucode_preview).

       Each time you call TLUprint, xxp_linc advances a line. Bit if
       xxp_linc >= xxp_linf, then nothing gets printed, and xxp_linc remains
       unchanged.

       If jam = 2, then the line box will have bpen for a background, else
       only fpen will be used, and the text will be superimposed on whatever
       was there before.

       The data input, if non-zero, is a pointer to 16 bytes of underline/
       overline/strike thru data as follows:

       byte 0           caller use
            1-5   pens     +0thru 1dubl_und 2dubl_ov 3sngl_und 4sngl_ov
            6-14  patterns +0     2         4        6         8

       the visible portion of the line (which will be truncated if it
       exceeds the ucode_path's width as specified when @{"TLUstart" link usta} made it)
       is pre-drawn in the ucode_path's ucode_rport, and then the line is
       draw to the rastport by calling graphics.libeary's ClipBlit. Thus,
       even if the caller has neglected to lock the window with IDCMP
       verifies, the worst that can happen is for the window's borders to
       be over-written.

       The result of TLprint is the height of the character box just written.
       This is never less than the ascender of "M" (004D) + the descender of
       "g" (0066). This can be a guide for the ypos of the next line. The
       ucode_preview has other information that may be helpful in vertical
       line placement:

            The ascender and descender of the next line to be printed are in
            the xxp_lind's xxp_pwla and xxp_pwld.

            The width of the next line to be printed is in the xxp_lind's
            xxp_pwlw (it is usual to have half the normal line spacing
            after zero width (i.e. blank) lines.

            The ucode_preview's main section has pwhl, the height of the
            highest line.

            (ucode_prev's xxp_pack is as yet inoperative).


   INPUTS
       xpos  = xpos of the top left of the line box, relative to the
               wbox (can be -ve)

       ypos  = ypos of the top left of the line box, relative to the
               wbox (can be -ve)

       wbox  = pointer to the window box  } (see @{"Window Boxes" link wint})
       wint  = pointer to window interior }

       jam   = 1/2

       fpen  = foreground pen

       bpen  = background pen

       data  = 0 / pointer to underline data as above

       upath = pointer to a ucode_preview made by @{"TLUstart" link usta}

       rport = rastport to be drawn to

       uprev  = pointer to a ucode_preview made by @{"TLUmake" link umak}


   OUTPUT
       height = height of character box just printed (see above)


   SEE ALSO
       @{"TLUpreview" link upre} @{"TLUprint" link upri}

@endnode

@node usav  "[usav]    Autodoc for TLUsaveprev"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUsaveprev@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

   NAME
       TLUsaveprev -- save the contents of a ucode_preview


   SYNOPSIS
       success = TLUsaveprev(uprev, handle, upath)
       D0                    D0     D1      A0

       BOOL TLUsaveprev(APTR, BPTR, APTR)


   FUNCTION
       TLUsaveprev saves the contents of a ucode_preview, after TLUpreview
       has been called for it.

       Even if @{"TLUformat" link ufor} has been called, TLUsaveprev does not save line
       format data (xxp_linds). You can re-load what you have saved with
       a call to @{"TLUloadprev" link uloa}.


   INPUTS
       uprev  = a ucode_preview for which @{"TLUpreview" link upre} has been called

       handle = the handle of a file which had been opened for writing.

       upath = pointer to a ucode_preview made by @{"TLUstart" link usta}


   RESULT
       success = -1 / 0 (boolean). After you call TLUsaveprev, the caller must
       close the file. If TLUsaveprev failed, the file will still exist,
       but will probably be of size zero.


   SEE ALSO
       @{"TLUloadpreview" link uloa}

@endnode

@node uloa  "[uloa]    Autodoc for TLUloadprev"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUloadprev@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

   NAME
       TLUloadprev -- load a file which saved by a call to @{"TLUsaveprev" link usav}


   SYNOPSIS
       success = TLUloadprev(uprev, handle, upath)
       D0                    D0     D1      A0

       BOOL TLUloadprev(APTR, BPTR, APTR)


   FUNCTION
       TLUloadprev loads a file saved by a previous call to @{"TLUsaveprev" link usav}
       (which need not have been saved by the caller) to a ucode_preview
       structure. TLUloadprev will not succeed if the ucode_prev is too
       small to hold the file contents.

       After the call to TLUloadprev, the ucode_preview will be in the same
       state as it would be if @{"TLUpreview" link upre} had been called. That is to say,
       that the caller can must call @{"TLUformat" link ufor} with line0 = 0, before
       calling @{"TLUprint" link upri}.

       Note that the program loading the fie need not have access to any
       of the glyph files which the saving program had access to. @{"TLUformat" link ufor}
       and @{"TLUprint" link upri} make no use of any glyph files. Thus, the files made
       by calls to @{"TLUsaveprev" link usav} can be used to transfer data between
       computers and applications, without worrying about what glyph files
       or fonts the receiving application might have access to.


   INPUTS
       uprev  = a ucode_preview for which @{"TLUpreview" link upre} has been called

       handle = the handle of a file which had been opened for reading.

       upath = pointer to a ucode_preview made by @{"TLUstart" link usta}


   RESULT
       success = -1 / 0 (boolean). If TLUloadprev fails, the caller can call
       @{"TLUerror" link uerr} to find out why.


   SEE ALSO
       @{"TLUsaveprev" link usav}
@endnode

@node umov  "[umov]    Autodoc for TLUmove"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUmove@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   NAME
       TLUmove -- Re-draw / Re-size / scroll what TLUprint has printed


   SYNOPSIS
       TLUmove(upath, rport, uprev, cback, parm0, parm1, parm2, parm3)
               A0     A1     A2     A3     D0     D1     D2     D3

       VOID TLUmove(APTR, APTR, APTR, APTR, UBYTE, UWORD, UWORD, APTR);


   FUNCTION
       You cannot call TLUmove for a ucode_preview, unless it has had
       @{"TLUformat" link ufor} called for it. If it has not had @{"TLUprint" link upri} called for it,
       or no lines have been drawn on the rport you supply, then nothing
       will happen.

       When @{"TLUprint" link upri} uses a ucode_preview to draw a line, the ucode_preview
       remembers which rastport and where on the rastport each of its lines
       was drawn to. With this data, TLUmove can re-draw lines if the
       window needs de-drawing, or if the window is resized, or if the
       window or one of its wboxs is to be scrolled.

       TLUmove also has a call-back system, so that whenever a line box
       or wbox or wint is drawn to, a the caller can specify an address to
       call first (e.g. to insert non-text visual elements on the window).

       In the next release I will also have a system for specifying a list
       of things to be drawn (pictues, lines, areas &c) which can be
       supplied as an alternative or supplement to the call-back.

       There are 5 jobs that TLUmove can do, i.e.:

       job0  re-draw all lines on a rastport

       job1  re-draw a rastport, allowing for a changed wint (i.e. a window
                     is resized)

       job2  re-draw a rastport if the whole wint is scrolled (so all its
                     wboxs move)

       job3  re-draw a wbox within a rastport if the wbox is to be scrolled

       job4  same as job0, but within a range of lines

       TLUmove uses graphics.library's ScrollRaster along with ClipBlit to
       do its rendering. job0 and job4 draws everything, but job1, job2 and
       job3 only draw what they have to draw.

       Using TLUmove is quicker and more reliable than using Amiga's
       refresh system. Just like any other rendering operation, you should
       surround TLUmove with setting and unsetting IDCMP verifies to lock
       the window.

       I recommend that if you get an IDCMP refreshwindow (for a smart
       refresh), you set IDCMP verifies, then call BeginRefresh and then
       EndRefresh, call TLUmove, and then release the IDCMP verfies. This is
       because if the user fiddles with the window gadgets while Amiga's
       refreshing is taking place, the system can lock up, but this does not
       happen if you use TLUmove.

       If @{"TLUhilight" link uhil} is in operation, then hilighted character boxes are
       rendererd hilighted by TLUmove.

       It doesn't matter if you have called @{"TLUset" link ustt} since you drew the lines
       on the window, TLUmove will still work. You can supply a different
       clone to TLUmove from the one used to draw the lines, TLUmove will
       still work.


   INPUTS
       job0  D0 = parm1 = 0 = redraw all lines on rport
             D1 = parm2 = ignored
             D2 = parm3 = ignored
             D3 = parm4 = ignored

       job1  D0 = parm1 = 1 = rport's wint has changed (window resized)
             D1 = parm2 = ignored
             D2 = parm3 = ignored
             D3 = parm4 = pointer to new wint (if same as old nothing happens)

       job2  D0 = parm1 = 2 = scroll rport
             D1 = parm2 = horz movement, +ve leftwards -ve rightwards
             D2 = parm3 = vert movement, +ve upwards   -ve downwards
             D3 = parm4 = ignored

       job3  D0 = parm1 = 3 = scroll a wbox
             D1 = parm2 = horz movement, +ve leftwards -ve rightwards
             D2 = parm3 = vert movement, +ve upwards   -ve downwards
             D3 = parm4 = pointer to new wbox

       job4  D0 = parm1 = 4 = same as job0, but for a range of lines
             D1 = parm2 = first in range
             D2 = parm3 = last in range
             D3 = parm4 = ignored

       upath = a ucode_path made by a call to @{"TLUstart" link usta}

       uprev = a ucode_preview made by @{"TLUmake" link umak}, for which @{"TLUformat" link ufor} MUST
               have been called

       rport = the rastport to be re-drawn to or refreshed

       cback = the call back address
               0 if none
               As of ucode.library version 1, cback must always be 0, as
               cback is not yet fully operative.

   RESULT
       none


   SEE ALSO
       @{"TLUformat" link ufor} @{"TLUprint" link upri} @{"TLUhilight" link uhil}

@endnode

@node uhil  "[uhil]    Autodoc for TLUhilight
@{b}ucode.library/TLUhilight@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

   NAME
       TLUhilight -- hilight a range of character boxes


   SYNOPSIS
       TLUhilight(line1, box1, line2, box2, upath, uprev)
                  D0     D1    D2     D3    A0     A1


       VOID TLUhilight(WORD, UWORD, UWORD, UWORD, APTR, APTR)


   FUNCTION
       The ucode_prev you supply for TLUhilight must have had @{"TLUformat" link ufor}
       called for it.

       ucode_prev has a component called xxp_hili which specifies a range
       of character boxes to be hilighted. This would normally be used for

       1. a cursor (when just one baox is hilighted)
       2. to show which boxes are chosen when cutting and pasting

       You should not poke values directly into xxp_hili, but rather call
       TLUhilight to so. If you call TLUhilight when xxp_hili is already
       set, then any previously hilighted boxes which become un-hilighted
       will be unhilighted first, before any previoiusly un-hilighted boxes
       are hilighted.

       The range of boxes hilighted can extend across move than one wbox -
       it can even extend across rastports (though that might be visually
       confusing).

       Where boxes are printed RTL, or a mixture of RTL and LTR, nevertheless
       hilighting takes on boxes numbered from left to right, as they appear
       on the rastport, regardless of what order they were supplied to
       @{"TLUpreview" link upre}.

       If you suppply line1/box1 -> line2/box2 numbers out of order, then
       TLUhilight will swap them as required to make them legal. If you
       have a box number too high, it will be corrected to the first box of
       the next line. If you supply a line number too high, it will
       be corrected to the last box of the last line.

       The input line and box numbers are numbered from 0+


   INPUTS
       line1 = the line holding the first box hilighted, or, if you set
               line1 = -1, then all hilighting will be turned off, and
               box1, line2 and box2 will be ignored.

       box1  = the box number within line1 of the first box hilighted

       line2 = the line holding the last box hilighted

       box2  = the box number within line2 of the last box hilighted

       upath = a ucode_path created by @{"TLUstart" link usta}

       uprev = a ucode_preview created by @{"TLUmake" link umak}
               uprev MUST have had @{"TLUformat" link ufor} called for it


   SEE ALSO
       @{"TLUformat" link ufor} @{"TLUprint" link upri} @{"TLUmove" link umov} @{"TLUcopy" link ucop}

@endnode

@node ucop  "[ucop]    Autodoc for TLUcopy"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUcopy@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

   NAME
       TLUcopy -- Copy TLUhilighted boxes to a file


   SYNOPSIS
       result = TLUcopy(upath, uprev, handle)
       D0               A0     A1     D0

       BOOL TLUcopy(APTR, APTR, BPTR)


   FUNCTION
       @{"TLUformat" link ufor} must have been called for the uprev supplied to TLUcopy.

       TLUcopy takes the boxes hilighted in the ucode_prevew (see @{"TLUhilight" link uhil})
       and saves them to a file.

       The handle supplied must be to a file which is opened for writing,
       and so far empty. TLUcopy will make it into an IFF file, with
       a UT16 chunk to hold the Unicode of the character boxes in UTF16
       form.

       The UT16 chunk is like a CHAR chunk, excpet that it contains words
       (or in the case of surrogates pairs of words).

       There is no IFF chunk I know of for saving Unicode, so I made one up.
       I don't know how to register a new chunk - can someone tell me?

       TLUcopy writes the IFF file to handle, but does not close the file.
       If TLUcopy fails, the file will still exist, but will proably be
       empty. If you call TLUcopy for a ucode_preview which has no boxes
       hilighted, the UT16 chunk will be valid, but have no words of unicode
       in it.

       A file created by TLUcopy can be read ("pasted") by calling
       @{"TLUpreview" link upre} with @{"xxp_xut16" link "upre"115} ~= 0.


   INPUTS
       upath = a ucode_path created by @{"TLUstart" link usta}

       uprev = a ucode_preview made by @{"TLUmake" link umak}

       handle = an empty file opened for writing


   SEE ALSO
       @{"TLUpreview" link upre} @{"TLUhilight" link uhil}

@endnode

@node upac  "[upac]    Autodoc for TLUpact"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUpact@{ub}    (primitive routine)
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

   NAME
       TLUpact -- change a nominal height to an actual hieght


   SYNOPSIS
       actual = TLUpact(nominal)
       D0               D0

       UBYTE TLUpact(UBYTE)


   FUNCTION
       TLUpact changes D0 from a nominal to an actual height. e.g. nominal
       height 11 is actual height 14.


   INPUTS
       nominal = a nominal height (5 to 31)


   OUTPUT
       actual = the corresponding actual height


   SEE ALSO
       @{"TLUpnom" link upno} @{"TLUpbas" link upba}

@endnode

@node upno  "[upno]    Autodoc for TLUpnom"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUpnom@{ub}    (primitive routine)
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

   NAME
       TLUpnom -- change an actual height to a nominal height


   SYNOPSIS
       moninal = TLUpnom(actual)
       D0                D0

       UBYTE TLUpnom(UBYTE)


   FUNCTION
       TLUpnom changes D0 from an actual to a nominal height. e.g. actual
       height 14 is nominal height 11.


   INPUTS
       actual = a valid actual height
                 If you put an invalid actual height, i.e. an actual
                 height for which there is no nominal height, the result
                 will be -1.


   OUTPUT
       nominal = the corresponding nominal height


   SEE ALSO
       @{"TLUpact" link upac} @{"TLUpbas" link upba}

@endnode

@node upba  "[upba]    Autodoc for TLUpbas"
@{b}ucode.library/TLUpbas@{ub}    (primitive routine)
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

   NAME
       TLUpbas -- change a nominal height to an baseline


   SYNOPSIS
       baseline = TLUpbas(nominal)
       D0                 D0

       UBYTE TLUpbas(UBYTE)


   FUNCTION
       TLUpbas changes D0 from a nominal height to the baseline (ascender)
       of glyphs of that height. e.g. glyphs of nominal height 11 have a
       baseline (ascender) of 11 (hence, a descender of act ht 14 - 11 = 3).


   INPUTS
       nominal = a nominal height (5 to 31)


   OUTPUT
       baseline = the corresponding baseline


   SEE ALSO
       @{"TLUpnom" link upno} @{"TLUpact" link upac}

@endnode

@node upoi  "[upoi]  Autodoc for Other Primitive Routines"
@{b}Other Primitive Routines@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

ucode.library has the following further primitve routines:

   TLUpoint -- look up an internal data table
   TLUgrab  -- grab a glyph into a ucode_path's ucode_glyph
   TLUtransfer -- copy a glyph form a ucode_path's Ucode_glyph to ucode_rport
   TLUwarp  -- use a ucode_path's ucode_warper on its ucode_glyph
   TLUsave  -- the the contents of a ucode_path's ucode_group
   TLUsavelist -- make a file list (called by the UcodeFix program)

These routines could perhaps be useful for specialised applications.
ucode.library is an open source program, so you can look up these routines
in the source code, where their use is documented.

@endnode

@node how4 "[how4]    C Language Stubs@{ub}

@{b}C language Stubs@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

  Sorry - I haven't done C language stubs for ucode.library yet.

@endnode
